<HEAD>Administration Wants to Sell F-18 Fighter-Bombers to Kuwait</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration intends to sell advanced F-18 fighter-bombers to <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, a deal that would make the tiny <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> state the first <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> country to have them, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday. Citing unidentified sources in the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> and State departments, the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> wants to buy 40 of the aircraft and the administration will notify <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> soon of its intention to proceed with the sale. The deal could be worth $ 680 million to the manufacturer, <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said company spokesman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>. Several <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials contacted by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday night said they were unaware that any decision had been made. One noted that Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> had told a congessional panel Tuesday that `` there was a request from <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> to look at the possibility of selling F-18s.'' Another source, who also spoke on condition that he not be named, said, `` I'm not aware that any decision is imminent.'' `` There's no more than the possibility of a sale,'' he said, adding that he was skeptical that such a decision would have been made so quickly. `` I would doubt it very seriously,'' he said. `` There's interest, but a lot of discussion needs to go on before any decision like that would be considered I think it's awful early. I would be very surprised if it's true.'' The source noted that <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> has talked to several countries, including <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, about the possibility of buying advanced aircraft. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> had told the congressional panel Tuesday that the administration had alerted <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> was interested in the F-18s and might prefer them to the less sophisticated F-16s. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> could block the sale. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is selling F-16s to <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION>, but it has n't sold F-18s to any Arab nation, the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> have created an increasingly close security relationship since last year, when the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> committed naval forces to protect U.S.-flagged ships traveling through the war-torn <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. Initially, 11 Kuwaiti ships were re-flagged under this policy and were given protection by the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> recently revised its policy in the gulf, announcing that it would offer help to other ships that were attacked by combatants in the 7 -LCB- - year-old Iran-Iraq war
