<HEAD>Church Universal and Triumphant: A Threat in Paradise Valley?</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE DENNISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CORWIN SPRINGS, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here in a mile-high valley called Paradise, a religious group is building its home, a retreat for thousands that some local people say threatens the pristine environment bordering Yellowstone National Park. The group is the <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Triumphant </ORGANIZATION>, a `` New Age'' sect that moved its headquarters in late 1986 from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to a 12,000-acre ranch it had bought five years earlier in southwest <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Paradise </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. With that move came 200 followers, doubling the number already there, construction plans for a self-sufficient community, and the promise of more church members moving into a valley with a population of about 1,000. Next door is <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>, whose wildlife herds often migrate into the valley during the winter. `` This is a place of international significance,'' says <PERSON> Hank </PERSON> <PERSON> Rate </PERSON>, a local resident. `` If they do what they say they want to do, that value is going to be diminished _ not only for our time, but for all time.'' Rate and others fear the group's building plans and its summer conclaves that attract thousands will cause environmental damage in the valley. Some critics say they're uncomfortable with the group's beliefs. The church was founded 30 years ago in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, by <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Prophet </PERSON>, who said he received messages from spiritual figures of the past, including <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>, <PERSON> Buddha </PERSON> and Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> XXIII </PERSON>. Upon his death in 1973, his widow, <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Clare </PERSON> <PERSON> Prophet </PERSON>, became the leader. Church members believe a human soul is continuously reincarnated until people realize the God within themselves. They use praying or chanting to attempt to influence world conditions or personal concerns. Tobacco, alcohol and drugs are forbidden. Ms. <PERSON> Prophet </PERSON>, 47, says her visions suggest a war between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> before the end of this century. The church supports President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s Strategic Defense Initiative and a nationwide civil defense system. `` We have a lot of down-home, nice type of folks on this ranch who are just like the people that are our neighbors,'' Ms. <PERSON> Prophet </PERSON> says. `` I do n't think that all the hullaballoo that's been made in the press is the reality here.'' Critics draw comparisons between <LOCATION> Paradise </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and the tiny town of <LOCATION> Antelope </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, taken over in the early 1980s and then abandoned by followers of the Baghwan <PERSON> Shree </PERSON> <PERSON> Rajneesh </PERSON>. Church Universal and Triumphant bought some modular housing from the defunct Rajneeshee community, but church leaders say the similarities end there. Since the church bought the ranch in 1981, its leaders have hit the local Rotary and <ORGANIZATION> Kiwanis </ORGANIZATION> club circuit to calm fears that it is a far-out religious cult bent on political control. Church vice president <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Francis </PERSON>, married to Ms. <PERSON> Prophet </PERSON>, says church members' political persuasion generally resembles that of the area _ conservative and Republican. Not everyone is reassured. `` I'm concerned about the numbers,'' says <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sargent </PERSON>, whose 2,000-acre property borders the church's <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ranch </ORGANIZATION>. `` No matter what they happen to believe, it's still an awful lot of people to bring into a fragile area.'' Church officials counter that they chose the valley because of its natural beauty, which they want to preserve. The church bought the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ranch </ORGANIZATION> in 1981 from magazine publisher <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> Forbes </PERSON> for a reported $ 7 million. Since then, the church has purchased an additional 21,500 acres in the <LOCATION> Paradise </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, including 5,200 acres of hilly prairie near Emigrant intended for settlement by church members, about 25 miles north of the <LOCATION> Royal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Teton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ranch </LOCATION>. It also owns a printing shop in <LOCATION> Livingston </LOCATION> that employs 100 people. The church wo n't reveal its income but says it comes from members' donations and various business ventures, largely the sale of religious books and videotapes. It also leases land to members. The church has advertised the ranch to its members as a spiritual retreat offering protection from economic collapse, civil disorder or war. Thousands of followers gather each summer for an annual conclave in a spectacular mountain valley called the `` Heart of the Inner Retreat.'' Ms. <PERSON> Prophet </PERSON> and <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> say the <LOCATION> Royal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Teton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ranch </LOCATION> will become a monastic, self-sufficient community for 500 or so church members. With the help of ranch `` staff'' _ church members who receive room, board and small monthly salaries _ the church has installed an extensive irrigation system, grows a wide variety of vegetables and grains, operates a dairy and raises 2,500 head of cattle and sheep. Members also began work in 1986 on the development's central complex. Located near the west bank of the <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> several miles north of <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, it would include housing for 260, a church, school, kitchen, dining hall and recreation facilities. But that work halted in November 1986 when the state, prodded by local residents, launched an environmental review. A draft of the review, completed in March, said the project should be able to proceed without damaging wildlife, water quality or aesthetics, as long as the church takes several steps to cushion impact of the development. The state found no threat to the environment that would justify denying sewage and water permits, if the conditions were met. Following a public comment period _ `` We were overwhelmed with comment, both for and against,'' said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Pilcher </PERSON>, chief of <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quality </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> _ the state is completing a final report. The draft said the church should build a bear-proof fence around a tree farm and vegetable fields, monitor groundwater, maintain minimum flows in three creeks crossing ranch property and postpone any use of a geothermal spring near the <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. The church wants to pump water from <LOCATION> LaDuke </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hot </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> for use at its central complex. Park officials are concerned the pumping might affect <LOCATION> Mammoth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hot </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> nine miles to the south. <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> says the church is willing to accept the recommendations, but a number of groups have suggested the state review is inadequate. Since the 1970s, the church has occupied and later abandoned land in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> _ `` a series of steps to get here,'' <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> says, adding that the church has no intention of moving again. But critics say the church has not been forthcoming about its plans in the past. `` Basically, <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Francis </PERSON>' credibility with me is zero,'' says <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Parks </PERSON>, owner of an outdoor equipment shop in nearby <PERSON> Gardiner </PERSON> and a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Creek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, a local environmental group. `` If he told me it was Thursday, I'd check the calendar.'' When Church Universal and Triumphant bought the ranch, <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> said its rural nature would not be changed. <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> maintains he has been largely consistent: `` I feel that a 1 percent use of property in this area for anything other than open space and wildlife is appropriate and not something that should cause a lot of alarm.'' Parks says the church `` changes the ambience of the whole area,'' bringing the impact of a development but no direct economic benefits. <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> contends that what's really bothering the critics is simpler: They just do n't want others to have a piece of their paradise.
