<SECOND>PM-Tunisia's New Era,0799</SECOND>
<HEAD>`New Era' In Tunisia As Pro-Western Bourguiba Slips Into Oblivion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Habib </PERSON> <PERSON> Bourguiba </PERSON>'s statue still dominates a square in central <LOCATION> Tunis </LOCATION>, but the man who towered over <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION> for 32 years has slipped into oblivion six months after his ouster. His successor as president, <PERSON> Zine </PERSON> <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Abidine </PERSON> <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>, has proclaimed a `` new era'' for the North African nation, appealing to the nation's Islamic and Arabic heritage, a stand that has won him immediate widespread support. <PERSON> Bourguiba </PERSON>, who had set the nation on a Western course after he won independence from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in 1956, now is 84 years old and confined to a chateau outside <LOCATION> Tunis </LOCATION>. He was declared no longer capable of governing when he was removed from office Nov. 7. <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> took power during a tense crackdown on Islamic fundamentalists and is universally credited, even by political opponents, with sparing the nation from a more serious upheaval. He has sought to make peace with the Islamic fundamentalists and others in the Bourguiba opposition. Newspapers once banned by <PERSON> Bourguiba </PERSON> are back on newsstands. Many people say they no longer fear the police. <ORGANIZATION> Tunis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, disrupted three days a week last year by demonstrations, is quiet. About 5,000 prisoners, many of them members of an outlawed Islamic fundamentalist group, have been pardoned. The national legislature, dominated by <PERSON> Bourguiba </PERSON>'s ruling party since <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION>'s independence in 1956, has moved toward pluralism with a new law on political parties. In his most risky move, however, <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> has extended a hand to the growing Islamic fundamentalist movement, <PERSON> Bourguiba </PERSON>'s chief target in his waning years. Television and radio now broadcast the five daily calls to Islamic prayer. Islam has alway been the official state religion, but <PERSON> Bourguiba </PERSON> maintained a secular character in government and daily life. <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>, a military man once in charge of the crackdown on fundamentalists, invokes Allah -LRB- God -RRB- at the start of his speeches. `` It's life that's changed, not just politics,'' said <PERSON> Chakib </PERSON> <PERSON> Douss </PERSON>, a brassware merchant in the <LOCATION> Tunis </LOCATION> bazaar. `` Now everyone is free. We feel it every day, every minute. It's not something you read about in the newspaper. It's something you touch.'' Many in the opposition approved of the new climate, if only for now. `` Incontestably, Nov. 7 was a comfort to everyone,'' said a leading member of the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, the largest opposition party, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` It's still the honeymoon, so everyone feels obliged to publicly approve him,'' commented <PERSON> M'hamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaibi </PERSON>, editor-in-chief of the weekly Maghreb, reopened in September after being shut down four years ago. `` I hope this is a temporary situation,'' he said of <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>'s popularity `` Otherwise, we'll be back in the old system with a president who thinks he is infallible.'' That was an allusion as well to <PERSON> Bourguiba </PERSON>, who had become so dominant that he was declared president-for-life, a benign dictator in charge of a nominal democracy. His Destourian <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> controlled all seats in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. None of the three legal opposition parties had a meaningful voice. But <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> has promised that his new era would `` open the horizons to a truly democratic and evolved political life.'' Since taking office, he has moved to abolish the lifelong presidency, change the electoral code and press laws, dismantle the feared state security court and given <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, the London-based human rights group, a permit to operate here _ its first in the Arab world. <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> has also restored diplomatic relations with neighboring <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> and stresses closer ties with the Arab world. While citizens appear won over by the changes, some opposition politicians remain cautious and fundamentalists are reserving full judgment. The final year of <PERSON> Bourguiba </PERSON>'s leadership was marked by a battle against the fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tendency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, culminating in a trial in September of 90 fundamentalists on charges of plotting against the state. `` The Islamic dossier remains the hottest one on <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>'s desk,'' said <PERSON> Hassen </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghodhbani </PERSON>, an Islamic lawyer who defended some of the 90 in the trial He contended the measures taken by <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> remain insufficient. `` Islam is n't just prayer and pilgrimage. It's an entire life system,'' he said. In late April, the legislature quashed any hopes that the <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tendency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> might become a legal opposition party _ one of its demands. A new law allowed new political parties but forbade those based on religion, language, race or region. `` The government has adopted a double attitude toward Islam,'' said the opposition politician who spoke anonymously. `` It is a position both clever and dangerous.''
