<HEAD>Argentina To Take Part In U.S. Naval Games</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> will take part in naval exercises with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for the first time since the 1982 Falklands War. <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alconada </PERSON> <PERSON> Sempe </PERSON>, secretary of foreign affairs, said on Tuesday that <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> will participate in `` Operation <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' with <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and several of the Latin countries that once took part in `` Operation Unitas.'' <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> quit the Unitas war games after the <LOCATION> Falklands </LOCATION> conflict to protest what it said was <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistance to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. The 74-day war over the islands <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> calls the Malvinas killed 712 Argentine and 256 British soldiers. Final details of the exercises next year are to be completed this week in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> while <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> commander Adm. <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Arosa </PERSON> is visiting <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Alconada </PERSON> <PERSON> Sempe </PERSON> said. Naval vessels from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> took part in the Unitas exercises.
</TEXT>
