<DOCNO> AP880511-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0748EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Dance     05-11 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dance,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agnes de Mille's `The Informer' Ballet Opens in NY</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` The Informer,'' a new ballet choreographed by <PERSON> Agnes </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mille </PERSON> for American Ballet Theater, is a gripping anti-war work certain to become a favorite of audiences for years to come. It's a strong ballet, crisp, clear and deeply felt, with light moments and ominous ones, danced against sets with glowering gray skies. Based on the 1935 movie about strife in <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> between 1916 and 1921, it is set to Celtic songs, and every wave of the hand, flip or sweep of a scarf and every jig-like jump is identifiably Irish. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> premiere Tuesday at the <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opera </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> was danced with muscular eloquence. <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbee </PERSON> danced the wounded veteran, <PERSON> Johan </PERSON> <PERSON> Renvall </PERSON> the young fighter and red-haired <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> the girl. A corps de ballet of 20, as Dubliners, danced superbly. Miss <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mille </PERSON> had <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffith </PERSON> as Irish step-dancing consultant. The choreographer used the timing of quick Irish dance steps, as well as the way feet turn and legs cross each other. The story is crystal clear, almost all of it in dance with very little relying on mime. The young fighter, whose steps are carefree, likes the girl _ and other girls. She likes him but when he leaves with somebody else she flirts with the veteran, who holds one gloved hand, presumably artificial, close to his waist. The veteran is self-conscious, has intense feeling for the girl _ he lifts her with one hand _ and is jealous. So he points out the young fighter to unseen English soldiers. Women mourn the young fighter, heads thrown back then down, mouths silently screaming. In one enormously effective scene, the veteran is alone as dawn comes, revealing silhouettes of men hanged by the English. The veteran tries to strut but is stiff, unable to free his body from his realization of what he did. In the next scene, the girl finds consolation dancing with the veteran. But he confesses to her and she runs in horror to her friends. They shun her at first but take her into their measured line dancing. When the veteran arrives, there is a long silence before two men walk him into the wings. At the end of the half-hour dance Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> Miss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mille </ORGANIZATION>, who suffered a stroke in 1975, walked on stage arm in arm with company artistic director <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Baryshnikov </PERSON>. The audience, which had watched the ballet in rapt silence, stood to applaud, and bravos rang out. `` The Informer'' was premiered in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> in March.
</TEXT>
