<SECOND>PM-Supersonic Transport,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Growth In Transpacific Travel Will Mean Boom In Supersonics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 By the end of the century there will be a need for a new civilian transport plane capable of carrying 247 passengers on 5,000-mile trips at two to three times the speed of sound, says a new study. That will open a $ 200 billion-plus market for the country which first manufactures the new generation of supersonic planes for civilian use in the years 2000 to 2010, said the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. The agency, however, recommended against building a production transport faster than three times the speed of sound, saying that would involve `` too great a price and with too great a delay in reaching operational service.'' At Mach 2.7, an airplane could fly from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> in under four hours. A body traveling at <ORGANIZATION> Mach </ORGANIZATION> 1 would be traveling at the speed of sound, and <ORGANIZATION> Mach </ORGANIZATION> 2 would equal twice the speed of sound. The study said growth in travel across the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> will justify designing and building a supersonic transport. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had such an effort under way in the 1960s, but abandoned it because of noise-pollution problems and the high cost of fuel. `` Many technologies are much more advanced today,'' the <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> study said. `` Weight reduction and aircraft shaping are the best methods of reducing the sonic boom heard at ground level. New design methods for shaping are just now becoming avialable.'' The aircraft eventually would fly twice as far as the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Concorde </ORGANIZATION>, which has a range of 3,350 miles. The new generation of airplanes would not be the `` Orient Express'' that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> envisioned in his State of the Union message two years ago when he announced research for a plane capable of flying 25 times the speed of sound and thus able to go into orbit. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> jointly are now carrying out research for such a hypersonic plane and a decision will be made in 1990 on whether to build it at a cost of $ 3.3 billion. `` <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> program managers believe research for the long-range commercial market should now focus on getting the highest speed possible out of a conventionally fueled, high-speed transport,'' the agency said. Two studies were performed for <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Langley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> by <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION>, the only <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> firms building large transports. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> studies indicate that, by the year 2000, a fleet of 1,200 large, subsonic aircraft would be needed to carry the estimated worldwide, long-range traffic of 315,000 passengers per day,'' <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> said. `` By comparison, less than 800 supersonic transports, each carrying 247 passengers as far as 5,000 nautical miles, could serve the same markets.'' Timeliness in providing a viable and competitive vehicle is important if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is to capture a major portion of the high-speed transport market, estimated to be over $ 200 billion, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> said. It added: `` This market could be an important factor in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sustaining a positive balance of trade in the aerospace market.'' The federal government would not be a financial partner in building an SST, but <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> said it has a clear charter to pursue the technologies and reduce the financial risk to aircraft builders. `` It then would be up to industry to build and sell the high-speed, civil transport on their own,'' the agency said.
</TEXT>
