<FIRST>r w PM-DeficitCommission     05-11 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deficit Commission,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Learns When A Spending Cut Is Not A Cut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The national panel created to solve the national budget problem is quickly learning that balancing the government's checkbook first means decoding some artful accounting. `` If we did this in business, they'd lock us up,'' said commission member <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> chairman, after the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday held its first public hearing on federal budget practices. Experts told the commission the history of the convoluted budget process and the scope of the deficit problem, which has already saddled taxpayers with paying back principal and interest on more than $ 2.5 trillion in debt. The tone among the commission members was often jocular in reaction to testimony about federal budgeting oddities. <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Muris </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mason </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor who until last year worked at the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>, described how a `` cut'' can really be an increase in spending. That's because budget writers work from projections of inflated program costs instead of current spending levels. `` I thought I was pretty good when I was in government, but I was a rank amateur,'' said <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lawyer <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON>, a Democrat who is co-chairman of the commission. `` Think of it as a 20 percent cut from a 50 percent markup,'' quipped <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION>. But former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Caspar </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> made clear he did n't think the concept was funny when it applied to <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spending. Cutting the military short of inflationary increases is `` a very real reduction,'' he said. `` There is nothing in the world situation which justifies that kind of cutback,'' he said, referring to recent budget restraints. `` That is a reality and it is a very unhappy reality for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> said the first task of the commission should be to streamline the budget process, but the witnesses did not agree. <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> co-chairman <PERSON> Drew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s former <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> secretary and currently the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION>, announced that the group intended to produce its recommendation by Dec. 21, more than two months ahead of its statutory deadline. The revised schedule would give the 12-member commission a great chance of influencing policies of the next president, who will get to appoint two more commission members after November's election. `` We are not looking at this as a partisan mission,'' said <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> a </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Responsible </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>, told the commission that reducing the deficit will be a difficult task and efforts so far have had mixed results. `` It seems like we're on a treadmill _ we're running to stay in place,'' she said. But Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, was optimistic. `` We're talking about a situation that's within our capacity to solve. <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> said the budget mechanisms have worked well when there's a consensus to be carried out. Presidents <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> both used it to achieve their initial legislative successes when they took office, she said. <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Collender </PERSON>, director of federal budget policy for the firm of <ORGANIZATION> Touche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ross </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said procedures could be improved but `` the budget process is not the problem.'' `` It will always be subservient to politics,'' he said.
