<FIRST>r w PM-ProductLiability     05-11 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Product Liability,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Product Liability Lawsuit Bill Clears First Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Legislation setting new ground rules for filing damage suits against manufacturers of hazardous products survived its initial test in a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee, but its chances of passing <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> this year are still considered minimal. Consumer activists suffered a setback Tuesday when the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> rejected two proposals by Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>, D-Calif., that would have expanded the product liability bill's narrow list of legal grounds available to victims seeking to recover damages Then, after four hours of bickering, the committee postponed until Thursday any further action on what Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Florio </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, called a `` complex and extremely controversial'' measure. The bill would establish a uniform federal standard of product liability that would pre-empt conflicting state laws. Consumer activists vigorously oppose the measure on the ground that it would weaken the legal rights of victims of unsafe consumer products. It was the first time that the House bill, first introduced in 1979, had advanced to the full committee. Even if it reaches the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor, which is uncertain, the bill is virtually assured of a hostile reception in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, where it was filibustered to death in late 1986. Two consumer groups called it `` a radical bill that would immunize the manufacturers of defective goods, deprive victims of compensation for their injuries and expose American consumers to more hazardous products.'' Business support for the bill has become increasingly lukewarm with each revision aimed at meeting consumer demands. `` This is a watered-down bill,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Lent </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, `` but it is better than none.'' Other committee Republicans said the bill represented an important step toward discouraging `` frivolous'' damage suits, reversing the escalating cost of liability insurance premiums and bolstering the competitiveness of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> products on world markets. The committee's first day of debate focused on a compromise plan, drafted by Rep. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Synar </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., at the request of Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., the panel's chairman, which was aimed at making the bill more acceptable to consumer groups and moderate committee Charging that `` we are about to emasculate the product liability system,'' <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON> tried unsuccessfully to restore some of the legal grounds for damage suits in the states that would be pre-empted by a uniform federal standard. <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> voted with opponents in defeating <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>'s pair of consumer-backed amendments by roll call votes of 29-12 and 30-12. Under the bill approved by <PERSON> Florio </PERSON>'s commerce subcommittee last December, a manufacturer could escape liability for damages if he did not know _ or could not know _ of a design defect with knowledge `` reasonably available'' to him, or if there were no feasible alternative design. This restriction would not apply if the consumer could establish that the product was egregiously unsafe, that an ordinary consumer would not know of the product's risks and if the product had little or no usefulness. The <PERSON> Synar </PERSON> plan would require only that the plaintiff prove that the product was so unsafe compared with its usefulness that it should not have been marketed. <PERSON> Synar </PERSON> also would put the burden of proof on the manufacturer to show that a design defect could not be discovered and that an alternative design was not feasible. Leaders of four consumer organizations complained to <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> on April 27 that <PERSON> Synar </PERSON>'s plan `` still falls far short of protecting the legal rights of individuals injured by unreasonably dangerous and defective products.'' Underscoring the bill's poor prospects, Rep. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Bates </PERSON>, D-Calif., drew laughter at one point in the debate by referring to <PERSON> Synar </PERSON>'s plan as `` a killer amendment to a bill that's already dead.
</TEXT>
