<HEAD>Bennett Describes Self as Education Department's Savior</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Education Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> says his department is now much less likely to be eliminated, and that he deserves the credit. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>'s boast came Tuesday during a typically contentious appearance before a congressional committee, replete with the taunts and tantrums that have marked almost every Capitol Hill exchange between lawmakers and the education secretary. One day after <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> announced plans to step down in mid-September, Sen. <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON> accused him of having shirked his responsibilities to poor and handicapped students aided by federal programs. `` In the course of your tenure, you have chosen to go ahead and ravage these programs,'' said <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Conn </LOCATION>., referring to budget cuts sought on a nearly annual basis by the department `` Why did n't you concentrate on what was your responsibility?'' <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON> asked. `` I have difficulty understanding your preoccupation with everybody else's business. ... I find it incredible that nothing has been achieved in your specific charges.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> defended his interest in state and local education efforts during what he termed probably his final appearance before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Appropriations subcommittee on education and other agencies. `` The best federal program is the program that's deployed well at the local level,'' he sid. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> came into office pledging to dissolve the <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> conceded under questioning that he still does not see a real need for it, other than to spark debate. What, asked an irritated <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON>, would you think of teachers who see no real need for their jobs? `` They should n't be in a classroom,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> replied. `` Well, you should n't be in the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON> snapped. `` What kind of commitment does that show?'' `` I made a hell of a commitment. You just did n't like the direction,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> retorted. `` I was damn successful. You're mad at me because we were a lot more successful than you thought we'd be. In fact, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said, he has done such a good job that the question of the department's future is probably moot. `` It's much less likely you'll see abolition of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> in the future, largely because of me,'' he said. `` A lot of people think the department's been transformed.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> contended he had as much responsibility to lead `` an intense national conversation about education'' as to oversee federal programs. Sen. <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., the subcommittee chairman, has been highly critical of <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> but defended the secretary's conception of his job When he voted in favor of creating the department, <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON> said, `` I hoped there would be a national spokesman ... I quite agree with you that that is your role.'' The administration has sought deep cuts in education spending for every fiscal year except 1985 and 1989 _ the years for which proposals were submitted during presidential election campaigns. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> repeatedly has lectured lawmakers about the need to restrain spending and told them more money does not necessarily produce better education. For their part, lawmakers have blasted <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> for consistently agreeing to cuts far deeper than those proposed for any other department. The result has been a continuing series of stormy, sarcastic sessions with various congressional panels, including the one Tuesday. `` Mr. Secretary, I know you're going to miss these lovefests,'' said <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> indicated later that lawmakers may not have seen the last of him. He said he would n't rule out returning to a <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> post _ even possibly education secretary _ in a future Republican administration.
