<FIRST>r w PM-ContractFraud     05-11 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Contract Fraud,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Approves Tougher Penalties for Contract Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A unanimously passed <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill would raise penalties against contractors convicted of defrauding the federal government, and its chief sponsor predicts the measure will stop a flood of such cases. `` Procurement fraud is robbing the government of hundreds of millions of dollars a year, and in some instances costing peoples' lives,'' chief sponsor <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, said following Tuesday's 419-0 vote The measure, which now goes to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, would apply to any procurement contract of $ 1 million or more in which the government was bilked out of at least $ 250,000. Procurement contracts are those providing a product rather than a service. <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> said the bill would apply to some 10,000 existing contracts. The legislation would establish a maximum prison sentence of 10 years, and a minimum two-year sentence for cases involving a foreseeable and substantial risk of personal injury. <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> said the risk could result from substitution of inferior products by contractors, especially in military parts. Current law permits fines based on the monetary gain to the defendant or the loss to the federal government. The House bill would add a new fine of up to $ 10 million in cases in which the risk of injury is involved. A reward system would permit payments of up to $ 250,000 from the criminal fines for information leading to a conviction. The measure also contains protection for government whistleblowers who provide information leading to convictions. Fraud in procurement contracts has involved overcharges, malfunctioning equipment and product substitution, <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> reported in January that based on known cases, the estimated loss to the government in procurement fraud was $ 387.4 million in a one-year period ending March 31, 1986.
