<SECOND>PM-Postmaster,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Postal Service Cuts Could End by Fall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Post office window service and collections could be back to normal by the end of summer, but that wo n't mean the end of the agency's financial struggles, according to Postmaster General <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> said Tuesday that he is committed to restoring service that was cut earlier this year in the face of congressionally imposed budget restrictions. But reopening counters and restoring Sunday sorting and collection means finding $ 9 million a month in savings somewhere else, he said. With luck, he said, that can be accomplished by late summer. But he added that services will be restored only when he is sure that they can be kept open. Hundreds of construction projects for new postal facilities also were canceled or delayed to save money. `` Long after people forget about the windows being closed,'' building projects will still be delayed, land will have been sold to someone else and construction costs will be even higher, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, who took over as postmaster on March 1, said that explaining the need for service cuts at the same time rates are rising has been difficult. The rate increases imposed on April 3 do n't help, he said, because the accounting system mandated by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> results in the increased income being counted as a reduction in the national debt, not as extra money for the agency. On other topics, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> said: _ A system may be considered in which notices would automatically be sent out for people filing change or address forms _ The agency should help serve as a go-between for other federal agencies and the public, such as by making catalogs of <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Printing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> booklets available in lobbies The current program to deliver an AIDS booklet to every home is a good example, he said. _ It is `` amazing'' how many suggestions for new stamps he receives He said he does n't see anything wrong with issuing a stamp to honor singer <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> <PERSON> Presley </PERSON>, although so far the independent committee that makes the final choices has turned down that idea. The budget problems may be eased by a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill that would remove the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> from the federal budget. The agency had not been part of the budget until 1985. `` You really ca n't include us in the budget process, when we do n't use taxes,'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> said. Direct subsidies to the agency were ended several years ago. In addition to restoring the services that were cut earlier, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> said he wants to find ways to add other services. For example, automated postal tellers now under development could be placed in shopping malls, more markets and other stores encouraged to sell stamps at their checkouts and automation improved to speed post office lobby service. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> said battling for renewed public confidence means both improved service and improving perception of that service. He described a program in which postal carriers placed specific items in home mailboxes and, later, asked the residents to fill out forms indicating whether those items had been received. When the item was a large white envelope, only 0.3 percent reported that it had not been delivered, he said. But when it was a commercial catalog, 11 percent of the people who received it reported that it had not arrived. `` We know the items were delivered'' but the perceived value of the item makes a difference, he said.
