<HEAD>``A Lot Of Broken Hearts'' Over Coleman Sentence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The life sentences and possibility of parole given a once-condemned killer for his role in killing six members of the <PERSON> Alday </PERSON> family have left `` a lot of broken hearts'' in southwest <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, said one family member. <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> was sentenced Tuesday to six life prison terms after the jury that convicted him deliberated almost a week without voting the death sentence prosecutors won in his trial 14 years ago. By law, the life sentences were automatic because the jury could not agree. The 11 members of the <PERSON> Alday </PERSON> family present when the sentence was announced broke into tears. `` We do know we had some friends on the jury and we certainly appreciate them,'' said <PERSON> Bud </PERSON> <PERSON> Alday </PERSON>, brother of two victims, who discovered their bodies. `` We had some enemies, too, and they're going to have to live with it. `` Everybody down here is just as sick as they can be. There are a lot of broken hearts in <LOCATION> Seminole </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Alday </PERSON>, nephew of victims <PERSON> Ned </PERSON> and <PERSON> Aubrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Alday </PERSON>, said in a telephone interview Tuesday. <PERSON> Ned </PERSON> and his brother <PERSON> Aubrey </PERSON>, along with <PERSON> Ned </PERSON>'s sons <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chester </PERSON>, were shot to death in <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Alday </PERSON>'s mobile home on May 14, 1973, after they walked in on a burglary. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Alday </PERSON>, was repeatedly raped, then driven to a wooded area, where she was again raped, sodomized, shot and left to die on an ant hill. <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Isaacs </PERSON> and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Dungee </PERSON> _ who had escaped from a <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> prison camp _ were convicted in <LOCATION> Seminole </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> of the murders and sentenced to death. The convictions were overturned in 1985 by a federal appeals panel that said pretrial publicity influenced the original trial jury. `` It's been awful hard. We've been waiting for 15 years to see justice,'' said <PERSON> Ernestine </PERSON> <PERSON> Alday </PERSON>, widow of <PERSON> Ned </PERSON> and mother of <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chester </PERSON>. She said faith in God has sustained the family: `` He's going to be the judge.'' <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> was retried during the past several weeks in <ORGANIZATION> DeKalb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Isaacs </PERSON> was convicted in <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> in January and again sentenced to die; <PERSON> Dungee </PERSON> faces a retrial later this year in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> is immediately eligible for parole review under a 1964 law requiring a review after seven years in prison, and will go before the state <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pardons </ORGANIZATION> and Paroles next month, said board spokesman <PERSON> Silas </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>. But State Attorney General <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowers </PERSON> disagreed, saying <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> is covered by a 1983 law that would require him to serve 30 years before a parole hearing. <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>'s attorney <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> West </PERSON> said the life sentences were justified. `` We can only assume that if <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> had had a fair trial 15 years ago, he would have gotten a life sentence,'' he said. `` <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> is satisfied that his life has been spared,'' West said. Faded `` Remember the Aldays'' bumper stickers still can be found on a few cars in <LOCATION> Seminole </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, a sparsely populated area where most people are farmers. They do n't like that their tax dollars have financed such a long judicial process, said <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Alday </PERSON>, who was not in court Tuesday. `` I think <LOCATION> Seminole </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> is tired of getting these people TVs and tennis rackets,'' he said. `` Without a doubt, these people, they do n't deserve a second chance. They've not shown a bit of remorse.'' <PERSON> Alday </PERSON> said the numerous appeals and lengthy debate in the case since the murders took place have placed a strain on the closeknit family, whose `` big family reunions and such'' have now `` gone by the wayside.'' `` Most people down here would like to move on and put this behind them, yet it'll be years to come before everybody down here can move on with their lives,'' <PERSON> Alday </PERSON> said. `` When your family's been wiped out, it's not easy to put it aside,'' he continued. `` It's been a long hard road for everybody down here.''
