<HEAD>Prescriptions, Premiums Dominate Conferee Concerns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 House and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> conferees are getting down to the final rounds in their effort to resolve differences over a measure to protect the 31 million Medicare recipients against financial devastation from serious illness. After months of behind-the-scenes negotiations, the full conference met for the first time publicly on Tuesday to discuss the first major expansion of the program in its 23-year history. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> both passed legislation on catastrophic health insurance by overwhelming margins last year. Although more encompassing and expensive, the legislation is built on a basic framework devised by <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Otis </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> and embraced by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. While no formal timetable was set, the conference committee is expected to shape a final bill for presentation to the two houses later this month with an eye toward having the legislation ready for President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s signature next month. On Tuesday, both sides agreed on only two points: that major disagreements still separate them and that the time has come to resolve them. Sen. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee that did preliminary work on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill, cautioned against adopting a final version too expensive for the elderly to bear. He expressed particular concern about including the more expansive House version of a new prescription drug benefit. `` We can always expand these programs, but it is very hard to contract them,'' said <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>. But Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>, D-Calif., suggested a prescription drug program probably would be to the only additional benefit realized by millions of Americans who will not face a lengthy hospital stay `` They've got to see something out of this legislation,'' he said. The differences concern the level of additional protection the legislation will provide and how the costs are to be spread among the 31 million Medicare recipients who will have to pay for the Although the measures are substantially more expansive, and expensive, than proposed by the administration, The legislation does not provide long-term nursing home care under <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> _ a complicated and even more expensive issue put off until next year _ but would shield <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> beneficiaries against annual out-of-pocket doctor and hospital bills. The cap would be $ 1,043 in the latest <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> suggested compromise and $ 1,370 in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> compromise offer now on the bargaining table. Medicare now covers only the first 60 days of a hospital stay in a given year and pays only 80 percent of doctor bills, no matter how high they range. The major disagreement on the benefit side is over prescription drugs _ how much to pay and how soon to start paying. On the cost side, the major disagreement is how to distribute the additional premium <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> enrollees will have to pay _ particularly the so-called supplemental premium that is tantamount to an income tax increase for the estimated 50 percent of retirees who would be subject to it. The only other additional cost for the estimated 50 percent of the elderly not now subject to income tax would be a flat monthly premium of about $ 8 to $ 10 per month, depending on the shape of the final legislation.
