<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to correct category code</HEAD>
<HEAD>Breeding With Overseas Livestock Could Lower U.S. Meat Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELTSVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Exotic livestock breeds including Soviet sheep that reproduce much more quickly than American breeds could lower <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> meat prices if they were available here, an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official says. The American public should therefore demand that the government establish a program to gather and evaluate different breeds of livestock from abroad, said the official, <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Meat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Animal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, part of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. `` It is in the public interest to have such a program,'' <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> said Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is spending $ 26 million this year in an ongoing effort to gather, store and evaluate cultivated and wild plants so that breeders will have a kind of library of genetic traits to choose from in developing improved food crops, <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> said. Such a program has never been developed to provide what can be thought of as `` gene banks'' for livestock breeders, <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> said. The federal government should step in because commercial breeders have neither the capital nor the expertise to collect and evaluate exotic livestock species, <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> said. He spoke at a press conference held in conjunction with the <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s annual scientific symposium in <LOCATION> Beltsville </LOCATION>. The department's efforts to conserve plant `` germplasm'' _ genetic material that can be used to regenerate plants _ has been criticized as inadequate. Department scientists agree that the plant germplasm collection and storage system should be expanded, but they say it is difficult to convince other government officials and the public of the need for additional funds. The Office of Management and Budget recently acted to hold next year's budget equal to the current $ 26 million, said <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Shands </PERSON>, coordinator of the National Plant Germplasm System. Officials had hoped for an increase. `` <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> has not developed the clientele to insure that these programs get the support they require,'' said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Busch </PERSON>, a sociologist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> who specializes in agricultural issues. Of the various animals raised for meat in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> turkey </LOCATION> is the only one native to this country, and it was bred in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> before becoming established here, <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> said. He noted, for example, that <PERSON> Romanov </PERSON> sheep from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and Finn sheep from <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> reproduce much more quickly than traditional <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> breeds. `` Those are two sources of genes that might enable us to increase the breeding rate,'' <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> said. A higher breeding rate means lower production costs, and ultimately lower costs for the consumer. The two breeds have their drawbacks _ they produce less wool and it is of lower quality, he said. Nevertheless, their genes could be useful in the development of improved breeds, he said. Bringing such animals into the country involves expensive quarantining procedures that can last years, <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> said. In the case of sheep, for example, the animals must be kept in complete isolation for five years to be certain they do n't carry the scrapie virus, a potentially devastating disease. Only then can breeding experiments begin. Recent advances in biotechnology now allow sperm and embryos to be frozen, providing new means of storing genetic resources. Research also suggests that it might be possible to wash frozen embryos so that they are free of viruses, thus eliminating costly quarantines, <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> said.
