<FIRST>r i PM-Canada-Summit     05-11 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Canada-Summit,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Major Initiatives Unlikely At June Economic Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 To Canadian Finance Minister <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, the Oct. 19 stock market crash was a bracing `` tap on the shoulder'' but there is no cause for alarm about the world economy. The Economic Summit of the <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seven </ORGANIZATION> major industrialized countries, to be held in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> on June 19-21, is therefore likely to reaffirm current policies rather than adopt sweeping new initiatives, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> told a group of foreign correspondents Tuesday. `` I would n't look for major new statements, major new decisions,'' he said. But in another pre-summit briefing, the government-funded <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION> took a much gloomier view of economic realities. The council's deputy chairman, <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Lazar </PERSON>, said failure to correct the `` fundamental disequilibrium in the world economy'' _ evidenced by continued huge <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> deficits _ points toward another economic shock. He feared a `` hard landing'' in which interest rates will soar along with unemployment. `` We've gotten off relatively easy so far,'' <PERSON> Lazar </PERSON> said of the surprising resilience of major economies following the market crash. `` The question is whether between now and the election of a new <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government, the world can somehow muddle through. There remains a serious risk we may not.'' He said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must either raise taxes or slash spending to attack its deficits, but either course is unlikely in the final months of <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s presidency. With that major problem untackled, <PERSON> Lazar </PERSON> said, the summit's `` scope is pretty limited. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> maintained that since the October crash, the <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seven </ORGANIZATION> countries _ the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> _ have patched up differences and cooperated to stabilize markets. He also pointed to a clear shift in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy from consumption to exports, while <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> have moved to increase imports to shave their trade surpluses. `` Inflationary pressures on a worldwide basis are n't there,'' he said, adding that the recent `` upward creep'' of interest rates should not derail Group of Seven policies. But senior forecaster <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> Preston </PERSON> of the independently-run <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> said: `` We're still lacking a true consensus about how to manage international economic policy.'' He said that since the mid-1970's, `` people have been resistant to face up to the fact that real growth has declined.'' With `` macroeconomic'' fiscal and monetary policies fixed, Canadian officials said the summit will likely focus on `` microeconomic'' structural factors such as tax reform, deregulation and privatization. Reform of land prices and the goods distribution system in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the extension of shopping hours in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and tax incentives to boost the level of bank savings in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are examples of `` micro'' initiatives that could have a major impact, <PERSON> Sylvia </PERSON> <PERSON> Ostry </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s ambassador for multilateral trade negotiations, told reporters. She said summit leaders may discuss a proposal for the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, which governs world trade, to monitor microeconomic factors in the same way the International Monetary Fund surveys macroeconomic policies. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said he saw no need for changes in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s interest rate or other economic policies, despite the latest figures showing domestic growth stalled in January and February, after 3.9 percent real growth in the gross domestic product last year. `` We're still nicely on track and I see no reason to change,'' he said.
