<HEAD>Indian Leaders Begin Talks With Sandinistas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nicaraguan Indian rebel leaders, their support from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> shrinking, resumed peace talks with Sandinista government officials aimed at restoring some of their native rights. `` We have sought dialogue with the Sandinista government because our people are in a very difficult situation and because aid approved by the American <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has diminished,'' said <PERSON> Brooklyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON>, a leader of the Yatama organization of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> coast Indians `` In <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, the government has closed our rearguard and has adopted a hostile attitude against our organization while the Americans say we are acting against our own interests and have cut aid,'' <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday, when talks resumed. <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON> began negotiating in February with Interior Minister <PERSON> Tomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Borge </PERSON>, who heads a national commission on autonomy for the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> coast. They failed to reach concrete agreements in a meeting in March `` but we delved deeper into the proposals'' made by both sides, <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Yatama </PERSON>, which claims to have 2,000 guerrillas, has fought the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> for regional autonomy along the coast. The Indians also resisted any exercise of authority over them by the rightist, pro-American Somoza dynasty which ruled <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> for 42 years until the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> came to power in 1979. The Indian organization does not belong to the Nicaraguan Resistance, the umbrella group of the Contras, as the largest rebel group is known. The resistance is engaged in separate peace talks with the leftist government. <PERSON> Wicliffe </PERSON> <PERSON> Diego </PERSON>, one of five <PERSON> Yatama </PERSON> directors, was suspended for forming an alliance with the resistance, said <PERSON> Stedman </PERSON> <PERSON> Fagoth </PERSON> <PERSON> Muller </PERSON>, another <LOCATION> Yamata </LOCATION> leader. <PERSON> Yatama </PERSON> arose from the disintegration of <LOCATION> Misurasata </LOCATION>, an organization of Miskito, Sumo and <ORGANIZATION> Rama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION>. Factionalism has marked the Indian struggle against the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> since fighting began in 1981, when the government tried to impose authority on the isolated, traditionally independent coastal region. <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON> noted that the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> formerly viewed autonomy talks as `` counterrevolutionary,'' but said their attitude had changed. Still, the two sides differ over the definition of Indian self-rule. `` What the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> propose is decentralization of power, but through its representatives in the region,'' <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON> said. `` We want to elect our own authorities and organize the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> nation according to our customs and tradition,'' he added. `` We want our community borders to be as our grandfathers made them and not in a mechanical form.'' <PERSON> Yatama </PERSON> presented <PERSON> Borge </PERSON> with an autonomy proposal on Monday `` that is basic to talks for a permanent cease-fire,'' <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON> said. The talks are due to end Thursday. <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON> said a truce signed a week ago by a few <LOCATION> Yatama </LOCATION> leaders was not significant and was not authorized.
