<HEAD>Caller: Contra Dissidents Demand Resignation Of Rebel Commanders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A telephone caller said 200 dissident Nicaraguan rebels have declared they will no longer take orders from the insurgents' military commander, <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON>. The call to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday reflected divisions among the U.S.-backed insurgents during stalemated negotiations between the rebels, known as Contras, and the leftist Sandinista government. It could not be determined if the caller, who did not identify himself, represented a substantial number of guerrillas opposed to <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON>. He said the dissidents also demanded the removal of eight other military leaders of the Nicaraguan Resistance, the main 8,000-strong rebel force that fought the Nicaraguan government before a recent truce. Before he left <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> on Tuesday, <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON> acknowledged to reporters that there had been a rebellion and hinted forceful action might be needed to end the mutiny, The <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> reported in today's editions. A Contra official in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity, told the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday it was believed <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON> would come to meet with the dissidents. The caller did not say where the dissidents were located, but <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported on Tuesday that up to 3,000 dissident rebels have been holed up at a Honduran base camp since Saturday. It said the camp is in <LOCATION> Yamales </LOCATION>, a tiny Honduran village three miles from the Nicaraguan border. There has been constant friction among Contras who served in the national guard of the late right-wing President <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON> and groups who had fought to overthrow <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON>. The Sandinistas gained power after defeating <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON>'s national guard in a civil war that ended in July 1979. Many Somoza supporters fled into neighboring <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, where they established military camps, and were later joined by Nicaraguans who said the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> had betrayed the revolution. Members of both groups formed the <ORGANIZATION> Nicaragua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resistance </ORGANIZATION> about eight years ago and began guerrilla operations inside <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. The telephone caller said the dissidents were demanding the resignations of <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON> and eight other rebel military commanders because: `` We disavow them as corrupt ... and assure the Nicaraguan people that we, the workers, campesinos and students who form the army of the resistance will not allow corrupt and dishonest people in our ranks who want to return to the past.'' The caller said the dissidents recognized the authority of rebel military leaders <PERSON> Diogenes </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Membreno </PERSON>, <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Calderon </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON>, <PERSON> Encarnacion </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdivia </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tirzo </PERSON> <PERSON> Roman </PERSON> <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON>. <PERSON> Calderon </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON>, <PERSON> Valdivia </PERSON> and <PERSON> Roman </PERSON> <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> were among seven Contra leaders expelled from <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> on Friday after demanding that <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON> resign. <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON> <PERSON> Matamoros </PERSON>, a Nicaraguan Resistance spokesman in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, declined comment on the telephone call. Earlier, he denied the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> report that up to 3,000 Contras taking orders from <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Membreno </PERSON> had been holed up in a Honduran base camp since Saturday and were refusing to take orders from the resistance leadership. <PERSON> Matamoros </PERSON> said on Monday that <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> political and military representatives met on Sunday at a camp ner the Honduran-Nicaraguan border to try to resolve the disputes among the Contras. <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON> reportedly opposes the 60-day cease-fire agreement signed March 23 by <PERSON> Contra </PERSON> and government representatives. The pact calls for additional negotiations to make the truce permanent. The last peace talks ended April 30 in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> and no date or location has been set for another round.
