<HEAD>Europeans Report Transplanting Parts Of Same Liver Into Different
Humans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The world's first two reported successful attempts to transplant parts of the same liver into different patients are big steps toward overcoming the chronic donor organ shortage, say transplant surgeons. Dr. <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Bismuth </PERSON>, a liver transplant surgeon at <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brousse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, reported here Tuesday that he had no choice but to divide the liver of a 40-year-old brain-dead man for two women, both unconscious and near death. The procedure, performed May 1, is believed to be the second in the world, according to Dr. <PERSON> Christoph </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Broelsch </PERSON>, professor of surgery at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>. The previous one was performed in February in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` This is one way to increase the donors. If you have patients who are terribly ill and in equal need, it's one way out,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION>'s Dr. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Starzl </PERSON>, who performed the world's first successful liver transplant in 1967. `` I can see this happening at our institution anytime soon if we have the appropriate setting,'' <PERSON> Broelsch </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. About 450 people are awaiting liver transplants in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrell </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on Transplantation. About half are children. In this month's transplant, the donor had been rushed to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and was a suitable match for either the 40 - or 54-year-old woman Unable to choose between the women, <ORGANIZATION> Bismuth </ORGANIZATION> transplanted half the liver into each patient. Because the liver is the only organ in the body that can regenerate itself, it grows naturally along with the body after being reduced in size. <PERSON> Bismuth </PERSON> told about 100 physicians from around the world gathered in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> for a conference on liver disease that both of his patients' transplanted livers are functioning well. One of the women, however, is still critically ill because of kidney and lung complications she suffered before surgery. On Feb. 2, Dr. <PERSON> Rudolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hannover </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> performed a similar split-liver transplant <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON> said he, like <ORGANIZATION> Bismuth </ORGANIZATION>, was desperate to save two patients' lives even though just one liver was available. As a result, he split the liver of a 23-year-old man and transplanted half into a 2-year-old boy and the other half into a 63-year-old woman. Both recipients are back home and doing well, <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> early today. `` I guess the risk for both recipients will be a little bit higher. So I think it's a step forward, but it's only a step forward if one can not manage the donor problem,'' <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON> said. `` It's an enormous need for livers in our country,'' he said. `` We have too few donors, so we have to take all the maneuvers to get more livers, particularly of course for the small children.'' In recent years, <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON> and other doctors in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have trimmed livers so the organs can fit into transplant patients, particularly children for whom donor organs are most scarce. `` It's of course a pity to throw away the other half of the liver,'' <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON> said. Split liver transplants are more complicated than simply paring down the organ because doctors need to divide a common artery and bile duct, <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON> said. As a result, half the split organ is often weaker than the other. <PERSON> Broelsch </PERSON> said the one-year success rate is about 50 percent to 60 percent for children who receive reduced-size livers, compared with 80 percent to 90 percent for those who receive an entire organ. The risk for split-liver transplants will likely be even greater and, until more is known, will remain a method of last resort, doctors said. `` Nevertheless, it's a big step,'' <PERSON> Starzl </PERSON> said.
