<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar finished lower today in dealings against the Japanese yen, while stock prices fell back substantially. The dollar closed at 124.24 yen, down 0.39 yen from its finish on Tuesday. It remained little changed from its opening at 124.23 yen, hovering between the 124.17 and 124.35-yen level. `` Trading was mixed in selling and buying, but generally it was a quiet day without incentives to direct the market,'' said an official of a major commercial bank, speaking on condition of anonymity. There was also a wait-and-see attitude among investors in regard to the completion of the refunding auction of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Treasury bonds, which began Tuesday in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and the pending announcement in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> next week of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures for March, he said. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, which gained 147.95 points Tuesday, lost 251.20 points, or 0.92 percent to close the day's trading at 27,161.05. Share prices fell sharply during the afternoon session on a news report that British Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> said there could be an internationally coordinated boost in interest rates, traders said. The report by a <LOCATION> Japanese </LOCATION> news service quoted <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> as saying a coordinated effort to raise short term rates by <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and other leading nations is `` certainly possible.'' An official of a securities house, speaking anonymously, said there were no changes in fundamentals, however. Volume on the first section trade was estimated at