sitioned to be the first auction house to be allowed to set up at least for one auction in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Pury </PERSON> had worked with Soviet cultural officials in his former capacity as curator of the Thyssen-Bornemisza Collection in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, arranging exchanges with the Soviets. In August, at tea with Mrs. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, he broached the subject of an auction. `` When I mentioned the possibility the first time, to my amazement, they were intrigued, and said it was worth exploring. There was a definite interest,'' <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Pury </PERSON> recalled. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Pury </PERSON> said he had a free hand in selecting the contemporary works for the auction, and he roamed <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and other cities, visiting studios and picking paintings. `` It's a very lively, vital group of artists whose works have been fought over by museums and collectors in the West,'' he said. For the artists, <PERSON> Feldman </PERSON> said, `` The prices they may get are secondary to their desire to have their work seen in the West, to be known in the West.'' Soviet officials presented a list of avant-garde works that could be sold, and <PERSON> Sotheby </PERSON>'s selected from that. Highlights of the collection will be shown for five days in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> starting Saturday; then in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> -LRB- May 22-24 -RRB-; <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> -LRB- May 26-27 -RRB-; <LOCATION> Cologne </LOCATION> -LRB- May 31-June 3 -RRB-; and <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> -LRB- June 9-15 -RRB-. Customers planning to attend the auction in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> can sign up for a special program of visits to the artists' studios, as well as lectures, museum tours and evening entertainment. Among the more established contemporary artists whose work will be sold are <PER