<SECOND>PM-VDT Law,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Local Law To Regulate Use In Suffolk</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAUPPAUGE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Companies with 20 or more computer terminals would be required to provide employees with work breaks, eye care, special lighting and detachable keyboards, under a bill approved by the county <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>. If <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Executive <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Halpin </PERSON> signs the bill, which passed 13-2 Tuesday, it would be the first law in the country to regulate the terminals in private businesses, workplace design experts said. Business leaders have sharply criticized the measure, charging it would be costly to implement and put placing them at a competitive disadvantage in the marketplace. They contend the bill will drive companies out of the county. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> <PERSON> Pally </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Long </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the region's largest business organization, said the bill `` threatens the continued economic vitality of the community. `` We're obviously very disappointed and will urge Mr. <PERSON> Halpin </PERSON> to veto the bill,'' he said. The bill is intended to protect the health and safety of employees who use video display terminals -LRB- VDTs -RRB-, according to legislator <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, sponsor of the bill. <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, calling many offices `` high-tech sweatshops,'' said he believed there was a need for regulation. <PERSON> Halpin </PERSON>, who must act on the bill within 60 days of its passage, said he would hold a public hearing before deciding whether to sign it. Lawmakers in the <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> county approved a similar bill last summer, but it was vetoed by the acting county executive at the time, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> A. Lo Grande. Labor unions, business leaders and workplace experts from around the country said the <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> bill would serve as a model for other municipalities or states. `` Whether this bill will result in legislation elsewhere is unclear, but it'll rejuvenate a lot of campaigns for VDT standards around the country,'' said <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Stock </PERSON>, associate director of the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Occupational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION>, an advocacy group in <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. Legislator <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Rizzo </PERSON>, who abstained from voting, said, `` this legislation is doing what a union should be doing. Some companies hinted that they may consider areas outside of <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> for future expansion. `` We view the law as a potential deterrent to doing business in <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Reisman </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION>. `` Undoubtedly the law would have to be taken into consideration as a factor in planning expansions.'' <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> has 1,500 employees in <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> _ operators and office personnel who use VDTs routinely. Optometrist <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Hallick </PERSON> testified at the hearing that many of his patients complain that they never needed glasses until they started working at VDTs. <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> companies, however, argued that there is no evidence that the prolonged use of a VDT is harmful to the employee. It mandates that companies pay 80 percent of the cost of annual eye exams and eyewear required for an operator and provide 15-minute work breaks every three hours for employees who work at the terminals. Businesses would be given six months from the bill's passage date to comply. If the employer does not comply with the regulations, the bill provides a basis for an employee to seek damages in court.
