to begin on forming new government. Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``The
resolution...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANK POWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Poul </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> resigned today in a bid to form a new center-right coalition after an inconclusive parliamentary election called over <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s nuclear-arms policy and its allegiance to <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> Danish radio said <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> submitted his resignation to Queen <PERSON> Margrethe </PERSON> II at <LOCATION> Amalienborg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palace </LOCATION> and told her negotiations would begin this afternoon. Tuesday's balloting ended in a stalemate in which neither major bloc could form a majority government. <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON>'s outgoing minority, four-party coalition retained its 70 seats in the Folketing, the 179-member parliament. The socialist opposition dropped two seats for a total of 79. The opposition Social Democrats, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s largest party, touched off the election by pushing through parliament a new anti-nuclear resolution the government refused to implement because of strong objections from the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. The resolution, designed to bolster <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s 1957 peacetime ban on nuclear arms, calls for notifying visiting warships that such weapons were not allowed in port. Unless the resolution is overturned by the new parliament, the government will have to carry it out, after the wording has been determined. Despite the vote, the government and the opposition both claimed the outcome vindicated their position on the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> issue. <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON>, speaking during a televised post-election roundtable discussion with other party leaders Tuesday, claimed that the four coalition parties opposing the April 14 resolution came out best. `` The parties that voted for the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> resolution on <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> policy were weakened,'' he said. <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON>, who had called the election just eight months after the last one, claimed the outcome would ease <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s crisis in <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>. He had wanted voters to endorse the country's `` full membership'' in the Western military alliance. But Social Democratic leader <PERSON> Svend </PERSON> <PERSON> Auken </PERSON> insisted `` there was still a majority backing the resolution'' and said his party would work for its implementation in the new parliament. In reply, <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> invited <PERSON> Auken </PERSON> to negotiate with government parties `` a sensible solution'' to the issue. Until the opposition resolution was passed last month, successive governments assumed that <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies abided by <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s non-nuclear policy The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> said the new measure, if implemented, would jeopardize their plans to land troops in times of crisis to reinforce <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, which controls the narrow access to the <LOCATION> Baltic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. They also said the measure threatened the solidarity of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and was against their own policies, which forbid disclosure of which ships carry nuclear arms. Final results showed 3,913,318 ballots cast for a turnout of 85.8 percent. <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON>'s Conservatives lost three seats, retaining 35. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Uffe </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellemann-Jensen </PERSON>'s Liberals, the senior coalition partner, won 22 seats, three more than it had before. The coalition's nine-seat <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> and four-seat <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> were unchanged. Capturing seven additional seats to total 16, far-right <ORGANIZATION> Progress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> was the biggest winner. Shunned by the mainstream parties for its anti-immigration campaign, it is not expected to join a new non-socialist coalition. The Social Democrats stopped their slide from the past two elections by capturing 55 seats, a gain of one. The opposition <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> dropped from 27 to 24 seats, while the far-left <ORGANIZATION> Common </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Course </ORGANIZATION> failed to poll the 2 percent necessary for representation. The swing party Social-Liberals held 10, a loss of one. Two semi-independent territories, the <LOCATION> Faeroe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION>, each elect two representatives. A diplomat from a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> country, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the nuclear issue `` could n't come at a worse time.'' The election came the day before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> was to meet Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> to prepare for a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit in two weeks. A perception that <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> is wavering in its support of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> could strenghthen the Soviets' hand.
