 Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said today the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> could ratify the U.S.-Soviet nuclear arms agreement in time for the upcoming <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit if Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> works out disputes in talks this week with the Soviets. `` I think there's still time to get the consent of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to ratification prior to the summit. But these matters have to be dealt with,'' the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> Democrat said on <ORGANIZATION> ABC-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Good Morning America.'' <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> leaders said this week consideration of the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty would be delayed indefinitely because of a dispute between the superpowers over verification of settlement accords. The dispute has almost dashed hopes the INF treaty would be ratified by the time President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> travels to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> for the May 29-June 2 summit meeting with Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> today for a long-planned meeting with Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> that has taken on greater importance because of the verification issue. <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said if the impasse is not resolved, the treaty could languish in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> well after the summit. `` Even though I ca n't visualize these matters not being worked out, it is possible,'' said <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>. `` Unless they are worked out, I think we'll have a long delay and no ratification of the treaty anytime soon.'' <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said that although the verification provisions under dispute are technical issues, enough Democrats and Republicans in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> are concerned to keep the treaty on hold. `` It is a serious problem because on-site verification goes to the heart not just of this treaty, in terms of verifying, but also future treaties,'' he said. `` Frankly, the military significance of this treaty is marginal at best,'' <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said. `` But the symbolic and precedent kind of example here is very important, so we've got to clear these matters up.'' <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> also raised the possibility that the dispute over provisions signed by negotiators in December could reflect disagreements among Soviet officials. `` It may be that this is not the top leadership at all, but rather people who lost their points in the negotiation and now are trying to restore those points through obstruction in implementation,'' he said.
