<HEAD>New Premier Picks Chief Of Staff, Promises Prompt Choice Of
Cabinet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 19 grafs to UPDATE with Rocard choosing chief of
staff, newspaper reaction on his choice as premier. Picks up 21st
graf pvs, `The president...'
^By ELAINE GANLEY</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Premier <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> appointed a longtime aide as his chief of staff today and consulted with senior Socialists on choosing <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> ministers in his new government. President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, re-elected on Sunday, appointed <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> on Tuesday to succeed conservative <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON>, long a rival to <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> within the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said he would not delay naming his Cabinet ministers, but it was not clear how soon the appointments would come. The first move by the 57-year-old premier was to name <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Huchon </PERSON> his chief of staff. <PERSON> Huchon </PERSON> was chief of staff to <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> when he was planning minister, then agriculture minister, in Socialist governments from 1981-85. He is first deputy mayor of Conflans St. <PERSON> Honorine </PERSON>, the working-class town in the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> suburbs where <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> has been mayor since 1977. It is common in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> for senior national officials to keep their mayoral posts. <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, who was premier for two years, has been mayor of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> for more than a decade. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, 71, was re-elected to a seven-year term in a landslide victory over <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> on Sunday. But the success of a new government will depend largely on whether the Socialists gain the confidence of a broad spectrum of voters _ and backing from centrist politicans. <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>'s center-right coalition still controls the 577-seat <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, marking the first time in the 30 years of the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fifth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> that a government must face a hostile <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. Commentary on <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON>'s appointment was largely favorable in French newspapers, even those that traditionally support rightist policies. The conservative daily <ORGANIZATION> Le </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Figaro </ORGANIZATION> noted that <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> favored a free-market economy and said he had `` shown his independent spirit'' by bucking official Socialist positions in the past. Former President <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> Giscard </PERSON> d'Estaing, a prominent centrist member of the assembly, said on Tuesday that he was `` waiting for a gesture toward a united <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'' in the composition of <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON>'s Cabinet <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON>, 57, told reporters Tuesday that he would keep in mind <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> people's concerns `` for their future, for their jobs, for their education, for their security.'' He must assemble a government which reflects the Socialists' swing to the center and which can try to work with the conservative parliamentary majority <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> says he will not automatically dissolve the assembly to try to gain a leftist majority, choosing to try for success with the present system. He also says the new government will include non-Socialists. The new government is expected to profit from an increasingly divided right wing, ranging from centrists to ultraright. Presenting himself as <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s `` unifier,'' <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> wooed over some centrist politicians upset with <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>'s attempt to accommodate the growing far-right movement. <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON>, a self-described `` free enterprise leftist,'' was prepared to run for the presidency this year until <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> declared his candidacy. Polls usually rate him as one of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s most popular politicans. A non-doctrinaire Socialist, he symbolizes the president's effort for a policy of `` enlargement'' beyond the Socialist ranks. The debonair, 5-foot-7 <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> is known for his independent and outspoken views. He resigned as agriculture minister in 1985 because he objected to a new system of proportional voting instituted by the Socialists. The president bucked pressure in affirming that he will not immediately dissolve the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, in which the Socialists hold 211 seats. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> is being urged to take advantage of the victory momentum and move quickly with changes. The president, stressing the new political configuration, has made few concrete proposals for change. One of the few significant programs <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> says he intends to pursue is re-establishing the Socialist wealth tax abolished by <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> in 1986. He wants the proceeds to fund a minimum guaranteed income. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> also says he will not continue the <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> government's privatization of state-owned companies.
