<FIRST>r i PM-TransplantAftermath     05-11 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Transplant Aftermath,0428</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Heart Transplant Recipients Risk Mood Troubles, Family Distress,
Study Says
^By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new study of heart transplant recipients has found that half suffered mood disturbances after the operation and many faced family problems related to the surgery and recovery. The results indicate psychiatrists must work to help recipients get the most out of life after transplants, researchers said Tuesday. Side effects of post-transplant medications cause some of the psychological problems, said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>, assistant clinical professor of psychiatry at the <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Physicians </ORGANIZATION> and Surgeons in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. He and colleague <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Kornfeld </PERSON> did the work, which <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> presented Tuesday at the annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` This is a very important paper. It's really pace-setting and pace-making,'' said <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> B </PERSON>. <PERSON> Levy </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Valhalla </LOCATION>, an authority on psychiatric aspects of transplants. The research was done with two groups of recipients. One group of 30 was interviewed at up to a year after surgery, while another 43 were studied up to six years after the transplant. Overall, 37 of the 73 recipients had experienced some kind of mood disturbances following the surgery. Problems ranged from demoralization and difficulty adjusting to post-transplant life to four cases of major depression. Fifteen of the 37 patients reported a period of mood swings, irritability and argumentativeness, often with some mild mania. Symptoms began in the first few weeks after transplantation and gradually receded as dosages of drugs to prevent organ rejection were tapered off. Twenty-two patients reported sexual problems as a side effect of anti-rejection drugs. Twelve patients said they had experienced family or marital troubles, such as children running away from home or picking fights with their parents. The second problem was especially common with teenage sons who resented the father's trying to re-assert a role of disciplinarian now that the disabling heart condition was over, <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> said. Some problems result from the use of the anti-rejection drug cyclosporine, which is inconvenient to administer and accompanied by such side effects as headache, burning pains and interference with sexual performance, researchers said in a written version of the report. `` Impotence and fearful avoidance of sexual intercourse lead many patients to feel guilt and disappointment, which is expressed in fighting or creating psychological distance from the partner,'' they said. `` These problems tend to work out over the course of 12 to 18 months.'' Sixteen patients also complained of decreased memory.
</TEXT>
