>'s urine were `` comparable to those which could be expected following heroin use,'' said <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Brott </PERSON>, an FRA spokesman. Engineer <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> was killed when his empty train slammed into the rear of another empty commuter train. He tested positive for marijuana in his urine and his blood, the <ORGANIZATION> FRA </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Metro-North </ORGANIZATION> officials have blamed <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>, 42, for failing to activate an automatic safety system that could have prevented the collision. They also said the train appeared to be traveling well over the 15 mph speed limit. Three other railroad employees who controlled train movements also had controlled substances in their systems, the <ORGANIZATION> FRA </ORGANIZATION> said. The three, who worked at a station near the crash site, have been absolved of responsibility for the crash, according to <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Metro-North </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman. Along with <PERSON> Furlong </PERSON>, who worked in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, they were suspended after the accident and now face disciplinary hearings. <ORGANIZATION> Metro-North </ORGANIZATION> employees found to have used drugs on the job must enter a substance abuse program or face dismissal. They also are subject to spot drug testing while in the program. <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> declined to say whether the tests indicated drugs might have affected the men's performances. A final report on the accident, to be released in about two months, will determine what role drug use played in the crash, he said. The tests, he said, did not indicate how recently the workers might have used the drugs.
