<HEAD>Man Convicted Quickly in California `Trailside Slayings'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jury took only seven hours to weigh 500 pieces of evidence and testimony from 91 witnesses, then found a man guilty of killing five hikers in a series of `` trailside slayings'' that terrorized <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> parks. The <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> jury that convicted <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON> on Tuesday will return next week to begin for the penalty phase to determine whether the he should be executed or spend the rest of his life in prison. <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON>, 58, of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, was convicted of first-degree murder with special circumstances in the 1980 killings of five hikers in two <LOCATION> Marin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> parks, part of a series of crimes dubbed the `` trailside slayings'' eight years ago. After four months of hearing evidence, the jury returned the verdict against <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON> at the end of its second day of deliberations. Attorneys on both sides were surprised by the quick decision. `` It certainly seems to suggest they did n't buy anything the defense presented,'' said <LOCATION> Marin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Deputy District Attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Posey </PERSON>, who portrayed <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON> in closing arguments as a cold-blooded killer whose `` ultimate goal'' was to commit murder and rape and get away with it. `` We were much more hopeful than this,'' said defense attorney <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>. `` It came as a surprise to have an unfavorable verdict as fast as this.'' Defense attorneys argued <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON> deserved acquittal because of `` serious doubts'' created by what they termed questionable police procedures and inconsistencies in the testimony of witnesses. <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON>, who already has