<HEAD>Federal Study: Fewer Defects In Condoms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fewer defective condoms are showing up on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market, although more than 33 million condoms were recalled or rejected in the last year, a federal study says. Only about four in every 1,000 domestic condoms were deemed defective, an improvement from a 4.8 defective rate last year, said Dr. <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, which tested 115,000 condoms for such problems as pinholes and tears. Imported condoms proved more risky, with a defective rate of 6.5 per 1,000, which was still a drop from last year's rate of 7.3, he said. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> testing that ended last month resulted in more than 30 million imported condoms being kept from distribution and 3 million domestic condoms taken off the shelves in 19 recalls, according to the study. `` Although the level of defects in condoms has dropped, there is a need to continually improve the defective rate,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said, adding that the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> will continue to make random tests. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> issued its report Tuesday at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Microbiology </ORGANIZATION> annual meeting, where hundreds from academia, government and industry exchanged ideas on topics ranging from the spread of disease to how microorganisms can help control acid rain. Surgeon General <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> and other health professionals have said condoms and mutually faithful monogamous relationships remain the best weapons to prevent the spread of AIDS and other sexually transmitted diseases.
