<HEAD>Activist For Indian Rights Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, who called himself the grand sachem of the Mohegan-Pequot Indian Nation and conducted a marriage ceremony for newspaper heiress <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Hearst </PERSON>, has died. He was 90. <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, known as `` Chief Rolling Cloud,'' died Tuesday at Lawrence and Memorial Hospital. He broke his hip in a fall at his home last month. Best known as an Indian leader involved in lawsuits seeking the return of land to his southeastern <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> tribe, he was also a cowboy who worked the Western range during the first quarter of this century. In the 1930s, <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> founded the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> to protect Indian rights. He remained its head for decades. In addition to speaking in behalf of Indian causes, he lectured, wrote music and led an orchestra. He used the title `` grand sachem,'' although the chairman of the Mohegan tribal council said the last grand sachem died in 1769 and the title did not exist. <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> became a national figure in the early 1970s because of his practice of `` adopting'' people into the Mohegan-Pequot Nation. Among those he adopted was <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Hearst </PERSON>, kidnapped in the early 1970s by the radical <ORGANIZATION> Symbionese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. At the time, <ORGANIZATION> Hearst </ORGANIZATION> was being sought by the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> for a bank robbery and firearms violations. <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, blaming the crimes on a spell cast by <ORGANIZATION> Hearst </ORGANIZATION>'s captors, named her `` Brave Heart. Later, he asked that she be pardoned when she served a prison term. In 1979, <ORGANIZATION> Hearst