<HEAD>Texas Authorities Raid Unlicensed Boys' Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities launched a surprise inspection at an unlicensed home for boys today, taking away one youth and issuing citations to 19 men who locked arms to hinder officials from entering. Authorities snapped a padlocked gate and broke through the human chain shortly after 6 a.m. to begin inspecting birth certificates of children at the facility run by the Rev. W.N. <PERSON> Otwell </PERSON>. The inspection involved the state attorney general's office, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rangers </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Otwell </PERSON> and state Attorney General <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Mattox </PERSON> have disagreed for two years about whether the facility should be licensed by the state, and <PERSON> Otwell </PERSON> at one time agreed to close the facility. The facility is a combination home for troubled boys, a church-run school and preschool. It has about 25 boys and 10 toddlers and pre-schoolers, said church secretary <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>. A state district judge ruled April 12 that state officials could inspect the facility in the <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> compound at any time and remove children found there without a relative or guardian. `` They played it low-key. They said they did n't want a confrontation,'' said <PERSON> Rocky </PERSON> <PERSON> Otwell </PERSON>, the reverend's son, of today's multi-agency inspection <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Dusek </PERSON>, a spokesman for the attorney general, said a 17-year-old youth lacking guardianship papers was removed from the facility and taken to a <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> emergency shelter, and that 19 men were cited for preventing execution of civil process. In March 1986, a state district judge in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> ordered <PERSON> Otwell </PERSON> to close the home, but in November 1987 suspended $ 97,000 in fines after the minister promised he would keep the home closed unless the state passed a law exempting church homes from licensing. The state has never done so. <PERSON> Otwell </PERSON> reopened the facility this spring in mobile homes, vowing to renew his fight over licensing. `` If they come to shut us down, we'll just pick her up and sail her on down the road,'' said <PERSON> Otwell </PERSON>, who has previously contended that the requirement that he seek a state license violated the constitutional separation of church and state. Parents of several of the 25 students attending the school have been staying at the compound in past weeks anticipating an inspection, said Ms. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>. Authorities herded everyone into the school auditorium, asked to see children's birth certificates and released them when parents showed documents, she said. Rocky Otwell, interviewed by telephone, said his father was too busy to comment on the incident. `` He's upset, but there's not visibly any angry words exchanged,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>.
