<HEAD>Pope Meets Thousands of Jobless and Poor in Mining Town</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with pope addressing miners and
peasants, meeting in Paraguay canceled. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COCHABAMBA, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> today promised tens of thousands of jobless miners and dirt-poor peasants the church would help them pursue a society of love, solidarity and justice. In a one-hour morning visit to the hard-hit mining city of <LOCATION> Oruro </LOCATION>, the pontiff said he was aware of the crisis in <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>'s tin mining industry. In <LOCATION> Asuncion </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION>, meanwhile, the government of President Gen. <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> canceled a scheduled meeting between <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> and a group of Paraguayans that included opposition leaders. Authorities cited `` security reasons.'' The pontiff arrived in <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> on Friday for a 13-day tour of four South American nations. He is to leave <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> Saturday for <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> and is scheduled to arrive in <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION> on Monday. `` The deep mines that years ago were the great source of national wealth ... are now only mute witnesses to the so many lives consumed silently there,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> told the miners. `` I come with a message of hope, which does not mean passivity in the face of misery that each day becomes more evident, but instead is an obligation to construct a new society founded in love, solidarity and justice.'' The pope spoke from a tall platform that gave him a clear view of the entrance to <LOCATION> Oruro </LOCATION>'s state-run <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION> mine, from which most workers have been laid off in a government austerity program. An umbrella held by an aide sheltered the pontiff from the intense sun of <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>'s wind-swept altiplano, or high plain. <LOCATION> Oruro </LOCATION> is 12,160 feet above sea level. Local mining union leader <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> told the pope: `` Today you have not heard the call of our work sirens, because the mines are empty, and in our mining camps you hear only the wail of children, because they can not lift bread to their mouths.'' A rural farmer also spoke to <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>: `` We peasants suffer a lot. Treated very badly, we suffer for our produce. Prices are not good. We are cheated.'' Unemployment in <LOCATION> Oruro </LOCATION>, a city of 132,000, is running at easily twice the national average of 22 percent. It is considered the center of misery in <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, itself <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s poorest country. The collapse of world tin prices prompted <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>'s conservative government to shut down 14 of 21 state-run mines, leaving 21,500 of 27,000 miners out of work. The pope was to return from <LOCATION> Oruro </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Cochabamba </LOCATION>, where he spent Tuesday night in a monastery. He had several events planned for this afternoon in <LOCATION> Cochabamba </LOCATION>, including a mass and an encounter with the country's youth. <LOCATION> Cochabamba </LOCATION> is the gateway to the country's principal coca-growing region and a center for cocaine trafficking. It also is plagued by a growing problem with local drug consumption, especially among the young and poor. In <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Paz </PERSON>, the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> reaffirmed the importance the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> places on traditional values and criticized a Bolivian Indian custom of concubinage. The meeting in <LOCATION> Asuncion </LOCATION> was scheduled to bring together diverse members of the Paraguayan civilian sector, including leaders of opposition parties that are not recognized by the government. The government had criticized the invitation of opposition politicians to the meeting.
