<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Security forces exchanged gunfire today with Sikh extremists holed up inside the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION>, and police said witnesses had seen the bodies of five radicals inside the complex. Electricity and water were cut off to the temple, <LOCATION> Sikhism </LOCATION>'s holiest shrine, on Tuesday after more than 800 pilgrims were evacuated, according to security sources who spoke on condition of anonymity Heavy firing was reported early today between an estimated 100 extremists and about 2,500 police and paramilitary forces surrounding the walled complex, which covers about five city blocks. <PERSON> A.A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Siddiqui </PERSON>, deputy inspector general of police, said at least 10 people have been killed and 10 injured since the violence began Monday. He said there were reports that five bodies of Sikh radicals were inside the temple but there was no way for police to verify them. Police earlier reported that three bodies, believed to be Sikh militants, were seen at daybreak on the ground outside the temple complex. <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hakeem </PERSON>, a paramilitary police commander, said it could not be determined if the men had fallen from the temple rooftop or killed while attempting to sneak in or out of the shrine. <PERSON> Siddiqui </PERSON> said his men had orders to fire on anyone moving inside the shrine. He said that his troops could see entrances to food stores and an ammunitions dump inside the shrine and were preventing militants from getting to them. `` We will keep this up for a least a few more days,'' <PERSON> Siddiqui </PERSON> said. `` Either the militants will be forced to surrender or will be eliminated.'' He added, `` We have no plans to enter the temple at this time.'' The temple's head priest, <PERSON> Jasbir </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> <PERSON> Rode </PERSON>, was out of the temple for a speaking engagement on Monday and has not been allowed to return. He told reporters he asked authorities Tuesday for permission to return but was denied. He was conferring with Indian officials today on ways to resolve the confrontation, said <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> Police Supterindent Baldev <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> said. Meanwhile, a curfew imposed three days ago remained in place in most parts of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>'s old, walled sector. Elsewhere in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state, two men were killed by Sikh gunmen early today in the central <LOCATION> Jalandhar </LOCATION> district, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> reported. The latest slaying raised to more than 940 the number of deaths blamed on the extremists this year. Since 1982, militant Sikhs have been waging a guerrilla war for an independent homeland for their minority sect in the northern state. Their attacks have increased in recent months, despite the federal government's decision a year ago to take direct control of security in the state. Although a majority in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, Sikhs comprise just 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million people. The Sikhs claim they are discriminated against by <PERSON> Hindus </PERSON>, who make up 82 percent of the nationwide population. The temple siege began after at least five people were killed and 10 hurt in a gunbattle Monday between Sikhs inside the complex and security forces. The Golden Temple has become the main stronghold of Sikh separatists, and an estimated 100 were believed holed up in and around the shrine. The complex includes offices, living quarters, hostels for pilgrims, dining halls and kitchens. The temple itself is surrounded by a pool and reached by a single walkway. The security forces, beefed up after the initial outbreak of fire, were given orders on Tuesday to shoot anyone attempting to leave the shrine. Much of their gunfire on Tuesday afternoon was directed at a watch tower overlooking the temple's main entrance. In June 1984, the Indian army carried out a raid to drive militants from the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> and more than 1,200 people were killed. Five months later, Prime Minister <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> was assassinated by two Sikh bodguards in revenge. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chidambaram </PERSON>, minister of state for home affairs, told <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> today that `` other forces'' were being moved to <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> to deal with the situation, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> reported. He did not elaborate.
