<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> has come down on the side of those who advocate that <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> establish a robot research and manufacturing facility in space to fill the time until a space station is in orbit. `` We add our voice to the growing chorus of those urging <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s development of a mixed fleet of craft for access to space using ELVs -LRB- expendable launch vehicles -RRB- for launching unmanned experiment packages and the shuttle for those that require human presence,'' the academy said in a report Tuesday It urged the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> to develop methods for keeping the shuttle in orbit for longer periods of time than has been the case and to develop `` free-flier'' platforms. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration wants the space agency to encourage private development of space by agreeing to lease 70 percent of a robot factory, which would be put into orbit by the space shuttle. Such a scheme would cost $ 140 million a year and require astronaut visits every three months for servicing. Congressional committees have balked at the idea, viewing it as a move to deprive the space station program of funds, thus killing it.
