<HEAD>Thousands of Doctors Sign Up For Free Heart Medicine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 12,000 doctors have joined a pharmaceutical company program that gives free heart medicine to needy patients since the program was expanded five weeks ago, a company spokesman said. Under the program, <ORGANIZATION> G.D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Searle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> issues certificates to participating doctors, clinics and hospitals for heart medicine. Patients obtain the certificate and prescription from their doctors, then give them to pharmacists, who mail the certificate to <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> for reimbursement. `` We are satisfied the program is a success,'' <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Vaughn </PERSON> said by telephone Tuesday from <PERSON> Searle </PERSON>'s corporate headquarters in suburban <LOCATION> Skokie </LOCATION>. During a 14-month pilot program that ended in April, <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> distributed two kinds of high-blood pressure medication to 20,000 patients. On April 6, the company announced it would expand the giveaway to all seven of its heart medicines. Other drug companies have similar programs, but <PERSON> Searle </PERSON>'s is more extensive, said <PERSON> Judee </PERSON> <PERSON> Shuler </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceutical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> D.C </ORGANIZATION>. The value of the pilot program was put at $ 9 million by <PERSON> Searle </PERSON>, <PERSON> Vaughn </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Vaughn </PERSON> said the program is available to clinics nationwide and that there is no time or money limit. `` These are life-time drugs. You would n't want to put someone on a drug that he is going to need all his life, then pull the plug on it later,'' he said. The drug giveaway is for people with no insurance or other assistance, and annual incomes of $ 8,000 or less for a family of one or two and $ 11,000 for larger families.
