<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrats rallied on Capitol Hill today and vowed to fight President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> from now until November if he makes good on his threat to veto the 1,000-page trade bill. `` If you decide to pull out that pen, Mr. <PERSON> President </PERSON>, we will have to override that veto and we have the votes to do it,'' Rep. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>, D-Calif., told listeners gathered at the steps of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> It remained unclear, however, where supporters of the measure would find enough support in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to override a presidential veto. The bill fell three votes short of what would be needed. `` We'll consult the stars,'' Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON>, D-Mass., said, drawing a laugh from the crowd Several hundred supporters including congressmen, their aides and labor officials spilled into the street as party leaders urged <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to relent and sign the measure. It was the final show of political muscle before sending the measure to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s desk. Absent from the ceremony, however, was Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> committee </ORGANIZATION> that fashioned the legislation In reply to a question, Rep. <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ark </LOCATION>., said <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> may have had a scheduling conflict There have been recurrent reports, however, of friction between <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, over provisions of the measure. At the rally, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> introduced Majority Leader <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, D-Wash., as `` the architect'' of the bill The ornate Statuary Hall next to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> chamber was chosen as the site for ceremonies in which <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> was signing the bill and sending it on to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. Officials of labor unions and religious groups are among the invitees. Republicans are expected to be mainly absent from the festivities, aimed at pressuring <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to drop his veto threat and sign the bill after all. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has been critical of the bill's curbs on <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> oil exports and its provision requiring companies with 100 employees or more to provide 60-day notice of plant closings and large-scale layoffs. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> told a manufacturers' association the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration recognized the popularity of the plant notification provision `` We've gotten together _ you and us and everyone whose been trying to ` fight' the notification -LRB- provision -RRB- _ a real political problem,'' she told the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION>. `` The polls have indicated that, from the people I've talked to, 62 percent of the people think that plant notification is the right way to go. Another 13 percent think it should be much more stringent,'' she said. The major provisions of the bill have hardly figured in the debate in recent weeks. They would streamline the system under which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> imposes import restrictions and takes other steps to aid endangered <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industries and retaliate against international trade violations. But there are numerous other provisions ranging from agricultural subsidies to repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil companies. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has been saying the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> provisions violate the Constitution by discriminating against that state's ports while the plant-closings feature would dull rather than sharpen the nation's edge in global markets Supporters of the plant-closings provision call it a humane and decent way to treat employees and their families. But there are only a handful of supporters for the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> provisions, which <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leaders have been trying in vain to erase from the legislation. `` I had hoped that if these offending provisions had been eliminated the president would have had one less reason for vetoing this bill,'' <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, said The remark appeared to mark the end of efforts to erase the provisions. The bill won final passage on April 27 but has been becalmed on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> while leaders sought to do some after-the-fact custom tailoring. The House last week approved a resolution that would have instructed a congressional employee to call the enrolling clerk to smooth out any minor wrinkles in the bill _ and erase the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> provisions while he was at it. To bring up the resolution in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, however, <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> needed unanimous consent and was unable to obtain it Tuesday when he sought to do so.
