<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A car packed with explosives blew up today on a bridge minutes after police had chased it away from the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, authorities said. Three people were killed and 15 wounded. The semi-official <ORGANIZATION> Cyprus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said an Arab man who owned the car was arrested while trying to run away from the scene. A caller claiming to represent terrorist <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Nidal </PERSON>'s group told <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> this morning at a bureau in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> that <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Nidal </PERSON>'s organization was responsible for the bombing. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> McAndrew </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s manager of news information, quoted the caller as saying it was the first of future attacks against Israeli targets. <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Nidal </PERSON>, whose real name is <PERSON> Sabry </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Banna </PERSON>, has been accused by <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> and Western intelligence agencies of directing scores of terrorist attacks. They include simultaneous assaults at <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> airports Dec. 27, 1985, that killed 20 people. His group, <ORGANIZATION> Fatah-Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, broke in 1976 with <ORGANIZATION> Fatah </ORGANIZATION>, the mainstream guerrilla faction led by <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>. Israeli Ambassador <PERSON> Aharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> said the Israeli Embassy was a possible target of today's bombing. Authorities said windows were sh