<HEAD>Report Urges More European Responsibility in NATO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies should revise their joint defense compact to shift more of the financial and military burden onto the Europeans, a new study has concluded. The report by a panel of legislators and defense experts from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and eight European <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> member countries is a summary of conclusions from a yearlong study on the future of the Western alliance. The report, titled `` <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> in the 1990s,'' is to be presented publicly in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on May 18. Details were disclosed this week by sources associated with the study. The report says a new political mandate for the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> is needed to reflect a fundamental change in the relationship between <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The European members must take on more responsibilities in line with the region's increased economic strength and greater political cohesion, the report said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, it said, is undergoing a major re-examination of its global role in light of massive budget and trade deficits that jeopardize not only its own economy but also the world economic system. As a result of growing European and diminishing <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> clout, leaders from both sides of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> should strike a new defense bargain, the report said. `` It's time for a better equilibrium'' within the 39-year-old alliance, said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Corterier </PERSON>, secretary-general of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> advisory group of parliamentarians that sponsored the study. `` We feel it can not be denied that the relative weight of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> has changed,'' <PERSON> Corterier </PERSON> said in an interview Tuesday. Pressure in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has been mounting in recent years for the Europeans to bear a bigger share of the cost of defending <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> territory. A <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> study published Tuesday said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> spends 6.7 percent of its annual economic output on defense, compared with 3.3 percent for non-U.S. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> members. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been predominant in <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> since it was formed in 1949. This is because of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s role as the nuclear guarantor of <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s security, as well as its traditional economic power. The report's conclusions do not call into question <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s official doctrine of relying on a mixture of conventional and nuclear arms to deter attack It says a substantial <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troop presence in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, as well as a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nuclear guarantee for the alliance, remains vital to Western security. Nonetheless, a new mandate for the alliance should be drawn up soon, preferably within a year after President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> leaves office next January, it said. The mandate should reaffirm the standard <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> aims of pursuing arms control agreements with the Soviet bloc while maintaining a strong defense. But it should include the following additional elements: _ The European members should promise to intensify cooperation among themselves as a way of economizing in an era in which government defense spending is expected to be severely constrained _ The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should welcome a move toward greater European cooperation on defense matters _ All the allies must agree that future <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> policy matters reflect a progressively larger European influence The report also recommended: _ Creating, separately from <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>, a consultative body to coordinate policies on security matters outside the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> treaty area Membership would be open to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and other non-NATO democratic nations. _ Lessening <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s reliance on short-range nuclear weapons and, by the 1990s, further reducing the number of nuclear arms in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> The report rejected the Soviet aim of scrapping all nuclear weapons. _ Establishing a NATO-Warsaw Pact crisis avoidance center, which would bring together military experts and diplomats from both blocs to exchange information on military activities and seek to resolve low-level incidents involving <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact military personnel
