<DATELINE>OZARK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A woman who was wounded during a Christmas rampage by a gunman who killed 16 people testified today that she crawled along the floor and hid behind a counter after being shot in the mouth. `` I thought to myself, there is nowhere else to go, so I stayed quiet,'' <PERSON> Roberta </PERSON> <PERSON> Woolery </PERSON>, a market cashier, testified during the trial of <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>, 47. Mrs. <PERSON> Woolery </PERSON> said identified <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> as the gunman and said she and <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> had been co-workers at the market for 3 -LCB- years. <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>, a retired <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> master sergeant, is on trial in the Dec. 28 deaths of former co-worker <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kendrick </PERSON>, 24, and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaffin </PERSON>, 33, in <LOCATION> Russellville </LOCATION>. Four people were wounded during the shootings. <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> is to be tried July 18 in the deaths of 14 relatives, including his wife, children and grandchildren. The bodies were found at his home near <LOCATION> Dover </LOCATION> after the shootings in <LOCATION> Russellville </LOCATION>. Police said the 14 were killed during the Christmas holidays. Mrs. <PERSON> Woolery </PERSON> testified that she did not know how many shots were fired because the incident happened so quickly and she could not distinguish gunshots from the noise made by bottles and cans that a customer threw at the assailant. On Tuesday, a witness testified that the gunman wore a `` horrid grin'' as he aimed his revolver at office workers during the rampage. The gunman stepped over the body of one of his victims, `` took a stance and pointed the gun at me,'' said <PERSON> Juli </PERSON> <PERSON> Money </PERSON>, extending her arms with hands clasped to show how the man held the gun. `` I screamed, ` No!' and dived behind some boxes,'' she said. `` He was grinning. He had a horrid grin that looked like false teeth and his eyes were wide open.'' According to police, <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> used two .22 - caliber revolvers to kill <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Kendrick </PERSON>, who friends say rejected <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>' amorous attention, and <PERSON> Chaffin </PERSON>, who apparently was a chance Police said <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> had a grudge against most of the people he is accused of shooting. <PERSON> Chaffin </PERSON> was shot in the right eye at point-blank range as he opened a door at <ORGANIZATION> Taylor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> after he and Ms. <PERSON> Money </PERSON> heard two shots fired in the office area, Ms. <PERSON> Money </PERSON> said. The gunman had already wounded the company president, <PERSON> Rusty </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>. It was <PERSON> Chaffin </PERSON>'s body, Ms. <PERSON> Money </PERSON> testified, that <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> stepped over before aiming at her. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Salyer </PERSON>, who was shot in the forehead, also said <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> fired with a grin on his face. <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>, who had worked for <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> and <PERSON> Salyer </PERSON>, then went to a nearby law office where Miss <PERSON> Kendrick </PERSON> worked and stood in front of her desk, according to another witness, <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>. Miss <PERSON> Kendrick </PERSON> returned to her desk a short time later and said, `` Can I help you?'' <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> had his hands in his pockets but jerked his right arm up and started firing a pistol, Miss <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. `` He missed her at first,'' she said. `` She just stood there. He kept shooting. Finally, he hit her.'' Prosecutor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bynum </PERSON> said in his opening statement Tuesday that <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Kendrick </PERSON>, a legal secretary, was shot at least four times in the head as she sat at her desk. About 60 spectators were present in <LOCATION> Franklin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Circuit </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Court </LOCATION>, including relatives of some of <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>' family members. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> McNulty </PERSON>, 36, of <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>, whose brother was among the dead family members, said, `` We've got our grief to deal with and <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> has got God to deal with.'' Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> replaced one juror with an alternate during a closed hearing. The judge said someone reported that the replaced juror said something derogatory about <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>. The trial was moved here because of extensive pretrial publicity.
