<HEAD>Trial Begins for First of 80 People Charged in Ethnic Riots</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> metalworker went on trial for murder Wednesday in connection with ethnic riots that killed at least 32 people in February, Pravda reported. He was the first of more than 80 people charged to stand trial. The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper said the defendant, identified as <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ismailov </PERSON>, was accused of participating in the riots in the <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> and intentionally killing someone for `` hooligan motives.'' <PERSON> Ismailov </PERSON> is an employee of a pipe and tube plant. Ethnic violence broke out Feb. 28 in <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> during a territorial dispute between <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> and the neighboring republic of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. Armenians had demanded that <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, an Armenian-dominated region of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, be annexed to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. Armenian activists said Armenians living in <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION>, an industrial city on the <LOCATION> Caspian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> about 20 miles of <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION>, were hunted down by bands of Azerbaijanis. Soviet media have said 26 ethnic Armenians and 6 Azeris were killed. Officials said 200 people were injured. All those charged will be tried in <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> by a tribunal led by <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Klokov </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Azerbaijan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, Pravda said. If convicted of murder, <PERSON> Ismailov </PERSON> could be sentenced to death and shot by a firing squad. Pravda quoted <PERSON> Zulfi </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadzhiev </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Sumgait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, as saying even petty crime has declined since the riots, but effects of the violence remain. `` Many families that left the city during those bitter February days have still not returned home,'' he said. `` We will be exact: more than 1,200 jobs at factories and institutions are still empty.'' <PERSON> Gadzhiev </PERSON> said the jobs were being kept open because officials expect the people who held them to return. The unrest caused a `` bleeding wound'' that made a rift between Armenians and Azeris, Pravda said. It also declared that the trials will show `` who needed to sow hostility between the two peoples,'' a possible reference to official allegations of foreign involvement in the riots. Soviet media customarily accuse such Western media as the <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberty </ORGANIZATION> of trying to foment trouble among the many Soviet ethnic groups.
