<HEAD>Government Proposes to Make Islam State Religion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government introduced legislation in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday to make Islam the state religion of <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>. The move sparked street protests and was denounced by opposition parties and women's groups. `` Like the water lily is the state flower, Islam shall be the state religion,'' Information Minister <PERSON> Mahbubur </PERSON> <PERSON> Rahman </PERSON> told reporters before Prime Minister <PERSON> Maudud </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> introduced the bill in the house. The bill was expected to pass easily because the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Jatiya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> of President <PERSON> Hussain </PERSON> <PERSON> Muhammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON> holds 251 of the 300 seats. `` The government is trying to divide the nation in the name of Islam,'' opposition member <PERSON> Shahjehan </PERSON> <PERSON> Siraj </PERSON> said. `` Government seems to have some bad motives behind it.'' Witnesses and opposition leaders said at least 50 people were injured when more than 1,000 opposition supporters stoned six government-owned buses in downtown <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>'s 105 million people are 85 percent Moslem, with <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION>, Hindu and <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> minorities. The country has had a secular constitution since it won independence from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> in 1971. <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON> told a religious gathering in March that `` the day-to-day life of the nation must be guided by the tenets of Islam and the ideals of Prophet <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>.'' `` This law will curtail the activities of the fundamentalists, who are gaining ground because of Islamic slogans,'' said a senior leader in <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Jatiya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, who spoke on condition of anonymity. The constitutional amendment is the first major bill to come before the <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, which was elected last March 3. Most opposition parties boycotted that election, and only about half of the nation's 48 million eligible voters cast ballots. Twenty-one opposition groups, which have been agitating since last November for the ouster of <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON>, pledged to oppose any attempts by the <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> to change the constitution. These parties, which have no seats in the house, contend Parliament does not represent the people. But <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> promised that the bill would not be rushed to passage. `` There shall be enough time for the opposition to speak on it,'' he said. `` The government will seek public opinion on the legislation,'' he added. Several women's rights groups have already held demonstrations against the idea of making Islam the state religion.
