<HEAD>Groups Laud Bill Provide Quality Schooling for All 4-Year-Olds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A prominent business group and the nation's two major teachers unions on Wednesday endorsed a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill aimed at making high-quality nursery schooling available to all 4-year-olds The so-called Smart Start program, proposed by Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., would provide money to supplement and strengthen existing early childhood education programs run by schools, community groups and others States and communities would share the cost. The bill reserves at least half the spaces in the program for poor children. Better-off families would be charged on a sliding scale. The Kennedy bill authorizes $ 500 million for the program in its first year, $ 750 million in the second year and $ 1 billion in its third year. `` We believe the time for this legislation has arrived,'' <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION>, said in testimony to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> chaired by <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. Both <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatwood </PERSON> <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said preschool programs receiving money under the bill should not emulate kindergarten or grade school but should help young children develop and learn as individuals. They also said the federal government should set high training standards for preschool teachers in federally supported programs. <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON>, vice chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, said the group of 250 academic and corporate trustees views the <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> bill `` with considerable enthusiasm.'' <PERSON> Butler </PERSON>, retired chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Proctor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, recommended merging <ORGANIZATION> Smart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Start </ORGANIZATION> with the existing $ 1 billion Head Start program at the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. `` It makes little sense to have two programs,'' he said. <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> also said he was concerned about the federal government's reliability in paying for the preschool programs Under the bill, states would have to put up 30 percent the first year; 40 percent the second; and 50 percent thereafter. <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> said states should have to pay 50 percent right from the start. `` History has shown that where the federal government takes on too big a role and the federal funding is later reduced, many programs die,'' he said in his testimony. The <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> was formed to study ways to address pressing economic and social problems. Last fall the group released a study saying the nation should concentrate on helping poor children in their earliest months and years of life, including prenatal care and enriched preschool education.
