<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A defense attorney in the cocaine smuggling trial of reputed Colombian drug kingpin <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivas </PERSON> told jurors in closing arguments today that <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON>'s chief prosecutor must have attended a different trial. `` He was in a trial in which all the witnesses told the truth,'' <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shohat </PERSON> said of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON>, who wrapped up the government's final arguments minutes earlier. `` He was in a trial in which there was no cross-examination of the witneses. ... That was n't the trial that occurred in this courtroom.'' <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON>, 38, whom prosecutors said was a key member of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> cartel, is charged with bringing 3.3 tons of cocaine into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from 1978 to 1980, paying bribes and making threats to use <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>'s Cay in the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION> as a private relay station Co-defendant <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlton </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>, 57, of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pedro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, is charged with smuggling conspiracy. <PERSON> Shohat </PERSON> said a big inconsistency in the government's case was that the indictment claimed that all the cocaine was delivered to Colombians in southern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, but the government's key witness, an American, testified that some of the cocaine was delivered to him. In his closing arguments, <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON> referred to trial testimony that <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> used bribes, charm and threats to run a smuggling empire, and that for once <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> was without such advantages. `` He can not buy his way out of a just verdict. He can not charm his way out of a just verdict. And he can not force his way out of a just verdict,'' <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON> said. A day earlier <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON> said <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> was waging a violent war against the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and viewed cocaine as a weapon. `` He's still at war,'' <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON> told the jury that has heard 22 weeks of testimony. <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON> said Tuesday that <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> viewed cocaine as a weapon against the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The prosecutor also said the <LOCATION> Colombian </LOCATION> was responsible for smuggling 19 tons into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and had earned $ 20 million. `` That is an example of Mr. <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON>'s ` children' you saw in this courtroom,'' said <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON>. Several witnesses have testified that <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> referred to cocaine loads as children. <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON> blasted defense arguments that <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> had been used by convicted smuggler and key prosecution witness <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> as well as contentions that <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> was a legitimate businessman who wanted to develop <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>'s Cay as a resort. `` There is simply no way the defense is plausible, credible or believable,'' the prosecutor said. `` A legitimate businessman does n't attract tourists with machine guns.'' The prosecutor said that to equate <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON>'s drug organization to <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>'s group of American smugglers was like `` comparing the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sox </ORGANIZATION> to the Little League.'' `` The evidence in this case shows a trail of bribery, corruption, violence and personal debasement that has been created and fostered by Mr. <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON>,'' he said. The