<HEAD>Security Guard Writes Play About Farmer's Suicide</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lenard is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After reading about the suicide of a financially strapped farmer, a security guard began spending his evenings at home writing a play to dramatize the plight of farm families. <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> <PERSON> Riley </PERSON>'s `` Foreclosure'' opens next week for a limited run at an off-off Broadway theater in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> said he hopes the drama will be presented across the country. `` No one is a spokesman for the farmer, because farmers do n't speak much,'' <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> said Tuesday in a telephone interview `` Maybe the play could do that. It's suited to play in a field, in gymnasiums.'' <PERSON> Riley </PERSON>'s play is based on the experiences of the <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> family of <LOCATION> Waynesboro </LOCATION> in east <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lenard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, whose farm had been in his family for five generations, killed himself 20 minutes before the land was to be auctioned in February 1986 to pay a $ 300,000 debt. <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> reportedly hoped proceeds from his life insurance policy and a private land sale would settle the debt, but it was not enough. When the plight of his widow, <PERSON> Annabell </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, was publicized, <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> businessman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Argenbright </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> led a fund-raising drive to help the family. That drew the attention of, among others, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> developer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, who contributed $ 39,000. Two days before Christmas 1986, the mortgage on the 705-acre farm was retired. `` I kept getting news clippings and cutting them out of the paper about farmers committing suicide,'' said <PERSON> Riley </PERSON>, 38. But it was Mrs. <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>'s story that inspired him to write. `` I tried to show what it's like, what makes a farmer commit suicide,'' he said. `` Foreclosure'' does n't follow the Hill story exactly. In the play, for example, both husband and wife commit suicide, <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> said. Mrs. <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> now lives in <LOCATION> Augusta </LOCATION>; her son runs the farm. <PERSON> Riley </PERSON>, who has dabbled in theater before but never tried a major production, said he worked on the play for 1 -LCB- years. It will debut May 19 at the LaMama Theater, and run for three weeks. <PERSON> Riley </PERSON>, who farms part-time in <LOCATION> Blairsville </LOCATION> in north <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, said he planned to present Mrs. <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> with a signed copy of his play. `` Mrs. <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>'s story personifies for me the American farmers' condition,'' <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> said `` My hopes are that ` Foreclosure' will bring the urgency of the farmers' situation to the American conscience.''
