<HEAD>`Ecstasy' Drug Convictions Overturned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An appeals court has ruled that the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> does not have the authority to temporarily outlaw `` designer drugs'' as they hit the market. The 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday threw out the convictions of three men found guilty of distributing and conspiring to distribute MDMA, or methylenedioxymethamphetamine in 1985 and 1986. The drug's street name was `` ecstasy.'' The court said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney General had not delegated his authority to the administrator of the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> to designate the drug as a controlled substance. The opinion issued by Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Boochever </PERSON> said that federal law governing permanent scheduling of controlled substances was altered in 1984 with an amendment that fundamentally changed the process for temporary scheduling. Judge <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiggins </PERSON> dissented, saying, `` I believe the majority demands too much of the government's crime-fighting efforts in the face of an unambiguous delegation of responsibility by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.'' `` I believe the plain intent of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was to establish an expedited system of review in order to criminalize the possession, manufacturing and distribution of newly-developed ` designer' drugs before they become public health hazards,'' he wrote. In July, 1985, the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> administrator added <ORGANIZATION> MDMA </ORGANIZATION> to a federal list of temporarily controlled substances. Temporary scheduling, designed to take effect within 30 days of announcement to avoid lengthy public comment that could jeopardize public safety, expires after a year. It can be extended six months if the Attorney General has begun efforts to make it permanently illegal. The court did not make a finding that the Attorney General could n't delegate authority to place `` ecstasy'' on the emergency list.
