<HEAD>Bush's Foreign Policy Resume May Be More Hindrance Than Help</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has a foreign policy resume that stretches from <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to the Great Wall of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, but as he moves toward a fall presidential showdown his experience is proving more of a political handicap than <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' inexperience The Republican vice president relishes describing the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> governor of <LOCATION> Massachusestts </LOCATION> as one who `` does n't know much about foreign affairs.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> clearly expects to overwhelm <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> whenever foreign policy is an issue in the fall campaign. Granted that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has seemed ill at ease on foreign policy questions including the continued validity of the Monroe Doctrine against foreign intervention in the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hemisphere </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> retaliation against <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> and the use of nuclear weapons in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. But those seemed brief, mostly forgotten incidents compared to the incessant questioning <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> receives about his role in the Iran-Contra affair and his knowledge of Panamanian strongman <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s involvement in drug trafficking. And, it is <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> who will be haunted throughout the campaign by the words of his rivals for the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> presidential nomination, particularly former Secretary of <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Haig </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> who once questioned whether in administration councils the vice president had been `` in the cockpit or ... on an economy ride in the back of the plane.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> may yet prove correct as he anticipates that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' lack of foreign policy experience will lead him into a damaging gaffe when they debate in the fall. `` I ca n't wait for the debates,'' said the vice president. `` I ca n't wait for Mr. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> to discuss the <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> matter,'' he replied a week later when an <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> high school student asked if it was true, as <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was charging, that the Panamanian general had been on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> payroll. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he would ask <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, `` What would you do about it? ... You can make a lot of unfounded criticism, but what's his suggestion? What's he going to do and do it in a way that handles the delicate Central American relationships that we're building.'' Maybe, as <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, he ca n't wait to confront <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> on questions like <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> and Iran-Contra. But it is equally clear that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is just as eager to raise those issues. What better way to defend his lack of foreign policy experience than by going on the offense against the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> resume. Hardly a day goes by that the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor does n't raise the <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> matter `` Who was dealing with him and why?'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said Monday. `` Were we paying him and if so why? I can tell you one thing: If I'm the president we wo n't be doing business with drug-running Panamanian dictators.'' Dealing with dictators is a fact of life in international relations, one accepted by most voters. But the involvement in drug-trafficking makes the <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> matter a far more serious political issue. A pledge to wage a war on drugs was a theme common to the rhetoric of all presidential candidates, <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> and Democratic. That alone was recognition of the fact that voters were demanding to know what the politicians intend to do about a serious national problem. In 1984, Republicans were able to play back Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON>'s jibes at <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> when they were battling for the Democratic presidential nomination It will be the Democrats' turn this time. They are sure to recall <PERSON> Haig </PERSON>'s comment on the Bush-Noriega matter, the day the former <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> Cabinet official ended his race for the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> presidential nomination. `` I do think there's been less than forthright discussion of this issue by the vice president,'' said <PERSON> Haig </PERSON>. He refused to elaborate, but the fact that he was secretary of state during the first two years of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> presidency made his comment particularly tantalizing. Equally useful to the Democrats would be the collected jibes of <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, the acerbic senator from <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> who thrashed <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> Republican presidential caucuses and then saw his hopes of being the nominee buried on Super Tuesday. It was <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> who predicted Iran-Contra would be an issue for the Democrats in the fall campaign. And in case the opposition needed some help trying to describe the scandal, <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> referred to <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> advisers `` peddling arms to the ayatollah while others hear no evil, see no evil.'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> left it clear that one of the `` others'' was <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
