<HEAD>NY Gen, CP Note</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fuel Leak Found in Engine of Sea-Tac Crash Plane</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Pratt &amp; Whitney comments, brings up details of crash,
number of injuries, makes editing changes throughout.</NOTE>
<HEAD>SE Locals Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fuel leak was found in the engine of a <ORGANIZATION> Horizon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> comuter aircraft that caught fire and crash-landed April 15 at <LOCATION> Seattle-Tacoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, injuring 19 people, investigators said. The leak occurred because an `` O'' ring was out of place in a fuel filter assembly, and the filter was n't seated properly, <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopatkiewicz </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. The findings confirmed passenger reports of `` liquid streaming out of the engine,'' he said. `` An X-ray revealed that the ` O' ring was damaged and out of place,'' and a manual test also confirmed the leak, <PERSON> Lopatkiewicz </PERSON> said. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Horizon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, said investigators `` found exactly what we said the cause was'' and that it was `` not something Horizon had fixed, touched or been involved in.'' After landing, the twin-engine de Havilland Dash 8, with 40 people aboard, careened out of control and crashed into three passenger loading ramps. It came to rest against a terminal concourse. The crew and airport firefighters were praised for coolness under pressure and quick action in dousing the blaze. The turboprop engine, a 2,000-horsepower PW-120 manufactured at the <ORGANIZATION> Pratt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Whitney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> plant near <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>, was dismantled by investigators last week, he said. <ORGANIZATION> Pratt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> has asked airlines in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> that fly the Dash 8 to check the fuel filter assembly. `` They have checked and everything is in order,'' company spokesman <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> said Tuesday. He said it was possible the filter assembly on the Horizon plane might have been damaged during maintenance. `` Every time you remove a filter and put a new one in, ... if the cover is not on properly, a leak can develop because of the pressure,'' <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> said. The filter assembly had been in service six or seven days on the <ORGANIZATION> Horizon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> plane and was part of `` the fuel pump that had been taken straight from the factory and put on this engine,'' <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said. `` How it got in that shape, I do n't know.'' A check of other filter assemblies Horizon had in storage revealed a similar seating problem in one other unit, which was turned over to investigators, he added. Still unknown, <PERSON> Lopatkiewicz </PERSON> said, was how the fire ignited and why the plane went out of control when it made an emergency landing shortly after takeoff for <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
