<HEAD>Republicans Pledge Unity in Nebraska; Democrats Divided in WVa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> Republicans said Wednesday their bruising primary had given Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Karnes </PERSON> `` the strength to win'' against Democrat <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerrey </PERSON>, but <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> Democrats remained divided by their fight to choose an opponent for GOP Gov. <PERSON> Arch </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>. <PERSON> Karnes </PERSON>, who was running in his first election after being appointed 14 months ago, defeated Rep. <PERSON> Hal </PERSON> <PERSON> Daub </PERSON> by a bigger-than-expected margin Tuesday for the right to face <PERSON> Kerrey </PERSON>, the ex-governor who swamped one Democratic rival. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> edged millionaire industrialist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Raese </PERSON> to grab the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> nomination for an unprecedented fourth term, and will face another millionaire, insurance executive <PERSON> Gaston </PERSON> <PERSON> Caperton </PERSON>, who had never before run for office. Also in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> easily won the Democratic nomination to a sixth term and will be heavily favored over his Republican opponent, state Sen. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>. <PERSON> Daub </PERSON> appeared with <PERSON> Karnes </PERSON> at a unity gathering in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> on Wednesday, drawing cheers from party leaders as he placed a `` <PERSON> Karnes </PERSON> for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'' sticker on his lapel. `` I learned a great deal from him,'' said <PERSON> Karnes </PERSON>, who at 39 is the nation's youngest senator. `` Maybe he taught me too well.'' The four-term congressman, who had attacked <PERSON> Karnes </PERSON> aggressively during the campaign, praised his rival and said that without the hard-fought primary `` neither one of us would likely have had the strength to win'' in November. That sentiment was echoed by <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, director of communications and research for the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senatorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` Everybody would rather avoid a primary, but he got his political act together,'' <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Karnes </PERSON>. `` ... Had <PERSON> Hal </PERSON> <PERSON> Daub </PERSON> won, a lot of <LOCATION> Karnes </LOCATION> people would have sat it out.'' But <PERSON> Anita </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON>, communications director for the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senatorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campaign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, noted that <PERSON> Kerrey </PERSON> has been running ahead in polls pitting him against either Republican in a state where 51 percent of registered voters prefer the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION>. `` The race will tighten up,'' she said, `` but <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerrey </PERSON> remains a popular figure, and against that you have an appointed senator who just came through one of the most bitter primaries that anyone is going to see.'' In <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Caperton </PERSON> said Wednesday his top priority was to `` bring our party together because we share the common goals of better jobs, improved schools and a balanced budget for our state.'' But talk of party unity held little appeal for <PERSON> Clyde </PERSON> <PERSON> See </PERSON>, who finished second in a seven-man field. `` He bought this election fair and square,'' was the assessment from See, the former <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delegates </ORGANIZATION> Speaker who was outspent by <PERSON> Caperton </PERSON> $ 1.8 million to $ 500,000. See had been the Democratic nominee in 1984. Here are the returns from the major races, with 100 percent of the vote counted in <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> and 99 percent in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>: _ <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> GOP <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>: <PERSON> Karnes </PERSON> had 114,783 votes or 55 percent; <PERSON> Daub </PERSON> had 93,932 votes or 45 percent. _ <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> Democratic <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>: <PERSON> Kerrey </PERSON> had 153,611 votes or 92 percent; <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Michaelis </PERSON>, a disbarred lawyer, had 13,996 votes or 8 percent. _ <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> GOP Governor: <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> had 77,626 votes or 53 percent; <PERSON> Raese </PERSON> had 67,986 votes or 47 percent. _ <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> Democratic Governor: <PERSON> Caperton </PERSON> had 128,593 votes or 37 percent; See had 93,435 votes or 27 percent; state Sen. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Palumbo </PERSON> had 50,955 votes or 15 percent; Agriculture Commissioner <PERSON> Gus </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglass </PERSON> had 48,376 votes or 14 percent; the rest were divided among three other candidates.
