<HEAD>Gangster Sentenced in Murder of Chinese-American Journalist</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 8 grafs at end with background</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A gangster was sentenced today to a maximum term of 27 years-to-life in prison for killing a Chinese-American journalist in 1984, an act he testified was ordered by the Taiwanese government. <PERSON> Tung </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuei-sen </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bamboo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gang </ORGANIZATION>, was ordered to serve the prison sentence for the murder of <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> after he completes a 20-year sentence for heroin smuggling. <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mateo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Superior Judge <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> rejected defense arguments for concurrent sentencing that a prosecutor said could have set <PERSON> Tung </PERSON> free in six years. <PERSON> Liu </PERSON>'s widow also had asked the court for mercy, saying she was touched by <PERSON> Tung </PERSON>'s public repentance. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> called the slaying `` an act of political terrorism.'' <PERSON> Tung </PERSON>, 36, received 25 years to life for murder and two years for use of a firearm. Prosecutor <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> said <PERSON> Tung </PERSON> will not be eligible for parole for 17 years and eight months. <PERSON> Tung </PERSON> was convicted by a jury in March after admitting he gunned down <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> in the garage of the dissident writer's home in <LOCATION> Daly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> on Oct. 15, 1984. He claimed he carried out the act for patriotic reasons, believing he was killing a traitor on order from <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s government Wearing a red prison jumpsuit and manacles on his wrists and ankles, the short, stocky member of the infamous <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> gang smiled wryly as the sentence was explained to him by an interpreter in the packed courtroom. The 52-year-old <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> was a columnist for Chinese-language newspapers in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and was killed just after publishing an unflattering biography of <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Chiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Chung-kuo </PERSON>, who died four months ago. <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> had testified at <PERSON> Tung </PERSON>'s trial that before her husband's slaying, the <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> government had started sending over former friends of her husband's to try to convince him to quit criticizing the government. <PERSON> Tung </PERSON>, who is serving his heroin smuggling sentence at <ORGANIZATION> Lewisburg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penitentiary </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, is one of two suspected gunmen to be brought to trial in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He pleaded innocent last June despite having admitted to the slaying at his 1986 federal drug trial, saying he was unable to get a plea bargain and wanted to tell his story for the record. <PERSON> Tung </PERSON> testified that <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> was killed on orders from his gang boss and members of the Taiwanese government. He said he believed he was duped by his government into killing a man who was not a traitor and also sent a written apology to Mrs. <PERSON> Liu </PERSON>. In a letter to the court, Mrs. <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> said she hoped others involved in her husband's `` bloody murder'' would be prosecuted. <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON>, an assistant district attorney, said during the trial that Taiwanese Admiral <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Hsi-ling </PERSON> hired <PERSON> Tung </PERSON> to assassinate <PERSON> Liu </PERSON>. The prosecution said <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> <PERSON> Tun </PERSON>, 35, was the second gunman and is serving a life term for the killing in a Taiwanese prison. <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> <PERSON> Chi-li </PERSON>, 43, the reputed head of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bamboo </ORGANIZATION>, is also serving a life term in a Taiwanese prison for <PERSON> Liu </PERSON>'s killing.
