<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to CORRECT that today's recommendation
involves only this weekend's meeting, picking up 4th graf pvs,
``Attorneys for xxx</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LUFKIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal magistrate today recommended that Rainbow Family members be prevented from meeting this weekend in advance of a July gathering by thousands of family members. In a hearing Tuesday before Magistrate <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON>, health and <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> officials said the Rainbow Family's planned July 4 meeting in an <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> forest could strain resources <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> recommended to U.S. District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Justice </PERSON> in <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> that the group be restrained from advertising and organizing for the `` tribal council'' this weekend. <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> will consider the recommendation Thursday. Attorneys for the group and the government may file arguments on <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON>'s recommendation. He will hold another hearing Friday, a law clerk said. Family members will fight the recommendation and still plan to meet, spokesman <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Principle </PERSON> said. `` I do n't know who can stop this,'' he said of both gatherings. `` All our literature every year has said, ` Ignore any rumors of cancellations, regardless of source.''' Principle said no state has ever stopped the annual July gathering. At the Tuesday hearing, the forest service said the loosely knit group had not applied for special-use permits. Dr. <PERSON> Marietta </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowder </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Tyler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> testified that a Rainbow Family convention the size of one in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> last year that drew 17,000 people would strain drinking-water supplies and garbage collection abilities. Members of the self-proclaimed peace and environmentalist group gathered before the hearing on the federal courthouse steps to protest the possible prevention of their gathering. The group, which held its first gathering in 1972, has no headquarters and no membership list, said spokesman <PERSON> Garrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Beck </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Officials predicted about 500 people would show for this weekend's council meeting and up to 20,000 for the July 4 weekend event, called the Rainbow Gathering of the Tribes. A Rainbow Family spokesman who identified himself only as <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> said today that the group had scouted four possible sites for the gatherings _ <LOCATION> Angelina </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Davey </PERSON> <PERSON> Crockett </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Houston </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Sabine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forests </ORGANIZATION> _ but had not chosen one.
