<FIRST>r i AM-TeenSuicides     05-11 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teen Suicides,0576</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Longstanding Aggressiveness, Impulsiveness Seen in Suicidal Teens
^By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new study of suicidal teens clashes with the popular notion that teens often brood for weeks and give indirect clues before killing themselves, a psychiatrist reported Wednesday. `` That was very, very rare'' in the teen-agers studied, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON>, a teen suicide expert at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, which is affiliated with <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Instead, the teen-agers most commonly had a long history of aggressive and impulsive behavior, oversensitivity and suspicion, he said. `` They were aggressive to others for years, and finally they were aggressive to themselves,'' <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON> said. Their most common trigger for suicide was getting in trouble at school, or with the police or the family, but not knowing what the consequences would be, <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON> said. He spoke at a session of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s annual meeting Results of the research are still being analyzed, he said. The study focused on suicides of people age 11 to 19 in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> metropolitan area over two years. Of the 181 suicides, 142 or 78 percent were committed by males, <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON> said. Whites accounted for 71 percent of the suicides, though they make up only 62 percent of the area's population, <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON> said. Blacks were underrepresented with 12 percent of suicides and 20 percent of population, <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON> said. Sixty-two percent of the suicidal young people were ages 15 to 18, with 14 percent ages 11 to 14, and the rest age 19. To perform `` psychological autopsies,'' researchers interviewed 142 families of suicidal teens. <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON> said half the male cases had shown anti-social or aggressive behavior, while only about 14 percent could have been diagnosed with major depression. About half the female cases showed depression alone or with anti-social behavior, he said. Less common than the teens who showed the long history of aggressiveness and impulsivity were perfectionists, who worked hard at school and showed rigid personalities, <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON> said. Next came girls with untreated depression, and finally a small group of psychotic teens who had been treated, he said. The triggering factor of waiting for the consequences of getting into trouble suggests such teens were probably highly anxious, bordering on terror, when they killed themselves, he said. He told of one teen who had broken into a neighbor's home and been discovered by the neighbor. The homeowner threatened to tell the boy's father that night. The youth went home and shot himself. Another teen-ager, a perfectionist who worried about entering a new school as his family planned a move to <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, killed himself the night before they were to leave, <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON> said. The study also found that about half the teens who killed themselves had a close relative or grandparent who had attempted or succeeded at suicide. That was much higher than the rate for a comparable group of youths who had not killed themselves, <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON> said. That hints at a possible genetic influence on suicides, he said, but it might simply be that the young people were imitating their suicidal relatives. Other studies have shown that people who killed themselves show biochemical abnormalities. The longstanding characteristics of impulsivity and aggressiveness in suicidal teens mean those are signals to get a teen into treatment, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jed </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyatt </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
