<HEAD>U.S. Watches Election Aftermath in Denmark for Effects on NATO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With post-election maneuvering under way Wednesday in <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration declined to speculate publicly about how the balloting will affect continued Danish participation in the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. `` The results are somewhat inconclusive,'' <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> have a long and close friendship and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> government will continue to work closely with the government that is formed after the <LOCATION> Danes </LOCATION> have evaluated their election.'' The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration had been hoping Danish voters would elect parliamentarians opposed to a recently passed resolution that would make it impossible for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ships carrying nuclear weapons to visit <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>. The resolution has raised questions about <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s continued membership in <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> because nuclear deterrence is one of the bedrocks of alliance doctrine Tuesday's vote for 179 Parliament seats resulted in a modest shift to the right and strengthened the parties that give unqualified support to <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>, analysts there said. The future of the Danish nuclear resolution depends on whether Prime Minister <PERSON> Poul </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> _ who does n't want to implement the policy _ is able to form another minority government. White House spokesman <PERSON> Roman </PERSON> <PERSON> Popadiuk </PERSON> said `` we have an interest in the substance of the -LRB- nuclear -RRB- ship issue and expect to discuss it with the new government once it is formed.'' As the delicate coalition-bargaining unfolds in <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is remaining noncommital about the situation, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said. Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> made clear, however, during a trip to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> late last month that he is disturbed by the possibility that <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> might institute a ban on nuclear-armed ships. A similar ban enacted by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> led to the demise of a three-decade alliance in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> asserted that <LOCATION> Danish </LOCATION> action to limit nuclear missions would hurt <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> as well. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, who has said his hand in dealing with the Soviets is strengthened by <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> solidarity, said `` if you like the benefits, if you like peace, if you like the fact that progress is being made in negotiations, then you ought to like the responsibilities that go with making that possible.''
