<FIRST>r a AM-SplitLivers     05-11 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Split Livers,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Livers Halved; Transplants Working</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The West German doctor who performed the first known successful use of one liver split in two and transplanted into two patients said Wednesday that the procedure still is a method of last resort. `` I guess the risk for both recipients will be a little bit higher. So I think it's a step forward, but it's only a step forward if one can not manage the donor problem,'' <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hannover </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> said by telephone from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Exasperated by the shortage of donor organs, European surgeons have begun dividing livers and grafting the parts into different patients, a development hailed by other transplant surgeons when it was reported at a conference here Tuesday. `` It could double the donors,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Starzl </PERSON>, who performed the world's first successful liver transplant in 1967. `` If you have patients who are terribly ill and in equal need, it's one way out.'' `` It's an important step forward,'' agreed <PERSON> Christoph </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Broelsch </PERSON>, professor of surgery at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Bismuth </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brousse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> reported at the conference here on liver disease that he had no choice May 1 but to divide the liver of a 40-year-old man for two women, both near death. Both parts of the organ have since functioned well, although one woman is critically ill from kidney and lung complications she suffered before surgery, according to <LOCATION> Bismuth </LOCATION>. The liver is the only human organ that can regenerate itself. In splitting a liver, surgeons divide it by its two main groups of blood vessels, but a common artery and bile duct must be carefully divided, and one half can be weaker than the other, <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON> explained. <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON> performed such an operation Feb. 2, believed to be the first successful attempt at split-liver transplantation in the world. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, about 450 people are awaiting liver transplants, according to <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrell </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on Transplantation. About half of them are children. <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON> said he, like <ORGANIZATION> Bismuth </ORGANIZATION>, was desperate to save two patients' lives but had just one liver. As a result, he transplanted the halves of a 23-year-old man's liver into a 2-year-old boy and a 63-year-old woman. Both recipients are home and doing well, said <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON>. `` I can see this happening at our institution anytime soon if we have the appropriate setting,'' <PERSON> Broelsch </PERSON> said. `` We have to take all the maneuvers to get more livers, particularly of course for the smaller children,'' <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON> said. `` I have many patients waiting and many children waiting and too few donor organs.'' Doctors have been trimming livers for several years to make them fit properly, particularly for children. `` It's of course a pity to throw away the other half of the liver,'' <PERSON> Pichlmayr </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Broelsch </PERSON> said the one-year success rate is about 50 percent to 60 percent for children who receive reduced-size livers, compared to 80 percent to 90 percent for those who receive an entire organ.
</TEXT>
