<HEAD>Mixed Reception Seen for Next Wave of 20,000 Cubans a Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thirty-six bleary-eyed Cubans arrived before dawn Wednesday to tears and hugs from relatives, but they and 20,000 other Cubans coming to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> this year face a more uncertain reception from the rest of the city. For some residents, concerns stem from memories of escalated street crime after the 1980 Mariel boatlift; others, particularly <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> blacks who feel their economic and political opportunities will shrink with the rising <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> population, also are concerned. And government officials fret about the financial costs of the new immigrants. `` It's a shame people tend to remember only the bad parts of Cuban immigration, but the truth is that most Cubans have gone on to be some of our most thriving citizens,'' said City Manager <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> <PERSON> Odio </PERSON>, a Cuban-American. Officials are quick to note that the new, carefully screened <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> immigrants, who began arriving by the hundreds this month, have little in common with the 125,000 who came ashore when <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> opened the port of <LOCATION> Mariel </LOCATION> _ and his prisons _ for six months and ignored <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> administration pleas for controlled immigration. `` Not only have they been through a rigorous procedure by federal immigration officials to ensure their financial stability, but most will initially be living with relatives here _ that's a support system the bulk of the Mariels never had,'' said <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernal </PERSON>, refugee affairs coordinator for <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. Unlike most other immigrant groups, Cubans have chosen one city as their own. More than 80 percent of the Cubans coming here since <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>'s 1959 revolution stayed in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. They have overtaken non-Latin whites, called `` Anglos,'' and make up 42 percent of <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s 1.86 million people as the largest group. Cubans dominate <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> politics, economy and society and transformed a tourism-based southern city into a modern, Latin-oriented financial center. Still, simmering resentment flared in the years immediately following <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>'s uncontrolled `` Freedom Flotilla.'' A minority of hard-core criminals helped push <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> atop violent crime statistics and that lawless image was spread with a <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> remake of `` Scarface,'' starring <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Pacino </PERSON> as a Mariel cocaine kingpin. Thousands were placed on the public dole, and state and local governments still are seeking federal reimbursement for $ 150 million in services spent on the refugees. In 1980, <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> residents expressed a backlash by passing an anti-bilingualism ordinance, and continued resentment by the remaining non-Latins often surfaces on radio talk shows and other forums. `` Cubans already here would like to allow any Cuban to come over here and live in liberty _ but you have to draw the line somewhere,'' said WNWS radio talk show host <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Rantel </PERSON>, who roused attention with his proposed referendum to put a cap on public spending for refugees. Black leaders have protested every new influx, fearing Cubans will further dilute black political and economic power. `` From day one they're competing for the same jobs as blacks,'' said <PERSON> Garth </PERSON> <PERSON> Reeves </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, publisher of the black-oriented newspaper The <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. `` We need more Cubans like we need the plague.'' The basis for the new immigration is an agreement signed by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> in late 1984, only to be suspended by <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> five months later after the start of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> broadcasts into <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. That pact was revived seven months ago when <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> agreed to take back about 2,500 <LOCATION> Mariel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cubans </LOCATION> _ a move that sparked riots and hostage sieges at federal detention centers in <LOCATION> Oakdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> then opened its doors to 3,000 political prisoners and the annual flow of 20,000 immediate relatives of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens. The 36 former political prisoners and their families, who arrived in a regular chartered flight at Miami International Airport from <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION> Wednesday, were part of another group of some 400 political prisoners and relatives whose release was secured from the Cuban government by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>. Cubans are being issued 40 to 45 visas a day and the immigrants are allowed to travel by any means they desire anytime within four months of the visa, said <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. At that rate, about 250 arrivals per week are expected this month and as many as 350 a week are expected by summer's end, she said.
