<HEAD>GAO Faults Quality Assurance Efforts by Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Government efforts to make sure <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> patients receive good health care are hampered by poor coordination, questionable information and a lack of treatment standards, a congressional investigative agency said Wednesday. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said it `` found reasons for concern about current systems for monitoring'' the quality of care given the Medicare program's 31 million enrollees. The government spent $ 70 billion on such care last year. In a report, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said review methods of `` uncertain validity'' are being used and problems identified by one set of reviewers are not coordinated for action by others. Further, it said, `` the accuracy of key information -LRB- generated by reviews -RRB- is questionable'' and the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> HCFA </ORGANIZATION>, does not have an adequate long-term strategy to improve its overall Medicare monitoring system. Any future strategy should include setting minimum standards of clinical practice and testing incentives to get doctors to follow them, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. It recommended that the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> health subcommittee, chaired by Rep. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Stark </PERSON>, D-Calif., consider proposals to assign quality-assurance responsibilities to a new or existing federal entity Stark, who requested and released the report, said he would use it `` to look at whether we need to develop legislation to make sure we get good quality care for the nation's retirees.'' `` Right now we do n't know if we're getting quality in the medical care <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> is paying for,'' <PERSON> Stark </PERSON> said in a statement. `` The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report makes clear that <ORGANIZATION> HCFA </ORGANIZATION> does n't have a strategy for finding out how to know quality care when we see it, or if we did, to make sure <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> is receiving it.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, of which <ORGANIZATION> HCFA </ORGANIZATION> is a part, was quoted in the report as agreeing with all or most of the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>'s recommendations. The report said the agency opposes creation of a new federal entity to develop quality assurance methods but would consider improvements in internal coordination.
