<HEAD>Man Gets Maximum for Wife Killing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man who pursued his estranged wife for two years, then shot her 13 times and stuffed her body in an oven, was sentenced Wednesday to 28 -LCB- years to life in prison. A jury found <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Linton </PERSON>, 32, of <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> guilty in February of the murder in February 1987 of <PERSON> Yvonne </PERSON> <PERSON> Renee </PERSON> <PERSON> Linton </PERSON> in her <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> apartment. He was also convicted of attempted assault on a friend of Mrs. <PERSON> Linton </PERSON> who was in the apartment moments before the killing. <PERSON> Linton </PERSON> entered his wife's apartment from the fire escape and attacked her and the friend as she spoke to her mother on the phone. She shouted, `` <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>, you're a murderer!'' her mother said. Their three children were asleep when he came in and did not see him. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Colabella </PERSON> imposed a 25-year to life term for murder and a 3 -LCB- - to seven-year term for the attempted assault conviction _ both the maximum _ and ordered that they be served consecutively. <PERSON> Linton </PERSON> says he is innocent and will appeal. The murder occurred one day before <PERSON> Linton </PERSON> was due in court to answer a charge that he had violated a judge's order of protection barring him from contacting his wife, who was divorcing him. According to prosecutor <PERSON> Jeanine </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON> <PERSON> Pirro </PERSON>, <PERSON> Linton </PERSON> pursued his wife for two years from <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>, repeatedly threatening her. The couple's 11-year-old son, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, testified that his father had repeatedly said he would `` hunt down'' his wife and kill her for leaving him.
