<HEAD>With AM-Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 4,000 construction workers demanding higher wages were on strike Wednesday in southern <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. The strikes began Tuesday when 1,000 workers stopped work in <LOCATION> Pristina </LOCATION>, capital of the southern region of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>. The workers were demanding pay raises of 100 percent. Most make about $ 50 a month. <PERSON> Izet </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheku </PERSON>, trade union president in <LOCATION> Pristina </LOCATION>, informed the strikers about an economic recovery program of their construction company. <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> said most workers greeted the news with applause, but a few taunted <PERSON> Sheku </PERSON> that `` you promised us a lot before but nothing was realized.'' The workers protested excessive bureaucracy and organization in the company without any decision taken on whether to continue the strike, <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> said. The agency said the number of workers on strike in and around <LOCATION> Pristina </LOCATION>, capital of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s poorest region, rose to 4,000 Wednesday. About 2,000 textile workers of a textile plant in <LOCATION> Djakovica </LOCATION>, another <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> town, went on strike a week ago demanding higher pays before they were accomodated. In 1987, according to official estimates, there were more than 1,570 strikes in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> involving some 365,000 workers.
