<HEAD>China Suspends Fireworks Exports After U.S. Crackdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 26 million defective or mislabeled fireworks have been seized in a federal crackdown that reportedly has led <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to suspend export production of firecrackers. More than 100,000 cartons of Chinese fireworks awaiting shipment were recalled and production of fireworks intended for export to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was halted in April, until quality control can be improved, sources familiar with the Chinese fireworks industry said Wednesday. The sources spoke on condition they not be identified. <PERSON> Zheng </PERSON> <PERSON> Wanchen </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said he had no information on the report. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>, head of the importing company <ORGANIZATION> Hop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pyrotechnics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Monterey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, was out of town and not available for comment, his office said. But officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Product </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> comfirmed that more than $ 2 million worth of imported fireworks has been seized in recent weeks in a joint operation with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. That operation concentrated on imported products arriving at customs offices in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, S.C.. the safety commission reported Mislabeling and overloaded fireworks were the most common problems cited by the agency, which seized more than 15 million `` Thunder Bomb'' firecrackers containing between 72 milligrams and 84 milligrams of powder. Federal law limits firecrackers to 50 milligrams. The crackdown does n't mean there will be no Fourth of July fireworks, agency officials added. In <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, for example, some two-thirds of the imported products passed inspection and were allowed into the country. The effort does represent a shift in emphasis from inspecting retail dealers to trying to stop problems before they are widely distribued, according to <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Terrence </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scanlon </PERSON>. `` We have taken enforcement of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government safety standards from the roadside to the dockside in an effort to be more effective,'' <PERSON> Scanlon </PERSON> said Tuesday in a statement in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> where he announced `` Midwest Thunder,'' the joint Customs-CPSC operation in that area. The effort combining the work of the two federal agencies will give taxpayers `` more bang'' for the dollar, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mackey </PERSON>, an aide to <PERSON> Scanlon </PERSON>. Officials predicted the effort would lead to the availability this year of safer firecrackers. In 1987 more than 9,000 Americans were injured by fireworks seriously enough to require hospital treatment, the safty agency said. Seized fireworks can be returned to commerce and sold if the problem is repaired, such as improving the labeling and warnings, according to officials. Products that can not be fixed are destroyed, they said.
