<HEAD>Allied Soldiers Reminisce Over Life Behind Enemy Lines</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: To update with French Jeds arriving, INSERTS two grafs after
5th graf bgng ``This week.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Aging American, British and French comrades who harbor the often agonizing memories of one of World War II's most heroic missions gathered Wednesday for probably their last full reunion, 44 years after they were parachuted behind enemy lines `` It took some of them this long to find each other, and they wo n't let go,'' said <PERSON> Daphne </PERSON> <PERSON> Friele </PERSON>, who was an 18-year-old secretary in the British intelligence office that trained 279 Americans, Britons and Frenchmen for a mission code-named `` Jedburgh.'' Records of the operation remained top secret until 1985, although many of those taking part have told their dramatic stories of sabotaging German forces and supporting the European resistance. The specially trained soldiers were dropped in teams of three with a radio _ scattered across <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> The </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> _ in advance of the June 6, 1944 <LOCATION> Normandy </LOCATION> landings. Their code name, Mrs. <PERSON> Friele </PERSON> said, comes from the name of a Scottish town where the term `` Jedburgh justice'' was the rule for dealing with sheep rustlers: `` hang them first and question them afterwards.'' This week, 51 American, 26 French and 18 British survivors of the <LOCATION> Jedburgh </LOCATION> unit will meet with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, receive honors at the French and British embassies and visit the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> headquarters where one of their members, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Colby </PERSON>, was director in the mid-1970s. The final group of French veterans arrived Wednesday to shouts of greetings from their fellow <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> soldiers at <LOCATION> Dulles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. French Gen. <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecquenem </PERSON> of <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Julien </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Concelles </PERSON> said his memories of the resistance are `` neither sad nor gay. We experienced the happiness of fulfilling a duty.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Friele </PERSON> _ she later married an American `` Jed'' who died in the Korean War and, after the Jeds first reunion in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> four years ago, married another one _ said she has been able to track down all but two of the original <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> soldiers in the operation. For them she has only names and scant detail: <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Gruen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Forbes </PERSON>. `` I was 18 and very impressionable, so these people have always been my heroes, and they always will be,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Friele </PERSON>, 62, who has lived in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since the war. Her second husband, <PERSON> Berent </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Friele </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 65, of <LOCATION> Redding </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, like many of the American Jeds, was also sent into <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to aid resistance against the Japanese. Mrs. <PERSON> Friele </PERSON> said life after the war has been difficult for some of the men because of the intensity of their experiences dodging enemy forces. She said the reunion in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and one in 1985 of American Jeds have given the men a chance to share experiences, often unpleasant, that they had rarely talked about. Many had not seen each other since they were trained in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, she said. `` Things that angered them just spilled out,'' she said. `` Some could n't readjust. They became alcoholics and went through terrible experiences,'' she said. But she said many have done very well in the military and elsewhere. In addition to <PERSON> Colby </PERSON>, former Jeds include retired Army Maj. Gen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Singlaub </PERSON>, who has organized a controversial worldwide effort to support resistance groups against communism, and internationally known yachtsman <PERSON> Hod </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>, a retired Marine general. The late columnist <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> <PERSON> Alsop </PERSON> was a Jed. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Cyr </PERSON>, 66, of <LOCATION> Centreville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, said he only found out after the war that the headquarters of British Special Operations thought some of their messages were coming from the German Gestapo and so did not respond to requests for assistance, including arms drops. <PERSON> Cyr </PERSON>, who was sent behind enemy lines twice in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and later in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, said his biggest problem was communications. `` It could take all day to get the radio into the sidepockets of a bike and get out into the countryside to send a simple message,'' he said. In <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, he said, the mostly French-speaking Americans operated in villages and towns with Germans all around them. The Jeds tell the story of one American who did n't speak French and injured his back during the jump. He had to spend time in a German hospital, speaking very little, before a mission was flown in to rescue him. <PERSON> Cyr </PERSON> said he has some horrible memories, including holing up on a farm with 300 resistance fighters and ending up with only 15 survivors after Germans were led to the scene by a Frenchman. Retired Col. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Mills </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Fairfax </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, who worked with the Allied forces in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and with the Americans who went to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> but was not a <PERSON> Jed </PERSON> himself, is writing a book about the missions. Since the documents were declassified, <PERSON> Mills </PERSON> has spent three years going through hundreds of boxes stored in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archives </ORGANIZATION>. He said that despite the obvious danger of the missions, only a handful of the Jeds were killed. `` They were guerrillas. They had to design operations that would keep them alive,'' he said.
