<SECOND>AM-Mummy Savers,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Who Tested Mummy Provide New Hope For Decaying Relics</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARINA DEL REY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists who experimented with an ancient corpse nicknamed Lady X have developed a new type of museum case to protect from decay such priceless relics as mummies and the Dead Sea Scrolls. The technique involves construction of hermetically sealed display cases filled with inert nitrogen gas. A small-scale prototype of the case, which contains temperature and humidity sensors, a leak detector and almost no oxygen, was unveiled Tuesday during a seminar attended by 100 scientists, museum officials and Egyptian dignitaries. Lady X, a 3,000-year-old mummy, rested nearby in a less sophisticated case. Scientists at the <ORGANIZATION> Getty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> used cotton swabs to collect bacteria and fungi from her surface for use in tests that led to development of the new case. `` In the past, very little research has been done on the conservation of organic materials,'' said <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Monreal </PERSON>, director of the institute. Included among organic materials, he said, are mummies, parchment manuscripts, textiles and embroideries, artworks on paper and relics made of leather, bone or wood. The institute, part of the <ORGANIZATION> J. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Getty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION>, plans to build a full-size display case and test Lady X in it for one to three months, said research director <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Preusser </PERSON>. The mummy, a brown-skinned, 4-foot-10 woman believed to have been a commoner, was shipped here from <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> last September. Discovered near <LOCATION> Luxor </LOCATION> in the 1960s, she was the first mummy sent out of <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> since the remains of Pharaoh Ramses II were taken to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> in 1976 for radiation treatment to halt fungal decay. Once research is completed, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> will build cases so mummies of 27 pharaohs and queens discovered in 1881 can be placed on display for the first time, perhaps by May 1989, said <PERSON> Zahi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawass </PERSON>, director general of the <ORGANIZATION> Egyptian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Antiquities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. Plans to display 15 of those mummies last October were canceled to await results of the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> research, he added. He said <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s government has extended its original six-month contract with the institute for another six months to allow completion of research on Lady X, who was nicknamed by an Egyptian official. `` I'm afraid this mummy will stay here and ask for an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> green card,'' <PERSON> Hawass </PERSON> joked, referring to a temporary work permit. <PERSON> Monreal </PERSON> said the new case was designed to be built relatively inexpensively so any country can use it to preserve organic materials. He said the institute offered its findings to the <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Museum </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> if the museum wants to build cases to preserve the Dead Sea Scrolls. The leather and papyrus manuscripts were discovered in the 1940s and 1950s and contain all the books of the Old Testament except <PERSON> Esther </PERSON>. Lady X probably was about 40 years old when she did. She lived sometime during <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s New Kingdom period, from 1500 B.C. to 1050 B.C. <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> has thousands of such mummies. Most were commoners. The mummies were perfectly preserved for millenia in tombs. But after excavation, they became threatened by pollution, bacteria, fungi and changes in temperature, humidity and light. <PERSON> Getty </PERSON> scientists did n't take tissue samples from Lady X. Instead, the microbes they collected were grown on strips of parchment placed in glass vials. Growth of the microbes was tested under varying conditions of light, temperature, humidity and oxygen levels, said researcher <PERSON> Nieves </PERSON> <PERSON> Valentin </PERSON>.
