<HEAD>Special Forces Soldiers Indicted on Travel Vouchers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAYETTEVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eight soldiers who trained Jamaican troops after the 1983 <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> invasion have been indicted by a federal grand jury for allegedly submitting thousands of dollars in false travel vouchers to the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. The Special Forces soldiers from <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bragg </LOCATION>, who were temporarily housed in the Americana Hotel in <PERSON> Ochos </PERSON> <PERSON> Rios </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, allegedly conspired to receive two sets of receipts. One showed the amount actually paid for their rooms, $ 27.50; the second showed that the hotel received $ 55. The indictment, handed down Tuesday, said that just before or immediately after returning to <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bragg </LOCATION> in May 1984, the eight destroyed the receipts that reflected what was actually paid. They then filled out false travel vouchers that showed they paid the greater amount and were reimbursed, according to the indictment. Each of the eight was indicted on a single count of conspiring to defraud the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, along with a second count of submitting a false claim for reimbursement of lodging expenses. A spokesman for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney's Office in <LOCATION> Raleigh </LOCATION> said the conspiracy charge carries a maximum sentence of 10 years in prison, a fine of up to $ 250,000, or both. The false claim charge carries a maximum of five years in prison and a fine of up to twice what was taken, or $ 250,000, or both, the spokesman said. The indictment alleged that the eight were assigned in December 1983 to <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> to provide trained personnel to serve as security forces for the government of <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> following the invasion of that country two months before. The eight returned to <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bragg </LOCATION> in May 1984.
