<HEAD>U.S. And Laotian Soldiers Fail To Find Remains of MIAs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Laotian soldiers digging on their hands and knees scoured a remote hillside Wednesday where a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warplane crashed 22 years ago, but officials said they failed to find the remains of two missing American fliers. The soldiers searched the bamboo - and brush-covered hillside in <LOCATION> Savannakhet </LOCATION> province where the OV-1A Mohawk reconnaissance aircraft was shot down on March 15, 1966 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government is trying to resolve the fates of 555 Americans listed as missing in action in the <LOCATION> Indochina </LOCATION> war. `` There was an exhaustive search of the crash area from May 2 to 11 ... -LRB- but -RRB- no remains of the two crewmen aboard the aircraft ... were found,'' said <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> Petzing </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>. `` There was some danger posed by unexploded ordnance left over from the <LOCATION> Indochina </LOCATION> war period,'' <PERSON> Petzing </PERSON> said. `` Three cluster bombs and several live shells were exploded at the excavation site by <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> emergency ordnance disposal experts.'' Maj. <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Pfister </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, said the team returned to <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> with some pieces of wreckage from the Mohawk and a very small amount of personal effects. He said the soldiers toiled in dusty conditions and temperatures of more than 100 degrees, using simple tools to shovel out clumps of earth and fine metal screens to sift for remains. The 14 Americans stayed in tents at the crash site, about 95 miles east of <LOCATION> Savannakhet </LOCATION> city in southern <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Pfister </PERSON> said the Mohawk had taken off from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> air base at <LOCATION> Phu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bai </LOCATION> in central <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> on a mission involving interdiction of the <ORGANIZATION> Ho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trail </ORGANIZATION>, which communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> used to infiltrate men and supplies into U.S.-backed <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. He said another aircraft on that mission reported that one crewman parachuted out and landed near the area where the Mohawk crashed. <PERSON> Petzing </PERSON> said that as an expression of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s concern with <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION>' own humanitarian problems, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> team donated six months of medicine and equipment worth about $ 13,000 dollars to the <LOCATION> Sepone </LOCATION> district hospital for use by inhabitants of the crash area. It was the third such joint excavation in communist-ruled <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION>. The remains of 11 missing Americans were found in the first joint excavation in 1985, and eight others were found in the second dig in 1986. <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION> had promised a third dig in 1986, but a long period of inactivity followed until <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> agreed last August to consider <LOCATION> Vientiane </LOCATION>'s calls for humanitarian aid. In February, the Laotians handed over two boxes of remains they said were found in their recent excavations. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said they received exceptional cooperation from the Laotians. The American team was from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATI