rading data to the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> decreased by 7 percent and imports plummeted by 31 percent from 1982 through the first half of 1987. The declines came while overall trade was rising substantially. The interim report by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> did not say how much of the decline was due to the limited sanctions imposed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 over President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s veto. Those sanctions banned imports of agricultural products, coal, iron, steel and textiles, and exports of oil, arms, nuclear materials and computers, as well as new <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> loans. The report also noted that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> direct investment in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> declined by about 10 percent since 1982. About 80 percent of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s trade remains with six major industrial nations: the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> recently have decreased their share of trade, while <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has increased its share, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> found. <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> said the South African government remains intransigent, exercising what amounts to terrorism over its black majority despite the earlier sanctions by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. And he suggested that world attention to the problem has waned. `` I want to know what the South African government still has to do so the world would be filled with so much revulsion and outrage that it would move heaven and earth to rid the world of the scourge of apartheid,'' the Anglican archbishop said, comparing the government to that of <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` It sometimes takes our breath away, the things that the South African government has been able to get away with,'' he said. <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> contended that `` anything that has happened in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has happened because of pressure.'' He specifically cited the continued detention by the government of children as young as 7 and 8 years old, with some held more than a year and kept without contact from the outside. `` What must our people still suffer so that the world, recognizing their anguish, would then say we ca n't allow this to continue?'' <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> asked. Rep. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Gunderson </PERSON>, R-Wis., who supported the limited sanctions in 1986, said he was concerned that unilateral action by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> might have little impact without parallel moves by other major South African trading partners like <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> `` It would be far more effective if we had a global approach,'' <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> acknowledged. `` But who is likely to persuade them? No country is in a better position that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. ... The moral stand you take sends out ripples.'' In a speech at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> faulted the current leaders of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain <