<HEAD>Polish May Events Remind Both Sides of Stakes of Reform</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Poland, Bjt
^AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s worst labor unrest in nearly seven years reminded authorities that plans to reform the economy and political system are racing against a deadline of mounting public impatience. But the opposition learned that the public is not ready for a repeat of the nationwide strikes of 1980 that led to the birth of Solidarity. The walkouts that began April 25 among bus and tram drivers in the western Polish city of <LOCATION> Bydgoszcz </LOCATION> led to the sit-in strike by hundreds of <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> shipyard workers that ended Tuesday night in the <LOCATION> Baltic </LOCATION> port city. The workers' demands for higher pay and union freedoms echoed August 1980, when <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> was electrified by a sudden national labor revolt and the Eastern bloc's first independent trade union federation, Solidarity. The organization, formally banned after the imposition of martial law in 1981, claimed 10 million members _ nearly one out of three Poles _ and was far larger than the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- Party. The younger Poles who are most ready to storm the barricades did not experience the disappointment and trauma of martial law in the same way as their elders. When the <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> shipyard strike committee _ led behind the scenes by Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> _ agreed to discuss a compromise in which the strikers would give up a demand for the immediate recognition of Solidarity, it was the younger generation that balked. `` History does not like to repeat itself. And this was exactly what the aging veterans of Solidarity could not understand,'' said a commentary Wednesday by the state-run news agency <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION>. Although there were frequent expressions of concern and sympathy for the recent protests, the vast majority of society hung back from any overt moves to help the strikers. `` -LRB- The Poles -RRB- saw in 1981 that -LRB- pursuing strikes -RRB- was a cul-de-sac, given the geopolitical situation in this part of the world,'' said a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity. He said the strikes in 1980-81 led to Soviet-supported repression by the Polish government and further economic hardships for common Poles. Government spokesman <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON> said the recent unrest was instructive for the authorities and would cause them to redouble efforts to reform the economic and political systems. Indeed, one day after the last strike, the Polish parliament unanimously passed a program to speed up its plans to make the economy more efficient by giving it special powers to fire managers or take over enterprises that resist economic changes. But the diplomat said the authorities have already lost `` the hearts and minds'' of the new generation. `` Solidarity has not necessarily captured them either,'' he added. He said there was `` impressive but not overwhelming support from the rest of society,'' but that Solidarity calls for sympathy action `` were not taken up with alacrity.'' Official comments were quick to label the strikers' decision to leave the shipyard even without a settlement the end of Solidarity. `` The myth of Solidarity's might has fallen,'' the <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> commentary said. It `` turned out to be a small group which could not find support in big enterprises, including those in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>, and even in the <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> shipyard.'' But another Western diplomat said he thought it was too early to write Solidarity's obituary. He said the group will continue to exist `` because it continues to be a necessary focus for a whole band of postulates and opinions that exist among the Polish people.'' For Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, it was more a matter of timing. Despite official propaganda that portrayed him as the manipulator of events, he said repeatedly that the strike at the <LOCATION> Lenin </LOCATION> shipyard this time caught him by surprise and came `` too early'' to attract enough support to be effective. Public dissatisfaction is building, he said, and if authorities do not pursue reform more effectively _ including dialogue with Solidarity and other independent groups _ the final result will be `` bloody revolution.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniszewski </PERSON> covers <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>.
