<FIRST>r p AM-VotingBarriers     05-11 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Voting Barriers,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Poor, Minorities Disenfranchised By Voting Barriers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Discriminatory voter registration procedures are disenfranchising the poor, minority and disabled citizens throughout the country, directors of a private study said Wednesday. Among the practices are arbitrary registration hours, inconvenient registration locations, `` mysterious purging of voters without notice, denial of registration before an election,'' said a statement from Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>, D-Calif., who is the author of legislation to correct such practices The <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> in hearings in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> in 1984 and 1985 `` documented numerous examples of discrimintory practices,'' the group said. The commission also reviewed the registration systems in each state and the historical voting and registration practices. The report said in most states, local officials have `` wide discretion'' in setting times, places and conditions for people to register to vote. `` This discretion is often is exercised in ways which establish barriers to registration and voting,'' said the report. The restrictive practices `` have a disproportionately adverse effect on low-income, minority and disabled citizens,'' the report said. It cited the following examples: _ Limited registration sites affect poor people who do n't own cars. _ Limited hours for registration affect working people who ca n't get away from their jobs _ Many registration sites are inaccessible to the disabled. _ Failure to provide bilingual assistance affects low-income citizens and non-English speaking minorities. The Voting Rights Act of 1965 has eliminated the most blatant discrimination practices, but `` remnants of the old systems of disenfranchisement persist,'' the report said. Among the specific problems are refusal by local officials to designate sites in black commuinities for mobile registration units; requirement of excessive identification from black applicants; `` undue scrutiny'' of Hispanics and Asian-Americans to determine their citizenship; sites `` that require extraordinarily long trips'' and dual registration requirements for tribal and state elections for Native Americans. The commission recommended legislation to permit registration by mail, election-day registration, and a congressional investigation into denial of the right to vote for homeless people. <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>'s bill, pending in <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee, and a companion House bill by Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON>, D-Mich., generally parallels those recommendations The commission is sending a copy of its report to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the White House and the presidential candidates, seeking support for its proposals.
</TEXT>
