lion have resulted in inflation of more than 15 percent this year and prompted widespread grumbling from citizens and the official trade unions about the government program. The communique on Wednesday said leaders at Tuesday's meeting also debated personnel changes and formed a special committee to deal with such matters at the three-day conference opening May 20. But it did not reveal who made the report on personnel matters or say who will be on the committee. Western diplomats, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said they expected some changes in membership of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> at next week's conference. They described Tuesday's decisions as a modest step forward in dealing with the mounting political and economic crisis. Communist party leaders, including <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON> and <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>, have said in recent months they would like the party to retreat from day-to-day adminstrative duties and concentrate on ideological and political leadership of the country. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> has also declared readiness for dialogue with any Hungarian who is not opposed to socialism and <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>'s alliance with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>, a leading contender to succeed <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON> as party chief, has said the political future of the party leader may be up for debate at next week's conference. `` In the event that some 1,000 delegates attending the conference decide that personnel changes are necessary, and if these changes include the person of <PERSON> Janos </PERSON> <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON>, he will accept the decision,'' <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> told reporters while in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> last week. <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON> has said he would step down if asked, but he has shown little sign of wanting to do so. Hungarians will watch closely to see whether outspoken reformer