<HEAD>Labor Department To Monitor Pressures On Pension Fund Managers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> launched an effort Wednesday to ensure that pension fund managers who control a growing percentage of the nation's corporate stock are free from improper pressures in takeover battles. Over the next several months, department investigators will be monitoring how selected investment managers vote on takeover defenses and other issues that affect the value of stock, according to <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, assistant secretary of labor. The department's <ORGANIZATION> Pension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benefits </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> issued guidelines in February saying pension fund investment managers should keep the interests of the members of the fund in mind when voting proxies for shares in their care. The enforcement project is intended to see if the guidelines are being followed. `` We're not trying to come out pro-corporate management or pro any other party. The important thing is that pension funds not be viewed as tools or pawns of corporate management or any other party,'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said. There has been growing concern in recent years that investment managers have been subject to pressure from parties trying to block takeovers, such as corporate managers or union leaders, who have the ability to add to or take away from a fund manager's business. `` We want to make sure there's not undue influence, improper influence, that would adversely affect the economic interests of the plan,'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said. If the enforcement project turns up violations, investment managers could be subject to civil enforcement proceedings, <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said, adding, `` If the plan suffers an economic loss ... then there is personal liability.'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said he did not know how much abuse exists. However, a survey released in September by the <ORGANIZATION> Employee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benefit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a Washington-based, non-partisan research organization, showed that 65 percent of pension fund investment managers reported being pressured at least once in voting on corporate takeovers. `` The stakes are high in this area for a lot of parties. There's a great potential for abuse and we hear a lot of assertions ... We're trying to do a little bit of preventive medicine ... before abuse becomes widespread,'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said. The question of improper influence over fund managers has become more important as more companies call on shareholders to adopt poison pills and other measures designed to thwart corporate raiders. Pension funds controlled 24 percent of the nation's stock last year, up from 19 percent in 1980 and 10 percent in 1970. But, the percentages are significantly higher for stocks traded on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said, and pension funds own 60 percent of some companies, he said. The department estimates by the year 2000, pension funds are likely to control half the stock in all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies.
