<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nine astronauts who worked in Skylab, the only manned <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> space station, gathered Wednesday to celebrate its launch nearly 15 years ago and to urge a greater commitment to space exploration. `` Space is our frontier, and beginning its exploration may be our generation's greatest contribution to human history,'' said <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bean </PERSON>, commander of the second of three Skylab crews. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Carr </PERSON>, who headed the third mission, agreed, saying future space probes `` should avoid the 10 - to 12-day mindset and plan for the long haul. Bean, <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> and their seven colleagues joined dozens of engineers and other members of the Skylab team in observing the historic events following Skylab's launch aboard a Saturn V rocket on May 14, 1973, from <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. The three Skylab missions, from May 1973 to February 1974, resulted in significant information about bio-medicine, solar physics, astrophysics, engineering and technology, materials processing and other topics. But the Skylab team first had to overcome problems that threatened to jeopardize the mission before the astronauts stepped aboard. Ground crews noticed shortly after the launch that a meteorite and heat shield had ripped off and struck solar panels that were left improperly deployed. But ground crews managed to alter the lab's orbit and develop a shield that the first crew members, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerwin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> `` Pete'' <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Weitz </PERSON>, carried into space with them 11 days after the initial launch. The crew made a daring space walk to adjust the panels when they arrived and salvaged the mission. Other Skylab crew members were <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Garriott </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Lousma </PERSON>, who flew on the second mission, and <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pogue </PERSON>, on the third. Tuesday's conference, sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alabama </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION> as well as local space and aeronautics groups, was held at the <ORGANIZATION> Wernher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> von </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Braun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, named in honor of the former German rocket scientist who helped develop the American space program after World War II. The Skylab astronauts showed no reluctance to join a similar mission again. `` Eight of us got together after dinner Tuesday night and someone asked if we would volunteer to go to <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Kerwin </PERSON>, scientist pilot on the mission. `` Eight hands shot up as rapidly as possible.'' `` We would do it in a minute,'' said <PERSON> Carr </PERSON>, commander of the last mission. <PERSON> Kerwin </PERSON> said the nation's space program reached its peak in 1967, when it received 7 percent of the federal budget. He said it had been shrinking since then, now getting a fraction of 1 percent of the budget. `` I hope that's not permanent,'' he said. One thing that Skylab showed, <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> said, is that people can hold up in space longer than was thought. The first crew stayed aboard 28 days, the second 59 days, and the third 84 days. <PERSON> Carr </PERSON>, now an aerospace consultant in <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, said today's generation of space scientists should avoid `` reinventing the wheel. They would be remiss if they do n't take the lessons that have already been learned and re-apply them and build on that data.''
