<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday it would increase government payments to defense contractors for work in progress to help ease the burden of lining up financing to perform weapons work. The increase in the so-called progress payment percentage will apply to <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> contracts awarded on or after Oct. 1, the start of fiscal 1989, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said in a prepared statement. The progress payment rate for large contractors will be increased from 75 percent to 80 percent a month, while the rate for small business concerns will be hiked from 80 percent to 85 percent, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> added. The increase is the first since 1981 and follows two reductions in progress payment rates _ in 1985 and again in 1986. The move will cost the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> an estimated $ 500 million in fiscal 1989, but is justified because the current 75 percent rate is imposing `` an excessive financing burden on the defense industry,'' wrote <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Costello </PERSON>, the undersecretary of <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> for acquisition, who approved the change. Under longstanding practice, defense contractors are allowed to submit monthly bills for contract work in progress instead of waiting until all work is completed. That system of progress payments was developed as weapon systems grew larger and more complex, in many cases requiring years of work and straining the ability even of the biggest company to borrow enough money to keep assembly lines moving. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has never paid progress fees at the full contract rate, however. Currently, for large firms, it pays out a maximum 75 percent of the monthly bill. The remaining 25 percent is withheld pending deliveries, completion of contract work or final audits. The progress payment rate for large contractors has ranged as high as 90 percent in the early 1980's, when inflation was soaring in double digits, but held steady at 80 percent from 1968 to 1981. The last change in the rate _ dropping it from 80 percent to 75 percent _ occurred in 1986 at <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' direction in order to trim government spending to comply with the Gramm-Rudman balanced budget law. Unless <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> intervenes with new legislation, however, the Pentagon is no longer bound to keep the 75 percent rate. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, `` The 25 percent financing share now required of the defense industry is higher than historical levels and is not compatible with current interest rates and economic conditions.''
