<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Supporters of <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> say the Democratic presidential candidate was shortchanged in delegates he received at <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> district conventions. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> backers filed a formal challenge to the delegate selection process last week, as state party officials prepared for a state <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> committee meeting on Saturday to choose the last of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>' delegates to the Democratic National Convention in July in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. Supporters say <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> should have been allocated 12 national delegates instead of the seven he received, based on the results of county caucuses March 19. They also say <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> should have 10 delegates instead of 12, and Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> should have two instead of five. The number of uncommitted delegates would remain at two under the challenge. A total of 26 national delegates was selected April 22 at congressional district conventions. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> supporters also complain that the way delegates are chosen in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> is confusing and unduly complicated. `` It's an unfair process,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Meek </PERSON>, state coordinator for the <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> campaign. `` When you say ` caucus' to the average person, they say, ` What do you mean?' All we're asking for is what is fair.'' `` We're still formulating an answer to the challenge,'' said <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Scranton </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. `` We do n't know what that answer will be yet.'' The state party has until May 24 to rule on the <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> challenge. Delegates are selected to the national convention based on a process that started with 117 local caucuses, which chose the people who vote at the district conventions. The district conventions then selected 26 national delegates from the five congressional districts. The third and final step is the selection of 13 delegates at the state committee meeting. Those delegates will be chosen based on the results of the district conventions, with seven going to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and three each to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Beachy </PERSON>, former state party executive director who is acting as a consultant to the <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> campaign in the challenge, said the 26 national delegates selected at the district conventions should accurately reflect the results of the local caucuses under a party rule. That rule was not followed, he said. Candidates must receive at least 15 percent of the caucus votes before they can receive any delegates, according to the rules. <PERSON> Beachy </PERSON> says people were allowed to re-group at the district conventions and previously uncommitted delegates threw in with either <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> or <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>. Although <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> did not break the 15 percent threshold in the local caucuses in three congressional districts, he received one delegate from each of those districts after picking up uncommitted delegates at the district conventions. `` They should n't be allowed to re-group after the caucuses,'' <PERSON> Beachy </PERSON> said. `` The caucuses set what the -LRB- delegate -RRB- allocations should be.'' <LOCATION> Scranton </LOCATION> acknowledged there is a difference of opinion in interpretation of party rules. He also joined <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> supporters in their complaints about the complicated process. `` Anyone who has tried to administer this, from the county selection on up to the national selection, is painfully aware of how complicated it is,'' <PERSON> Scranton </PERSON> said.
