<HEAD>Hodel Attacks `Pure Racism' in Bill on Indian Adoption and Custody
Laws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Interior Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> on Wednesday attacked a bill to amend Indian adoption and child custody laws, saying it contains provisions that smack of `` pure racism.'' <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> wrote Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Hawaii </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Indian Affairs, that he was `` extremely alarmed'' about some portions of the bill. Assistant Interior Secretary <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> Swimmer </PERSON>, a former principal chief of the Cherokee Nation who is in charge of <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> affairs, asked the committee to hold up action on the bill until the department could propose a substitute. <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> said one provision of the bill gives parents no right to object to a tribe's attempt to transfer custody or adoption cases from state to tribal court unless the objection is `` consistent with the best interests of the child as an Indian.'' `` The provision ignores all other aspects of the child's status as a human being. That, in my view, is pure racism,'' <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> said. Current law permits tribes to claim jurisdiction in adoption and custody cases only for children of enrolled members, but the bill would extend that jurisdiction to children whose `` parents and other ancestors of the child may have had no connection with the tribe, perhaps for years or even generations,'' <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> said. In his testimony at a hearing of the committee, <PERSON> Swimmer </PERSON> said, `` We do not believe that Indian parents and their children should have to return to the reservation of their tribe, which is often in another state, for a court proceeding concerning the child.'' `` We strongly oppose the expansion of the definition of Indian child and recommend that the definition should not only contain a membership requirement but also that the domicile of the birthparent or parents is in Indian country,'' Swimmer said. If the family does not live in Indian country _ on a reservation _ then state courts should have jurisdiction, following certain guidelines of federal law for placement of children in foster homes and adoptions `` unless the best interest of the child requires a different placement,'' Swimmer said.
