<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A second luxury yacht seized for carrying tiny amounts of drugs remained in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Customs custody Wednesday, as the crackdown under the new `` zero tolerance'' policy continued. And a jetliner owned by <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Avianca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> was seized Wednesday following the investigation that began when cocaine was found aboard it. The seizures come a day after the $ 2.5 million <ORGANIZATION> Ark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> was allowed to sail away following payment of a fine. The $ 600,000 Ms. <PERSON> Mindy </PERSON>, a boat used to entertain customers of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>'s Cigarette Racing Team, was boarded Monday as it returned from the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION> and docked in <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salerno </LOCATION>. A search by Customs agents turned up cocaine residue on a dollar bill and traces of marijuana in a plastic bag. `` It's simply being detained and checked right now for narcotics, and a determination will be made later'' whether to confiscate the ship, <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON> said Wednesday. Neither the ship's captain, <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaver </PERSON>, nor his unidentified first mate, who were the only people aboard the boat registered out of <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, were charged with drug possession. <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON> said the plane's seizure also was `` consistent with zero tolerance.'' The new, tough policy allows the confiscation of a boat, plane or other conveyance if it carries any amount of drugs, no matter how small. The plane's seizure was based on a 35.8-pound cocaine shipment found March 27, <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON> said, adding that the delay was to allow for a full investigation. <ORG