<HEAD>China Has Ended Pork Rationing, USDA Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has ended pork rationing, according to Chinese officials, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. `` A Chinese agriculture official privately stated that pork rationing in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> had stopped being enforced,'' the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said in a report `` Other officials said that pork rationing had ended throughout the country, though no official announcement has confirmed this.'' <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> began rationing pork in most major cities last fall in response to shortages. Pork traditionally supplies about 80 percent of the total animal protein in the Chinese diet. `` The pork shortages that led to the rationing did not, however, affect <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s ability to supply hogs to its limited export markets -LRB- primarily <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> -RRB-,'' the report said. `` In fact, the country has had a surplus of hogs for export to <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, but increases in hog trade between the two countries have been limited by a Chinese export quota.'' The report said an end to rationing `` shows that Chinese agricultural officials believe the tight pork supply situation is now being resolved'' as producers respond to lower feed prices, higher pork prices and government incentives to promote larger production. `` It also is an indication that many urban consumers are willing to pay more for the higher-quality, free market pork instead of enduring the cheaper, fattier meat that has been sold at lower prices in state markets,'' the report said.
