<HEAD>Aloha Pilots Describe In-Flight Ordeal With Gaping Hole in
Fuselage</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New throughout to UPDATE with FAA tape recording</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The pilots of Aloha Flight 243 knew they had problems as they tried to land their plane with a large section of its cabin wall and ceiling torn away, but for a time they thought their predicament was even worse, it was revealed Wednesday. According to a tape of radio communications from the crippled <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737, the pilots were certain as they approached the airport on the island of <LOCATION> Maui </LOCATION> that the nose landing gear had failed to deploy. This would have made landing the severely damaged aircraft especially dangerous, according to aviation experts. `` Be advised we have no nose gear. We are landing without a nose gear,'' co-pilot <PERSON> Madeline </PERSON> `` Mimi'' <PERSON> Tompkins </PERSON> told the <LOCATION> Maui </LOCATION> airport tower in a strained but controlled voice as Capt. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Schornstheimer </PERSON> struggled to keep the aircraft aloft. `` We'll need all the -LRB- emergency -RRB- equipment you got,'' she continued, although giving little hint as to how serious Flight 243's predicament really was last April 28 in the skies above <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. Only seconds before the plane landed on the runway did the controller tell the pilots the landing gear actually was deployed. They possibly had been misled by a false instrument reading. The tape was played Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, the same day that Schornstheimer and <PERSON> Tompkins </PERSON> were honored by the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for their heroics. They met with Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Tuesday. <PERSON> Schornstheimer </PERSON> told the pilots group that training and teamwork allowed him and Ms. <PERSON> Tompkins </PERSON> `` to stay calm and fly the airplane'' as they rapidly descended from 24,000 feet to a safe landing with a 20-foot section of the cabin exposed to the sky, one engine out and another engine damaged by flying debris. A flight attendant was swept to her death during the flight. The two pilots were presented the Superior Airmanship Award from the 40,000-member pilots union for landing the plane safely without any additional casualties. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> tape provided little hint of the drama that was unfolding aboard the aircraft. The plane was just approaching the south coast of <LOCATION> Maui </LOCATION> when the first word of trouble aboard the plane reached the control tower. `` <LOCATION> Maui </LOCATION> tower, Aloah 243. We're inbound for a landing,'' Ms. <PERSON> Tompkins </PERSON> advised matter of factly. After providing the plane's position, she added, `` We are unpressurized, declaring an emergency.'' The tower directed another plane away from the runway and advised that Flight 243 had a clear, straight approach and emergency vehicles would be waiting. While Schornstheimer flew the plane, Ms. <PERSON> Tompkins </PERSON> handled the radio. While they must have been aware of the huge missing section of the cabin wall and ceiling, they never suggested the extent of the plane's damage to the control tower during the 10 minute and 18 second descent and landing. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> suggested that the controller had no need to know the information and the crew probably was busy otherwise. Ms. <PERSON> Tompkins </PERSON> at one point advised there were injuries on board. How many? `` We have no idea. We can not communicate with our flight attendants,'' she replied, the strain in her voice now showing. Muffled noise could be heard in the background as the wind whipped through the cockpit _ its door torn off by the rapid depressurization. The pilots later explained they had to resort to hand signals to communicate. As Schornstheimer struggled to keep the plane flying on a direct path to the <LOCATION> Maui </LOCATION> airport, Ms. <PERSON> Tompkins </PERSON> advised that the cockpit instruments indicated the nose landing gear had not deployed. Two minutes later there came good news. `` Just for your information, the gear appears down. The gear appears down,'' the tower informed Flight 243 seconds before it landed. `` Aloha 243, just shut it down where you are. Everything's fine. ... The fire trucks are on the way,'' the controller then said. During the <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION> ceremony, <PERSON> Schornstheimer </PERSON> said, `` What seemed like a short time to <PERSON> Mimi </PERSON> and I because of our busy cockpit duties must have seemed like an eternity to our passengers and flight attendants.'' Ms. <PERSON> Tompkins </PERSON> praised the captain, an 11-year veteran of <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION>. `` <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> analyzed the situation confronting us and he reacted,'' she said. `` All of his decisions were the right ones.'' Despite the experience, she said she was eager to return to the cockpit: `` I ` m looking forward to going back to <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> and flying again.''
