<HEAD>House OKs Pentagon Spending Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To update with Senate vote on breaching SALT II limits,
INSERTS new 7th graf, ``The Senate''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House cast aside President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s objections Wednesday and passed a <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> budget bill that restricts his arms control policies and Star Wars programs The 252-172 decision in the Democratic-controlled chamber went largely along party lines. The bill will eventually be sent to a conference committee to be reconciled with the different <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget measure now on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, voted Wednesday for a $ 4.55 billion Star Wars budget, narrowly rejecting a move to cut deeply into <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s cherished anti-missile research program The House bill authorizes the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> to spend $ 299.5 billion in the fiscal year starting Oct. 1, the same total as the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> plan and the amount <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> approved last December in an agreement with congressional leaders aimed at reducing federal budget deficits. The current budget is about $ 299 billion. But the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> added a ban on any Star Wars tests that violate the so-called `` narrow'' interpretation of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty, and also voted against buying any nuclear weapons that violate the numerical limits in the unratified 1979 SALT II nuclear arms treaty. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, by a 51-45 margin, voted Wednesday afternoon to kill a provision in that chamber's bill that would also ban weapons beyond the SALT II limits. The House also added a directive telling <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to order the military into the fight against illegal drug smuggling. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is likely to consider a similar proposal. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> opposes both arms restrictions and is also unhappy with the $ 3.5 billion approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Initiative </ORGANIZATION>, as Star Wars is formally known. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had wanted $ 4.8 billion for <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wars </ORGANIZATION> next year, compared with the current SDI budget of $ 3.9 billion. In a letter to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said he was `` deeply disappointed'' by the chamber's actions and said the restrictions `` would seriously undermine our position in negotiations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and -LRB- would -RRB- hold back the progress of the Strategic Defense Initiative.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said he wants progress in nuclear arms control, but added, `` We can not do it alone. It is time for the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to step up to these responsibilities and pass a defense authorization bill that will strengthen our security.'' But Rep. <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON>, D-Wis., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` I do n't believe the president has any reason to be upset I think it's a good bill. We gave the president a lot of what he wanted.'' Hours before the final <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> vote, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 50-48 against a deep reduction in Star Wars. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> defeated a proposal by Sen. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>., to reduce the SDI budget to about $ 3.8 billion and devote the extra $ 750 million to the space shuttle and a space station <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>'s loss was similar to his defeats in each of the past two years, when he failed by a single vote to slash the SDI budget. Last year, Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> cast the tie-breaking vote in his role as the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s presiding officer. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has consistently scaled back <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s annual requests for sharp increases in spending for the 5-year-old program SDI program. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> has said he would recommend a <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> veto of the entire <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget bill unless <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> votes enough money for Star Wars. <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> argued that `` it's going to be very, very difficult to get that space station going unless we give it some more money. ... What's the higher priority here, the space station and the shuttle or SDI? The space station has a lot of defense implications. ... Dollars are scarce.'' But Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Warner </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Va </LOCATION>., said <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>'s proposal `` would be very detrimental to the defense budget. Originally, Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, D-Wis., simply proposed reducing the proposed SDI budget from $ 4.6 billion to $ 3.9 billion, but that lost on a 66-29 vote While the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> measure restricts <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s arms control policies and Star Wars, it granted <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s request for spending for a vast variety of weapons. That total includes 180 F-16 jet fighter planes, 84 F-A-18 jets, 42 F-15 jets, a dozen F-14 jets, three new <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> destroyers, two more attack submarines, one Trident missile-firing sub, the first of the new `` Seawolf'' class subs and 611 M-1 tanks.
