negotiator named. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Queen <PERSON> Margrethe </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> turned the struggle to form a new Danish government into a battle royal on Wednesday when she named a neutral politician to lead coalition negotiations. Her unexpected choice of <PERSON> Svend </PERSON> <PERSON> Jakobsen </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman since 1981, upset Prime Minister <PERSON> Poul </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON>'s hopes to quickly reassemble his coalition of four center-right parties following parliamentary elections on Tuesday. Normally the chief negotiator, called `` the royal investigator,'' is the person most likely to become prime minister. But <PERSON> Jakobsen </PERSON>, 53, has said he does not want the job of prime minister. The pro-NATO <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> gambled on an early election after failing to stop a resolution in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> last month which tightened enforcement of <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s peacetime ban on nuclear weapons, a measure seen as a threat to <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> strategy. Election analysts said elections Tuesday for the 179-member Folketing, or parliament, showed a modest shift to the right and strengthened the parties giving the Western alliance unqualified support. But the inconclusive results left the political field open to both the government and the socialist opposition bloc to woo the <ORGANIZATION> Social-Liberal </ORGANIZATION> party, which holds the balance of power. The issue of <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s relations with <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> faded in the political confusion and uncertainty. <PERSON> Margrethe </PERSON> assigned <PERSON> Jakobsen </PERSON> to discuss a national policy agenda with the eight parties in the Folketing as a prelude to formation of a governing coalition. Emerging from <LOCATION> Amalienborg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palace </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jakobsen </PERSON> pledged to `` strive to be totally neutral'' in searching `` for a government program supported by a broad majority.'' <PERSON> Jakobsen </PERSON> was nominated by the socialist opposition to block <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> from the position. <PERSON> Jakobsen </PERSON> won the backing of the Social-Liberals. <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> submitted his resignation to the queen earlier Wednesday, a formal step to launch coalition jockeying. The monarch then held consultations with all the party leaders. After a second meeting with the queen in seven hours, <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> said a majority supported <PERSON> Jakobsen </PERSON> to conduct the political talks, although he said he had `` strong reservations'' about using the office of parliamentary chairman `` in this political game.'' <PERSON> Jakobsen </PERSON> is a former finance minister in a Social Democratic government. But his present position in the legislature is supposed to be above partisan politics. <PERSON> Jakobsen </PERSON> told reporters he would begin separate meetings with the parties on Thursday. Earlier, <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> said the first aim of negotiations should be to resolve the row which led to the election, the first vote in four decades to be fought on a foreign policy issue. He indicated he wants to revise the resolution, which requires the government to advise each visiting warship that nuclear weapons are barred from Danish ports. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> say the resolution undermines their standing refusal to confirm or deny the presence of nuclear arms on military vessels. White House spokesman <PERSON> Roman </PERSON> <PERSON> Popadiuk </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Wednesday that once a new Danish government is formed, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will discuss with it the controversy over nuclear-armed ships in Danish waters. `` We have always had an excellent relationship with the