<SECOND>AM-Chernobyl,0731</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Says Chernobyl Left Psychological Scars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KIEV, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists said Wednesday that Soviets still suffer psychological scars from the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear disaster more than two years after it took place. Soviet and Western scientists could reach no consensus on the number of deaths that eventually may be linked to the explosion and fire that destroyed the No. 4 reactor at the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> power plant on April 26, 1986. An <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> doctor said cases of leukemia may begin to appear in one to three years. A Soviet scientist said the number of voluntary abortions in areas of <LOCATION> Byelorussia </LOCATION> near the plant increased 20 percent in the months after the accident. At least 31 people were killed at the plant 80 miles north of <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION>, capital of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>. A huge cloud of invisible radiation spread over <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and eventually worked its way around the world. Wednesday was the first day of three days devoted to a conference on medical consequences of the disaster. It brought more than 160 Soviet scientists together with delegates from 24 foreign countries. `` The accident was very severe but the wounds are healing,'' said <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Blix </PERSON>, general director of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. He said nuclear plants remain a feasible source of electricity despite the accident. <PERSON> Yevgeny </PERSON> <PERSON> Chazov </PERSON>, the Soviet health minister, said in an opening statement: `` Soviet scientists have no reason to conceal anything about the accident.'' Several Soviet delegates said the nation must combat what they called `` radiophobia,'' an unreasonable fear of nuclear power. <PERSON> Oles </PERSON> <PERSON> Pyatak </PERSON>, deputy director of the Soviet Center for Radiation Medicine, said scientists had noted increases in tension and intestinal disorders attributable to stress, and the unwillingness of some couples to have children. <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> Knizhnikov </PERSON>, who heads a radiation-safety laboratory, said rumors arose periodically about the Chernobyl plant leaking radiation again. Reports in the official press have said public opposition halted construction of nuclear plants near <LOCATION> Odessa </LOCATION> in the southern <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Byelorussian </LOCATION> capital of <LOCATION> Minsk </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Krasnodar </LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Knizhnikov </PERSON> told reporters of a 20 percent increase in voluntary abortions in areas of <LOCATION> Byelorussia </LOCATION> just north of <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> following the accident. He said there was no evidence of an increase in spontaneous abortions or birth defects, and virtually no chance any children would have been born deformed. The high rate of abortions continued through 1986 but the number then returned to normal, he said. Specialists have said the disaster could add 30,000 cancer deaths to the 600 million expected in the next 50 years, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gale </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> doctor who helped treat the worst cases of radiation sickness. Half the extra cases would be in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, 40 percent in the rest of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the remaining 10 percent in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, he said. <PERSON> Gale </PERSON> emphasized that the figures were estimates and said: `` My own feeling is that they may be on the high side, maybe by a factor of 10.'' An increase in leukemia also might be noticeable in one to three years among the 135,000 people who were evacuated from an 18-mile zone around the plant, <PERSON> Gale </PERSON> said. An extra 100 cases would be significant and easily detectable, he said, and `` one may be able to precisely identify the cases caused by radiation.'' Some other American doctors disputed that. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Mettler </PERSON>, a radiologist and specialist in nuclear medicine at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION>, said there is no way to determine the cause of a particular case of cancer. Because of a lack of information about how much and what kinds of radiation people were exposed to, firm conclusions about the medical effects would be difficult to reach, he said. Soviet officials said they had not been prepared to deal with the Chernobyl accident and did not have enough trained workers or reliable equipment to monitor the radiation. The accident was not even reported until three days after it happened, when <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> detected high radiation levels and demanded an explanation. Their Western colleagues said the Soviets have done a good job since. Officials of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said modifications of <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> nuclear plants now under way would prevent another accident of the Chernobyl type.
