<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>'s million-dollar-a-day lottery was revived late Wednesday after a 24-hour shutdown following the discovery that tickets could be bought after the winning numbers were announced. The company that provided new computers for the lottery `` assured us the problems have been fixed,'' said <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Zieman </PERSON>, assistant chief of the lottery unit of the Division of Special Revenue. Lottery officials said parts of the 2,200-terminal system were operating at 7:30 p.m. but did not know how long it would take to get all 2,200 terminals back on line. The new equipment went on line Sunday. The games were suspended Tuesday evening. The flaw in the system was demonstrated by two <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> ticket agents who saw Monday's televised drawing then played the winning numbers, officials said. The machines gave them tickets with numbers dated Monday instead of Tuesday. The pair, <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gilberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pardo </PERSON>, startled lottery officials Tuesday when they revealed what had happened and handed back $ 16,500 in checks that had just been made out in their names. Lottery unit spokeswoman <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said she did not know whether there were any other such incidents. Officials say codes of winning tickets can be checked if a problem is suspected. The state operates daily lottery and Play Four games and twice-weekly Lotto games with drawings on Tuesdays and Fridays. Tuesday's drawings were held and winners' tickets will be honored when the system resumes operating, said <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, chief of the Special Revenue lottery unit. The state sells $ 8 million in tickets a week and has a net weekly profit of $ 3 million, <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said. The mixup compounded the headaches of the Division of Special Revenue, which was forced to shut down two jai alai frontons because of strike by players. The state gets $ 55,000 a day from jai alai wagering, officials say. Earlier Wednesday, some lottery agents reported unhappy customers. `` They're very angry about it,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shoztic </PERSON>, manager of <ORGANIZATION> Bull </ORGANIZATION>'s Head News and Variety in <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>. `` They think the store owners have something to do with it and do n't realize it's someone else's problem,'' <PERSON> Shoztic </PERSON> said. `` A few have said they would play in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said the contract with the company that runs the lottery system, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Instrument </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Hunt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, stipulates that the company will be penalized when the system is down for the amount of the state's lost profits. General Instrument took over the system from <ORGANIZATION> G-Tech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Providence </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION>, when it was awarded a five-year, $ 40 million contract in December. General Instrument's bid was $ 11 million lower than <ORGANIZATION> G-Tech </ORGANIZATION>'s, according to <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>. General Instrument also runs the Off-Track Betting computer and ran the state's lottery system when it was begun in the early 1970s, he said. General Instrument officials did not immediately return calls placed to their <LOCATION> Wethersfield </LOCATION> office. The company also provides equipment for the 1,200-terminal <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> lottery. Officials there said they experienced problems when the system went on line in 1986 but did not have to shut it down.
