 About 50 <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> students, most of them black, ended an overnight `` study-in'' Wednesday, saying the dean had agreed to some of their demands for recruiting more minority professors. `` We feel we were very successful over the last 24 hours,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which staged the protest in the outer office of <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> Dean <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Vorenberg </PERSON>. The students had demanded that additional black professors be hired and that <PERSON> Vorenberg </PERSON>, who is retiring, be replaced by a black professor. They remained at <PERSON> Vorenberg </PERSON>'s office overnight. <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON> said the dean agreed to seven of 12 demands, including establishment of a fellowship to encourage blacks to teach at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>; a policy statement expressing commitment to diversity in hiring, and a broader role for students in searching for and hiring minority faculty. <PERSON> Vorenberg </PERSON> did not immediately return telephone calls for comment. <PERSON> Vorenberg </PERSON> said he could not agree to demands to hire a tenured black female professor by 1989 or to increase the number of tenured faculty by 20 positions and filling them with professors from diverse backgrounds, <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Vorenberg </PERSON> also said he had no ability to fulfill the students' demand that he be replaced by <PERSON> Derrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, a black professor at the law school, the student leader said <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> 