<HEAD>Seven Charged With Bombing Capitol, Other Buildings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with background on defendants, more
details, CORRECTS date of Israeli Aircraft bombing</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Seven members of a radical leftist group that used `` armed propaganda'' to protest government policies are charged with setting off bombs in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Capitol and seven other locations, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. The seven defendants are charged with conspiring to set off a bomb that blew a hole in a wall outside the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> chamber on Nov. 7, 1983, and damaged five paintings, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> said in a statement. The Capitol bomb also blew doors off the hinges outside the office of Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, then the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> minority leader and now majority Explosives were also detonated at three Washington-area military installations and four locations in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> between 1983 and 1985, including the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> office on <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and the Patrolmen's <ORGANIZATION> Benevolent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> office as part of the group's campaign of `` armed propaganda,'' <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> said The bombings damaged the buildings but did not injure anyone. The indictment was unsealed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on the same day that one of the defendants, <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Buck </PERSON>, 40, was convicted in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> of murder, armed robbery and racketeering in two 1981 armored truck robberies that resulted in the deaths of two guards and two <LOCATION> Nyack </LOCATION>, N.Y policemen. Ms. <PERSON> Buck </PERSON> drove a getaway car in the unsuccessful robbery of a Brink's armored truck carrying $ 1.6 million in <LOCATION> Nanuet </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> on Oct. 20, 1981. <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, 41, one of the seven named in the April 20 indictment, is serving a sentence for harboring Ms. Buck when she was a fugitive wanted for the Brinks heist. <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> also was sentenced last year to 40 years imprisonment for illegally buying guns in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> in 1983. Federal authorities said they waited to unseal the five-count indictment until Ms. <PERSON> Buck </PERSON>'s trial had ended in federal court in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. All but one of the defendants named in the five-count indictment unsealed Wednesday are in custody on other charges, federal officials said. <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Duke </PERSON>, the seventh defendant, is a fugitive, officials said. <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> fled while awaiting trial on similar charges. The indictment identified the defendants as members of a group that variously called itself the <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fighting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unit </ORGANIZATION> and the Red Guerrilla Resistance. The Armed Resistance Unit claimed responsibility for the Capitol bombing to protest the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion of <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION> and involvement of Marines in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. Other defendants named were: <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitehorn </PERSON>, <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON>, <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Blunk </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Berkman </PERSON>. Besides the Capitol bombing, the group is charged with setting off a bomb outside the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> War </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McNair </ORGANIZATION> here on April 26, 1983, the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> on Aug. 18, 1983 and the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Officers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> on April 20, 1984. Bombs were also placed at the Federal Building on <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, on Jan. 28, 1983; the <ORGANIZATION> Israeli </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> building in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on April 5, 1984; and the South African consulate in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Sept. 26, 1984. The bombing of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrolmen </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Benevolent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> occurred on Feb. 23, 1985 The indictment charged the defendants with conspiracy, malicious damage of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> property and aiding and abetting. As part of the conspiracy, the indictment charged, the group conducted surveillances of other potential bombing targets including: the Old Executive Office Building next to the White House; the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> office of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>; the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Naval Academy in <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION>, Md.; and the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Aberdeen </ORGANIZATION> Proving Ground in <LOCATION> Aberdeen </LOCATION>, Md Explosives and weapons, including dynamite, water gel, and other material were stored in a <LOCATION> Cherry </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> storage bin and in a garage in <LOCATION> Doylestown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, the indictment said. The blast in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Capitol occurred at about midnight and blew a hole in the wall across a corridor from the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> chamber. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> concluded that three or four pounds of dynamite with a dual-release timer was placed beneath a bench in an alcove in the corridor outside the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> chamber. It caused numerous cracks in the walls and the ornate ceiling of the corridor but did not leave any lasting structural damage to the Capitol. The indictment did not identify which members of the conspiracy set off the bomb in the Capitol. After the bombing, a communique was mailed to <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and a local public radio station, <ORGANIZATION> WAMU </ORGANIZATION>, that said: `` We purposely aimed our attack at the institutions of imperialist rule rather than at individual members of the ruling class. We did not choose to kill any of them this time. But their lives are not sacred,'' the indictment said. Credit was also claimed in communiques or calls to news organizations for the other bombings to dramatize the group's political goals, the indictment said In his statement, <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> said the defendants were charged with being part of `` a secret organization which described itself as ` a communist politico-military organization' and which operated under the names <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fighting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unit </ORGANIZATION> and the Red Guerrilla Resistance.'' To protest government foreign and domestic policies, the members of the group `` would plan and carry out acts of violence, which they called ` armed propaganda,' including the bombing of various government and private buildings and property.'' The indictment charged that the members of the group used multiple aliases derived from the names of babies who died in the late 1940s and early 1950s to obtain false passports, driver's licenses as well as to get jobs, buy firearms and impersonate police officers The group armed itsef with <PERSON> Uzi </PERSON> submachine guns, shotguns, handguns, silencers and such accessories as bulletproof body armor. <PERSON> Berkman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Blunk </PERSON> used a bogus search warrant to stage a Sept. 2, 1984 armed robbery of a <LOCATION> Cromwell </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, supermarket, the indictment said. Other potential targets said to be subjects of surveillance were the Cuban <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> and the law offices of <PERSON> Smathers </PERSON>, <PERSON> Symington </PERSON> and <PERSON> Herlong </PERSON>, both in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Summit Aviation in <LOCATION> Middletown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Del. </LOCATION>, was also the subject of surveillance and training exercises for the bombing missions, the indictment charged. <PERSON> Whitehorn </PERSON>, <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> and Buck were charged with conspiracy, while all seven defendants were charged with malicious destruction of property in connection with the bombings of the Capitol and the three <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> military facilities. `` Let this be a warning to those who seek to influence the policies of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> government through violence and terrorism that we will seek unrelentingly to bring them to justice,'' <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> said in his statement. `` Those who attack our sacred institutions of government and seek to destroy the symbols of our democratic system ultimately will have to pay the price.'' <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON>, 32, and <PERSON> Blunk </PERSON>, 30, both of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, were sentenced to 58 years imprisonment for possession of 600 pounds of weapons and explosives seized during their arrest Nov. 29, 1985 in <LOCATION> Cherry </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J </LOCATION>. They were arrested while placing the explosives into a rented storage bin. <PERSON> Berkman </PERSON>, a physician, was sentenced to 10 years in prison last year by a <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> federal judge for possesion of explosives, weapons and false identity cards. <PERSON> Whitehorn </PERSON>'s was convicted of making false identity cards and possessing firearms. Buck, meanwhile, faces a maximum life sentence for her participation in the two Brink's robbberies in 1981. She and <PERSON> Mutulu </PERSON> <PERSON> Shakur </PERSON> were also convicted of murder in death of a Brink's guard killed during a June, 1981 armored truck robbery in the <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION>. The robberies were part of a string of attempted robberies and robberies in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>.
