<HEAD>Film Industry Wants More Controls on Cable TV `Monopoly'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, ``Before cable...,'' to clarify attribution.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The president of the <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> urged <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday to rein in some of the cable television industry's power to control the entertainment marketplace. But leaders of the cable TV industry dismissed the movie industry's concerns and rejected charges that cable TV has become an unregulated monopoly. At a hearing marked by a few lively exchanges, <ORGANIZATION> MPAA </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Valenti </PERSON> sparred with <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Turner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Malone </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Tele-Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest cable company. `` Cable is no longer a babe in swaddling clothes,'' <PERSON> Valenti </PERSON> told members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on telecommunications, which is looking into the effects of cable deregulation. Cable TV, he said, has grown into a multibillion-dollar industry dominated by several large companies. `` Consumers are held hostage by their cable system. They have no alternative. They can either commit suicide or go bowling,'' said <PERSON> Valenti </PERSON>, who represents the major <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> studios and independent producers. <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> and <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> defended their industry, saying it has brought more than 50 basic channels and more than a dozen pay channels to television viewers in more than half the country. `` Before cable, we had the three big networks and they dominated what people saw. Now there are the three networks and more than 50 cable channels,'' <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> said. More than 80 percent of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s TV households can receive cable, and about 52 percent of all households subscribe. The steady increase in cable subscribership and in the amount of cable-exclusive programming has cut into the audience of the broadcast networks and the receipts of movie theaters. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fritts </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION>, said `` the cable industry has become the mouse that roared,'' able to raise rates at will and decide what broadcast signals to carry. <PERSON> Fritts </PERSON> urged <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to pass a law requiring cable companies to carry local broadcast signals and prohibit cable companies from showing any syndicated program for which a local broadcaster has purchased exclusive rights. As cable's clout has grown, it has been winning contracts away from the broadcast networks to carry more and more major sports events, and Rep. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Eckart </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, wondered whether in the future average sports fans will have to subscribe to cable to watch their home teams play. <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> suggested that while <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> could pass a law to protect broadcast coverage of sports events, it would be more prudent to `` wait to see what the free market does.'' <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> disputed <PERSON> Valenti </PERSON>'s claim that cable TV is a monopoly. For movies, he said, consumers can go to the theater, rent video cassettes or watch them on the broadcast networks. <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> also defended the investment his company and other large cable companies have made in industry programming ventures, saying that without this investment many of these channels would have gone out of business. He cable companies helped shore up The Discovery Channel and Turner's enterprise. <PERSON> Valenti </PERSON>, however, said such investments give cable companies incentive to carry on their systems the services in which they have an equity stake, denying viewers other programming choices. `` These monopolies can decide what the consumer is going to see,'' <PERSON> Valenti </PERSON> said.
