<HEAD>East St. Louis Goes On Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELLEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The city of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> endangers its police force by failing to equip officers properly, a prosecutor said Wednesday at the opening of a trial on criminal charges of reckless conduct against the city. But Mayor <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Officer </PERSON> countered in afternoon testimony: `` I know of no officer of the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> police department required to go to work if they felt their safety was endangered.'' The <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> city, plagued by unemployment, crime and a growing municipal debt, is accused of failing to supply its seven-member patrol force with properly working radios and cars. Officials said it was the first <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> city to be tried on criminal charges. Convictions would carry fines of $ 1,000 on each of nine misdemeanor counts, filed Feb. 22 by the <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clair </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> state's attorney. State's Attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Baricevic </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Robert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> LeChien </ORGANIZATION> that some police had bought their own radios and that detectives had used their own cars. The city `` was aware of the situation and recklessly ignored'' it, <PERSON> Baricevic </PERSON> said. The city had the money to correct the problems but failed to do so, he said. He said he planned to call about 30 witnesses. The mayor testified the police-radio problems were routine. `` They are mechanical equipment. They are manmade; they break down,'' he said. He contended some of the vehicle problems were due to abuse by the police. <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> contended Wednesday that there were no local, state or federal regulations saying municipalities must provide officers with radios. Officer <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Waggaman </PERSON>, a 16 -LCB- - year <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> police veteran, testified that he felt endangered by problems with the radios and cars <PERSON> Waggaman </PERSON> said he bought his own portable radio in 1983 because the police radio did not transmit or receive properly. He said he was not reimbursed. <PERSON> Waggaman </PERSON> said he informed his shift commander repeatedly of the problems, which included cars with bald tires and low oil and without spotlights. During cross examination, <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> said there were no regulations to define what a `` properly equipped'' vehicle was. `` It's a luxury, is it not?'' <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Waggaman </PERSON>, referring to the radios. `` It's for the convenience of the officer.'' <PERSON> Waggaman </PERSON> said he knew of no regulations governing the equipment. <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> <PERSON> Malone </PERSON>, a former alderman and former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, testified that Police Chief <PERSON> Isadore </PERSON> <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON> told the panel on numerous occasions that new police equipment was needed. Chambers has said that while the force has six radios for its patrol cars, he often had as many as seven uniformed officers on the streets. When a seventh officer is available, two members of the force must share a car so both have access to a radio. <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, once a thriving industrial city, became one of the nation's poorest with the decline of the industries and the exodus of whites in the 1960s. Sixty-one percent of the city's 55,000 residents receive some kind of public assistance, and about 40 percent of its citizens are unemployed. Officials say the city's financial problems show no sign of subsiding. It recently reached a $ 4 million settlement with a man seriously beaten by another inmate in the city jail in 1985.
