<HEAD>For Farmers, No More Accounting `Out of Shoebox'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE BIGHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farmers who recently overcame their aversion to computers, now must face another test: accounting. Yes, it's not enough to be computer literate to succeed in agribusiness these days. You'd better understand the numbers you're crunching as well Bankers are telling farmers that accounting `` out of a shoebox'' is no longer good enough to support a loan application. Instead, farmers must provide sophisticated data about their operations and show they understand the figures. `` It makes a banker skittish when someone ca n't answer what we consider basic questions,'' warns <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Scarborough </PERSON>, a vice president with <ORGANIZATION> Sanwa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. `` When I meet a customer who can talk intelligently with me regarding financial plans, how to control that, how to optimize returns and can present this type of information to us, it lends a lot of credibility to the management and general character of the operation.'' <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Esterman </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Fresno-Madera </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Production </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, puts it more simply: `` Farmers have normally operated out of a shoebox, and we're trying to get them out of that mode.'' `` One question is obviously: ` Are you a good farmer?''' says <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, who along with the other bankers participated in a recent seminar on agricultural computing here. But he emphasized that it is not enough to be an expert about all the technical details of farming and have limited understanding of the farm's finances. `` The other aspect of being a good farm manager is being a financial manager as well _ understanding where those numbers come from and what they mean,'' <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> said. What technical data do bankers want before they will consider lending farmers money? <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, professor of farm management and accounting at <ORGANIZATION> Fresno </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, offered this checklist: _ Current business and personal financial statements, including a full accounting of outstanding debts _ Three years' worth of tax returns _ A cash-flow budget _ Details of proposed programs for cropping and marketing, along with a three - to five-year history of crop _ Land locations, maps and lease arrangements _ A list of trade suppliers and credit agreements _ A complete equipment list, including descriptions, ages and serial numbers _ Partnership or corporate organization details _ Insurance coverage `` The day when a farmer can just be a farmer and let his banker be concerned about the financial aspects of his business is past,'' <PERSON> Esterman </PERSON> said. `` The farmer who can relay his financial message in a way we understand and he also understands, with help from a computer, is the type we are looking for _ not the kind who comes in with bills in his back pocket,'' he added <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> said that when he began in banking a decade ago, `` I remember sitting down with customers at the kitchen table and helping customers prepare an application statement. We've gotten away from that.'' Lenders often are unwilling to start with the farmer's own raw financial figures, the bankers warned. They want information that has been spot-checked by a certified public accountant for accuracy or even audited as a more complete assurance of accuracy. That requires consistency and use of generally accepted accounting principles, which were not widely followed on the farm until about three or four years ago, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said computers can help provide the more sophisticated bookkeeping required on farms today. But <PERSON> Esterman </PERSON> cautioned that merely switching to computer bookkeeping will do little good `` if you are not in the habit of keeping good records, whether in a notebook or otherwise.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday May 12</NOTE>
