<HEAD>Farm Credit System Reports $165 Million Quarterly Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Farm Credit System has posted its third consecutive quarterly profit, a $ 165 million net in its first fiscal quarter that reversed its loss of $ 155 million a year earlier. The profit reported Tuesday was due entirely to a $ 160 million reduction in the reserve for loan losses and a $ 10 million net gain on other property owned. The system's net interest income of $ 146 million _ the difference between interest income and interest expense _ fell short of its other expenses of $ 151 million. A year earlier, the system had net interest income of $ 149 million, less than the $ 164 million in other expenses. The Farm Credit System has been able to reduce its loan-loss reserves because borrowers are considered better able to repay their loans. `` The improvement in the agricultural economy experienced in the latter half of 1987 continued into the first quarter of 1988,'' <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fass </PERSON>, president and chief executive of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Funding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said in a news release. <PERSON> Fass </PERSON> announced the Farm Credit System's profit jointly with <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brent </PERSON> <PERSON> Beesley </PERSON>, president and chief executive of the <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>. The Farm Credit System consists of 37 borrower-owned banks and associations serving the rural economy. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> put it on a more secure footing last year by authorizing the issuance of up to $ 4 billion in government-backed, low-interest loans. The 1987 legislation, by increasing confidence in the Farm Credit System, made it possible to narrow the interest-rate spreads on Farm Credit debt obligations over <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities. <PERSON> Fass </PERSON> said the first-quarter net interest income was boosted by special factors, and may be lower in the rest of 1988. The allowance for loan losses as of March 31 was $ 2.744 billion, down from $ 2.951 billion at the end of 1987 and $ 3.532 billion as of March 31, 1987.
