<FIRST>r f PM-ProgramTrading Bjt   05-11 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Program Trading, Bjt,0772</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brokerage Halt of Program Trading: Progress or Public Relations
Ploy?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Program Trading-Glance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A broad move by five big brokers to limit computerized stock trading has won enthusiastic endorsement from critics who claim the strategy has caused unwarranted price convulsions and alienated many investors. But some question the effectiveness of the halt on index arbitrage program trading, because four of the firms will continug using the strategy for their clients' investments. <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday announced limitations on program trading for their own accounts only, while <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said it had imposed a total suspension. The moves marked the most aggressive voluntary steps yet to calm an outcry over the strategy, which has been blamed for destructive volatility in the stock market before and since the October crash. `` It is necessary for all to work toward the goal of restoring confidence in and guaranteeing the vibrancy of the marketplace,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Gutfreund </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive of <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION>, said in a statement that also reflected a view expressed by the other firms. `` Any action taken by member firms to tone volatility and increase investor confidence should be applauded,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Torrenzano </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, which also has taken steps to limit program trading. `` I think it's meaningful and a step in the right direction.'' Wall Street sources said the firms have been under enormous pressure from stock exchanges, customers, lawmakers, and even their own salespeople, for coordinated action to control the computerized practice, which involves the massive purchase and sale of stock index futures and the underlying stocks on which they are based. Although their action wo n't mean an end to program trading, some traders said it should help limit the volatility because the brokerages had used the technique much more frequently than their customers did. `` We welcome their decision, of course,'' said <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> LaCroix </PERSON>, chairman, president and chief executive of <ORGANIZATION> Advest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, Conn.-based securities firm that has urged tough restrictions on program trading. `` We think it's a right one for the capital markets in the long run, and will encourage individuals to come back to the market.'' Nevertheless, experts say proprietary program trading by these brokerages has accounted for only about 20 percent of the total volume of trades attributed to the strategy. Some critics said this leaves plenty of room for more uncertainty. `` Liquidity in our financial markets has dried up, and this may be the first sight of rain we've seen in a long time,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., chairman of the finance subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> in reaction to the suspensions `` However, with customers still in the index arbitrage business, the question remains if intra-day volatility will increase or decrease.'' Capital Guardian Trust Co.. Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirby </PERSON>, a member of the presidential panel that investigated the stock crash, said the big brokers probably had determined that bad publicity over the technique did n't outweigh the profits they derived from it `` These guys decided that life's too short,'' <PERSON> Kirby </PERSON> said. `` I think they get the blame for all the volatility in the marketplace, but all the volatility is going to go on, because of their customers.'' Most index arbitrage program trading is done on behalf of institutional clients, such as pension funds and banks, who see the strategy as one of the few moneymakers in a market that has languished since the October crash. At the same time, program trading has frightened billions of investor dollars out of the market because it can swing prices violently without regard to a stock's real value. The result has been a severe drop in trading volume and stock underwritings. Some said the actions Tuesday reflected a growing belief in the securities industry that lawmakers would take steps aimed at restoring investor confidence unless brokerage firms could reform themselves. `` What's really developed is a tremendous fear by the Wall Street commmunity that legislators may take significant action that might be an over-reaction,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbanel </PERSON>, a futures expert at the <ORGANIZATION> Gruntal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> investment firm in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> had previously announced suspensions of index arbitrage program trading for their own accounts. But only <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION>'s was considered significant because the firm was among the biggest users of the technique.
</TEXT>
