<DOCNO> AP880511-0303 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 0301EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ProgramTrading-Glance     05-11 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Program Trading-Glance,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Program Trading, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Program trading is a catch-all term for a range of computerized trading strategies that most often refers to index arbitrage, which involves the rapid purchase and sale of stocks and stock-index futures. In this strategy, traders attempt to profit on discrepancies between the price of the actual stocks traded in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and the value of indexes based on them, such as the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500, traded in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. When the stocks trade at a significant discount to the index futures, traders sell the futures and buy the stocks. Conversely, when the index futures sell at a big enough discount from the underlying stocks, traders sell the stocks and buy the index futures. The speed at which these transactions are executed is crucial to the program trading strategy because the price discrepancies between stocks and stock-index futures are temporary during the course of a trading session. Big brokerages use powerful computer programs that track these discrepancies and instantly set off buy or sell programs when conditions are deemed profitable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880511-0304 </DOCNO>
