<HEAD>Chrysler union withdrawing suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Local </ORGANIZATION> 72 is withdrawing a suit seeking to prevent <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and the city of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> from using federal money to move subcompact car production from <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, the local's bargaining chief said. `` We're going to drop that one,'' <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuzel </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` They -LRB- company negotiators -RRB- asked for that because of some of the economics they were compelled to give us. The lawsuit was a bargaining chip.'' The union lawsuit filed in February charged that <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> were illegally using a federal grant to remodel <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> plant for work it planned to move this July from <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> since has announced it will build the subcompact cars in <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> until the end of the year, when it will stop all auto assembly and stamping operations at <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kuzel </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> agreed to increased pension and other monetary benefits for about 6,500 hourly workers and 8,000 retirees because it did not want to risk $ 50 million in federal money it would have lost had the union suit in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> been successful. The contract, which is to cover about 5,500 workers <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> intends to lay off or retire at the end of the year, and about 900 hourly workers it will retain in its engine division, gives workers severance and retirement options. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> also has promised to keep the engine division at <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> open for four years from Sept. 15, when the local contract becomes effective. The portion of the contract that governs those who will be laid off is a two-year agreement, <PERSON> Kuzel </PERSON> said in outlining the pact Tuesday for union members who were to vote on it today. The contract proposal calls for return of $ 8,000 to $ 10,000 owed each worker under an employee investment plan used to help then financially-strapped <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Kuzel </PERSON> said workers would get the money back over two years but would not get any interest or bonus payments That would amount to a total of about $ 58 million. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> bought <ORGANIZATION> AMC </ORGANIZATION> last year. <PERSON> Kuzel </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> also added $ 5 million to a $ 15 million job bank fund that will be used to pay full wages to eligible workers as long as the money lasts. The proposal also calls for payments of about $ 100 a week to each laid-off worker under the union's supplemental unemployment benefit fund.
