<HEAD>Spring Hill Wonders What Its Future Holds</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NS1 of May 10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABIGAIL WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRING HILL, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Every morning for the past seven or eight years, a half-dozen men have met for coffee and cigarettes at the oval table in the rear of <LOCATION> Spring </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>'s only restaurant, <ORGANIZATION> Poplar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. The `` Roundtable,'' as the group of contractors and builders is sometimes called, has watched with skepticism as the sleepy Southern town prepares for its transformation into a regional automaking center. <LOCATION> Spring </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, population 1,100, is the home of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s multibillion-dollar <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> plant, which is scheduled to begin producing cars in 1990. But whether the investment is paying adequate dividends for <LOCATION> Spring </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> is a question that still sparks debate over morning coffee here. <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> is located in a kind of never-never land, on 2,450 acres that are not taxed by any county, town or state government and that officially lie in no town. `` It is its own empire,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Brewer </PERSON>, a 68-year-old engineer who has lived in <LOCATION> Spring </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> for 40 years and is an acknowledged leader of the `` Roundtable.'' Brewer thinks <LOCATION> Spring </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> is missing its chances to cash in on the growth <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> will bring to the area once its 3,000 employees begin work. He abhors Mayor <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>' efforts to toughen development laws, which impose impact fees on new building and make it harder for developers to erect fast-food restaurants, convenience stores and the like. One regulation that particularly bothers <PERSON> Brewer </PERSON> is a new ordinance that restricts the size of business signs to 2 feet by 2 feet. Everyone agrees they want to ensure their quality of life, but to <PERSON> Brewer </PERSON>, quality of life includes fast food and the fast development that has been experienced by other Southern boom towns. `` They're not doing anything to encourage people,'' <PERSON> Brewer </PERSON> said of the town's stance toward developers. To the mayor, quality of life comes with controlled growth. For example, he views the erratic building that has occurred around <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> in the past 10 years as incompatible with <PERSON> Spring </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>'s goals If prepared, Spring Hill can avoid the overburdened roads and services that frustrate <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> residents, <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> announced in 1985 that it would build a $ 5 billion plant in <LOCATION> Spring </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> as a joint venture with the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>. The state, anxious to land the plant, promised to build a $ 50 million highway to the town and provide $ 20 million to train workers the plant would need. Almost all the Saturn employees will be <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> members who were laid off in other states by <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>. In return, <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> agreed to make payments in lieu of taxes to <LOCATION> Maury </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, which distributes money to neighboring towns. Land speculation cooled somewhat when <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said it would halve its planned production at the plant to 250,000 cars a year. In fact, more homes were built in 1980, before Saturn arrived, than in 1987. But for every fallow field in Spring Hill there is a realtor's sign advertising its availability, and even the skeptics admit the place is bound to change as the startup date for <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> nears. Within two years, the town will probably be unrecognizable. Developers have begun submitting plans to build tracts of homes for the newcomers. The largest proposal yet, by developer <PERSON> Howell </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pettigrew </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, proposes building about 3,100 multifamily homes and 1,000 single-family homes on 11,000 acres off the <LOCATION> Saturn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Parkway </LOCATION> over a 20-year period. <PERSON> Pettigrew </PERSON> also plans to develop 195 acres for commercial use and 270 acres for industrial use, said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, who is working on the proposal for <PERSON> Pettigrew </PERSON>. `` It's advanced <LOCATION> Spring </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> probably 10 to 20 years already,'' Mayor <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said of <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION>'s effect on the town. The town has advanced, in <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>' view, by increasing its police force from two to seven full-time officers, by building a town hall to grow into and by updating its zoning regulations. The $ 1.2 million town hall, built with money from <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION>, moved out of its one-room trailer -LRB- which was also donated by Saturn -RRB- to a building on a 165-acre complex on a hill off Main Street. Called `` The Town Center at <LOCATION> Spring </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>,'' the development eventually will feature restaurants, stores and multifamily homes. Despite such plans, contractor <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> is among those who believe <LOCATION> Spring </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> is chasing away developers by requiring them to pay impact fees for services. `` The only thing I've ever built in <LOCATION> Spring </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> is my house and that'll probably be the only thing I ever build,'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, like <PERSON> Brewer </PERSON>, believes landowners should be able to do as they please with their land. Farmers `` do n't want people telling them what to do,'' said <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>. Zoning regulations, such as the one governing sign size, discourage prosperity, he said. `` Everybody in the country wants to go to <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> to see those signs, but who in the hell wants to go to Spring Hill?'' Spring Hill resident <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Hickman </PERSON>, an engineer with <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION>, is one who views the slow lurch into the future gladly. `` In the long term, <LOCATION> Spring </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> will be a very attractive place to live because of the strict zoning laws. We're not faced with the tenement type projects,'' he said. `` We may have some lean years in <LOCATION> Spring </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, but in the long run it's going to pay off.''
