<HEAD>Saturn: Top Secret Import Weapon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Saturn-Spring Hill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABIGAIL WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRING HILL, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The manufacturing site for the Saturn car lies between the towns of <LOCATION> Spring </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>, obscured from view by a manmade rolling hillside bordered by a bright white picket fence. After Saturn arrived, both towns annexed land as close to the plant as possible, to take advantage of the housing and commercial development that will follow the completion of a new parkway to the plant. Despite their neighborly proximity, townspeople know little about what goes on inside the compound. <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> officials say the town wanted them to place the plant out of view, while their neighbors occasionally grumble that they are being intentionally shut out. But Saturn is intended to be a mystery, a successful top-secret weapon against import cars. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which funds <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> as a subsidiary rather than a division of the company, expects the plant to turn a profit immediately, said <PERSON> Laurie </PERSON> <PERSON> Kay </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for Saturn. Almost a fourth of the plant has been completed since construction began in June 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> plans to offer a family of <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> cars _ subcompact and compacts _ in 1990 for the 1991 model year, Ms. <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> said. State legislators who visited the sprawling site in March viewed the half-completed powertrain building where car engines and transmissions will be built. Construction also has begun on three other buildings where cars will be assembled and painted before rolling off the line. Part of the plan to make <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> competitive with imports involves approaching production work differently, and <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> officials _ along with their partners in the venture, representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> union _ are adopting management techniques developed by the Japanese, said Ms. <PERSON> Kay </PERSON>. Employees will be involved in all aspects of production, from understanding the cost of supplies to sales, she said. They will be on salaries rather than the traditional hourly wage rates, with 20 percent of their pay based on the performance of the company, Ms. <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> said. Saturn jobs will first be offered to the estimated 300,000 <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> members who have been laid off around the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>, said Ms. <PERSON> Kay </PERSON>. About 6,000 people have applied for the 3,000 jobs that are to be filled by mid-1989. The plant is designed to produce 250,000 cars a year initially. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> plans to increase production, depending on the auto's reception by car buyers. <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> has begun reviewing about 1,700 applications for a network of dealerships, which are expected to reach 123 cities by the end of the first model year. <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> has sent employees to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to study Japanese automaking procedures, as well as to <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, said Ms. <PERSON> Kay </PERSON>. `` We're looking very hard at everything. We're not inventing everything,'' she said. `` We are taking a fresh look at what we do.''
