<HEAD>Soybeans Open Sharply Higher; Grains Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soybean futures prices opened sharply higher today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> in reaction to the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s latest supply-and-demand estimates. Grain futures were mixed. The soybean market's early gains of as much as 9 -LCB- cents a bushel were expected after the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> revised downward its estimate of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soybean stockpile, predicting stocks would dwindle from 275 million bushels on this Aug. 31 to 145 million bushels a year later. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> also reduced its estimate for this year's Brazilian soybean harvest to 17.6 million metric tons from 18 million metric tons. `` This adds to the general feeling or perception that soybean stocks are shrinking very quickly,'' said <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Spilka </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> report, issued Tuesday afternoon, was considered neutral for corn futures, which opened slightly higher, and was construed as somewhat bearish for wheat. The government predicted this year's winter wheat harvest would be about 4 percent larger than last year's and that prediction weighed on wheat futures this morning, <PERSON> Spilka </PERSON> said. In early trading, wheat was 1 -RCB- cents to 2 \ cents lower with the contract for delivery in May at $ 3.01 -LCB- a bushel; corn was \ cent to 1 cent higher with May at $ 1.99 -RCB- a bushel; oats were \ cent lower to \ cent higher with May at $ 1.62 a bushel; soybeans were 6 -LCB- cents