<HEAD>Regan Calls on Congress to Ban Index Arbitrage Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Program Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS 6 grafs with comments by futures exchange officials;
also running on general news wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> called on <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> today to ban index arbitrage trading, saying the computer-driven transactions are undermining public confidence in the stock market. `` I do n't think it's too extreme to say that overall confidence in our free market system is threatened by this sort of scandal,'' <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` And that's what it is _ a scandal.'' <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>, former chief executive of <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, has been the focus of attention recently for a book he has written on his years as <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> chief of staff under President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. Most attention has been drawn to his revelation that First Lady <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> regularly consulted an astrologer about the president's schedule. Before <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> spoke, Sen. <PERSON> Alfonse </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, read <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>'s horoscope to him, which said that he could not `` force colleagues to be more understanding'' until May 17 <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> did not respond, but said later that his testimony `` comes at an interesting time in terms of my own personal activities.'' <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> said that program trading is `` fundamentally changing and endangering the basis on which our economy and stock market have functioned for generations.'' He said that although individuals still own most stocks, institutions in recent years have dominated trading. `` If the public feels that the markets are rigged, not only in favor of the big guy, but also in favor of some unidentified computer-based trading strategy, then confidence in our markets, indeed in our system, will plummet,'' <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> called on the nation's financial markets and the federal agencies that regulate them to impose their own restrictions on program trading. In index arbitrage, traders use computers to profit from price discrepancies between the stock and futures markets by simultaneously buying in one market and selling in the other. At the same hearing, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwab </PERSON>, who heads his own discount brokerage firm, said program trading should be totally abolished. `` The individual investor in this country is angry,'' <PERSON> Schwab </PERSON> said. `` Most of all, he is angry about <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s failure to enact reforms needed to promote greater stability in the securities markets.'' <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Schwab </PERSON>'s comments came a day after five big Wall Street firms announced they have halted index arbitrage trading for their own accounts as a means of restoring investor confidence in the stock market. However, <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Melamed </PERSON>, chairman of the executive committee of the board of governors of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, defended index arbitrage today at a breakfast meeting with reporters in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. He acknowledged that some individual investors believe program trading destabilizes the market, but he maintained that index arbitrage does just the opposite because it ensurse that stock and futures prices closely track each other. `` I'm not going to defend perception,'' he said. `` The reality is it is not a factor -LRB- in the volatility -RRB-. Index arbitrage was and is a stabilizing factor.'' `` I do n't believe there's many individual investors who understand the issue,'' he added. The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trades the most popular futures contract, which is based on the Standard and Poor's 500.
</TEXT>
