<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 F.W. <ORGANIZATION> Woolworth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Wal-Mart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, two bright spots in a mostly dismal first quarter for the retailing industry, on Wednesday reported robust increases in their earnings for the period. <ORGANIZATION> Woolworth </ORGANIZATION> said its net income for the three months ended April 30 totaled $ 35 million, or 54 cents per share, up nearly 21 percent from $ 29 million, or 43 cents per share, in the first three months of fiscal 1987. Sales rose to $ 1.71 billion from $ 1.53 billion. The first quarter of the retail fiscal year was a disappointment for many storeowners as consumers continued to spend cautiously. <ORGANIZATION> Woolworth </ORGANIZATION>'s sales dipped more than 5 percent in April, but the company fared better than most of the other big retailers in the first two months of the year. <ORGANIZATION> Wal-Mart </ORGANIZATION> saw no letdown in its business during the quarter. The rapidly-expanding discount chain reported earnings of $ 153.6 million, or 27 cents a share, up nearly 40 percent from $ 110.4 million, or 19 cents a share, in the first quarter of 1987. Sales totaled $ 4.28 billion, up from $ 3.21 billion. <ORGANIZATION> Woolworth </ORGANIZATION> is believed to be a possible takeover target for <ORGANIZATION> Dart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which recently asked for federal permission to acquire up to 15 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Woolworth </ORGANIZATION> stock. <PERSON> Dart </PERSON> has not yet made a bid for <ORGANIZATION> Woolworth </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Woolworth </ORGANIZATION> operates <ORGANIZATION> Woolworth </ORGANIZATION> general merchandise stores and specialty retailers including <ORGANIZATION> Kinney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shoe </ORGANIZATION>, Foot Locker and Lady Foot Locker. <ORGANIZATION> Wal-