<HEAD>Small Companies Outperformed Big Business, Study Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Companies with fewer than 100 workers increased employment at a faster rate than large businesses during the latter half of 1987, but the number of new small firms decreased sharply during the period, according to a study released Wednesday. Employment among small companies rose by 1.9 percent during the last six months of 1987, compared with an increase of 0.6 percent for larger businesses, a study by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Small </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partnership </ORGANIZATION> showed. The partnership charts small business growth based on data from 7 million companies with fewer than 100 employees. During the latter half of 1987, new small business incorporations plunged 7.71 percent. Sales of small business goods and services increased by 1.06 percent during the period, compared with an increase of 0.13 percent for their larger counterparts. The rate is down, however, from the 1.27 percent increase in sales small businesses reported during the first half of 1987. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Birch </PERSON>, who heads the small business partnership, noted that small businesses `` held up well during this uncertain economic period.'' He noted that the first half of 1987 was `` a period of uncharacteristically high levels of new business start-ups,'' and therefore any decline in the latter half `` should be considered in context.'' Small businesses in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> states posted the greatest growth, with employment up 2.26 percent and sales up 1.52 percent. Those in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> region had the highest gain in employment, which rose 2.31 percent, and a 1.25 percent increase in sales.
