<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices dropped on Wall Street today, as anxiety about the prospect for higher interest rates was heightened by a rise in the prime lending rate by two major banks. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 44.27 points at 1,959.38 at 2 p.m. EDT, widened from its losses earlier in the session. The broader market also showed deep declines. Losing stocks outstripped advancers by about 7-to-1 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, with 1,375 issues losing, only 200 gaining and 336 unchanged. Volume on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> was 138.82 million shares. <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> boosted their prime rates by a half percentage point to 9 percent. They were the first increases in the prime since just before October's stock market collapse. <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> was the first big bank to raise the key rate, which is watched closely because bankers use it as a base rate for loans to many businesses and for consumer loans, including mortgages. Chase's move was announced around noon today after Wall Street had already sustained sharp losses on interest-rate fears. `` It tends to reduce confidence in the stock market,'' said <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, senior vice president of <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Albany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, referring to the increase in the prime rate. Higher interest rates, by raising the cost of borrowing, tend to dampen companies' expansion plans and investments. The hike in the prime came against a background of growing edginess about the outlook for interest rates. British Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> indicated earlier today that there could be an internationally coordinated boost in rates. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>, who made the comments in an interview with the <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>'s overseas editions that was published today, noted that a coordinated effort by <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and other leading nations to hike interest rates `` is certainly possible'' following the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s increase in short-term rates to curb <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inflation. Separately, <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> economist <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON> confirmed that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has nudged up short-term rates in recent weeks. He defended the move as making sense in the face of a strong economy and recent growth in the money supply. Some observers and market players expect the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> to raise its key discount rate, the interest it charges big financial institutions, possibly this week. The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>'s composite index was down 2.59 at 143.16. At the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the market value index had dropped 4.72 to 295.09.
