<FIRST>r f AM-ConsumerConfidence     05-11 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Consumer Confidence,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Confidence Bounced Back In April, Survey Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumers' confidence rebounded in April, suggesting consumer spending will remain strong in coming months, the <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. The business research organization said its index of consumer confidence rose to 114.6 in April from 112.7 in March, leaving it just below its level of 114.9 in February. The index peaked at 115.7 in September, the month before the stock market crash. That was its highest level in 15 years. The index, based on a monthly survey of 5,000 households, is considered an important indicator for the economy because consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of the gross national product. Consumers have been spending cautiously in recent months, and analysts have attributed their hesitance in part to concerns about the economy. The base year for the consumer confidence index was 1985, when it was at 100. Its margin of error is plus or minus 2 or 2.5 points, meaning the change from March to April is near the limit of the margin of error.
</TEXT>
