<HEAD>Sale of 37 Hospitals in 10 States Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> will sell 37 hospitals in 10 states to an employee group in a transaction valued at $ 910 million, the company said Wednesday. The announcement follows sale of 15 hospitals and layoffs of 2,000 workers in the last 18 months in an attempt to boost earnings at the hospital company. It considerably exceeds Chairman <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weisman </PERSON>'s prediction after the company's annual meeting in January that between five and 20 hospitals would be sold in the next three years. American Medical said the acute-care hospitals, which among them have 4,200 beds, would be sold to a new company owned primarily by an employees' stock ownership plan to be established at the new company. The new company will be headed by <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> George </PERSON>, present director of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> region, and will have headquarters in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, the company said. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> will retain an interest through an issue of preferred stock in the new entity, which has not yet been named, said <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Mick </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> is seeking bank loans to finance the planned $ 600 million cash portion of the sale, <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said. The rest of the transaction would bring <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> $ 310 million in preferred stock in the new company, assumed debt and notes, the company said. The proceeds, estimated at $ 450 million after taxes and expenses, will be used to pay off debt and buy back stock. The company retains 48 hospitals and five psychiatric hospitals in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and 22 hospitals and three psyciatric hospitals overseas. `` This sale will allow <ORGANIZATION> AMI </ORGANIZATION> to focus singularly on improving the earnings per share generated by our remaining asset base,'' <PERSON> Weisman </PERSON> said. The hospitals to be sold are in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. Those hospitals had combined net revenue of $ 507 million in 1987. American Medical, which in March reported second-quarter profit fell 13.9 percent to $ 24.1 million, is under pressure from the holder of 5 percent of its stock to sell marginal operations. For the first half of its fiscal year, profit rose 11.8 percent, to $ 63.3 million, over the year earlier.
