<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0390</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices dropped on Wall Street today, as several major banks raised their prime lending rates and confirmed investors' fears about higher interest rates. About a dozen big <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks boosted their prime rates by a half percentage point to 9 percent _ the first increase in the prime since just before October's stock market collapse. Market analysts point out that hauntingly similar jitters about rising interest rates were a big factor behind the Oct. 19 crash, and those memories are still fresh in the minds of nervous investors. `` The major problem with the stock market has been the rise in rates,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wachtel </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> was the first big bank to raise the key rate, which is watched closely because bankers use it as a base rate for loans to many businesses and for consumer loans, including mortgages Chase's move was announced around noon today after Wall Street had already sustained sharp losses on interest-rate fears. `` It tends to reduce confidence in the stock market,'' said <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, senior vice president of <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Albany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, referring to the increase in the prime rate. The hike in the prime came against a background of growing edginess about the outlook for interest rates. British Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> indicated earlier today that there could be an internationally coordinated boost in rates. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>, who made the comments in an interview with the <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>'s overseas editions that was published today, noted that a coordinated effort by <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and other leading nations to hike interest rates `` is certainly possible'' following the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s increase in short-term rates to curb <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inflation. Separately, <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> economist <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON> confirmed that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has nudged up short-term rates in recent weeks. He defended the move as making sense in the face of a strong economy and recent growth in the money supply. Some observers and market players expect the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> to raise its key discount rate, the interest it charges big financial institutions, possibly this week. Higher interest rates, by raising the cost of borrowing, tend to dampen companies' expansion plans and investments.
