<FIRST>u f AM-NewFuturesContract     05-11 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Futures Contract,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>CFTC Approves New Stock Index Futures Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday approved a new stock index futures contract for the first time since the October stock market crash. The commission voted unanimously to permit the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> to trade contracts based on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Options </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> 250 Stock Index and the <ORGANIZATION> CBOE </ORGANIZATION> 50 Stock Index. The action came only a day after five big Wall Street firms announced that customer concerns about stock market volatility had prompted them to stop for their own accounts a form of futures trading known as index arbitrage. In index arbitrage, pension funds, mutual funds and other institutional investors use computers to profit from momentary price discrepancies between the stock and futures markets by simultaneously buying in one market and selling in the other. The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which governs the stock market, has blamed index arbitrage for accelerating the Oct. 19 stock crash and for the continuing vulnerability of the market to wild price swings. Former Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday stock index trading should be suspended. However, <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON>, chairwoman of the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION>, defended futures index trading as `` important and beneficial ... -LRB- to -RRB- our economic and financial system.'' Commission member <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION>'s approval of the contracts Wednesday `` will illustrate that, while the events of last October raise important policy issues, we are not prepared to let competing market factions use government regulatory authority to provide special status and competitive position to any faction, to the detriment of the broader public interest.'' The <ORGANIZATION> CBOE </ORGANIZATION> 50 and <ORGANIZATION> CBOE </ORGANIZATION> 250 are weighted indexes based on the largest 50 and largest 250 stocks traded on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. A rival to the CBOT, the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, trades futures contracts based on the largest 100 and largest 500 stocks on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>. Stock index futures allow an investor to buy a group of stocks and to hedge the risk by purchasing offsetting futures contracts. `` The improvement in risk management afforded by the trading of stock index contracts rebounds to the interest of millions of small investors who rely on institutions to manage their savings,'' Ms. <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON> said in a statement. She said the fears of some individual investors have made futures trading `` a perceptual issue.'' But, she said, `` The way to address it is through education of the public ... not by blocking innovative products that can improve market efficiency.''
</TEXT>
