<HEAD>Gulf &amp; Western Announces New Stock Buyback</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a major entertainment, publishing and financial services company, announced another stock buyback program Wednesday, its third in five years. The company said its board authorized the purchase of up to 10 million shares of its common stock in the open market. The plan, designed to bolster the value of the shares that will remain on the market, follows the completion of a 24 million-share buyback adopted in 1985. The latest repurchase plan included 5.2 million shares snapped up in the wake of last October's stock market crash, when scores of companies bought back their own shares to help stave off further price declines. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer, said the buybacks had enhanced shareholder value `` by giving each shareholder increased ownership of the company.'' Since the initial buyback was launched in 1983, about 44 million shares have been repurchased at an average price of slightly over $ 21 a share, the company said. <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Western said it had about 118 million shares of common stock outstanding after adjustment for a 2-for-1 stock split on May 2. Analysts said <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Western shares traded strongly on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in reaction to the announcement, but were dragged down 37 -LCB- cents to $ 37 by the market's broad decline. The Dow Jones industrial average dropped nearly 38 points to 1,965.85. The company's stock is up significantly from its 52-week low of $ 29.75 a share, and analysts credit management for keeping a high priority on shareholder interests. The buyback announcement follows the company's failed attempt to acquire <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a children's book publisher and commercial printer. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Manson </PERSON> of the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Donaldson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lufkin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jenrette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> said the company's cash flow was strong enough to accomplish both the buyback and the acquisition. `` It has strong momentum in its entertainment business, stability in financial services and a mass of cash,'' said <PERSON> Manson </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Western's publishing holdings include <ORGANIZATION> Simon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Shuster </PERSON>, which publishes books for mass circulation, and Prentice-Hall, an educational and professional publisher. Its entertainment segment includes <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION>.
