<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0539</SECOND>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices dropped sharply Wednesday in edgy trading, weakened by fears of higher interest rates that pushed the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average to a three-month low. The key index of 30 premier stocks slid 37.80 points to 1,965.85, its lowest closing level since it closed at 1,961.54 on Feb. 11. Most of the slippage occurred early in the session. Losing issues outstripped gainers by about 7-to-1 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, with 1,363 issues declining, 238 advancing and 367 unchanged. <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> volume totaled 176.72 million shares, up from 131.2 million Tuesday. Wall Street's fear of higher interest rates were aggravated by an announcement from big banks that they had raised their key prime lending rate from 8.5 percent to 9 percent, the first rise since the October crash. Hauntingly similar jitters about rising interest rates were a big factor behind the crash _ and those memories are still fresh in the minds of nervous investors. In addition, higher interest rates, by raising the cost of borrowing, tend to dampen companies' expansion plans and investments. `` The major problem with the stock market has been the rise in rates,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wachtel </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> was the first big bank to raise the key rate, which is watched closely because bankers use it as a base rate for loans to many businesses and for consumer loans, including some types of mortgages `` It clearly hit a raw nerve ... this market was clearly vulnerable,'' said <PERSON> Monte </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>, vice president and director of research for <ORGANIZATION> Dreyfus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The hike in the prime came against a background of growing edginess about the outlook for interest rates. British Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> reportedly suggested that there could be an internationally coordinated boost in rates. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>, who was quoted in an interview with the <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>'s overseas edition Wednesday, noted that a coordinated effort by <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and other leading nations to hike interest rates `` is certainly possible'' following the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s increase in short-term rates to curb <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inflation. Separately, <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> economist <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON> confirmed that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has nudged up short-term rates in recent weeks. Among actively traded issues on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Con </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION> fell -LCB- to 42, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> lost -RCB- at 38 -RCB-, <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> was down \ at 26 ~, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> dropped 2 -LRB- to 108 -RCB-, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> declined -RRB- to 50 -LRB-, <ORGANIZATION> Woolworth </ORGANIZATION> tumbled 1 \ to 52 -RCB-, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION>