<HEAD>World Markets React To Lawson Comments</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs with Journal statement; picks up 6th graf,
``The remarks ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 British Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>'s comments that there could be an internationally coordinated boost in interest rates sent a rush of worry through world securities markets Wednesday. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>, who made the comments in an interview with the <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>'s overseas editions, noted that a coordinated effort by <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and other leading nations to hike interest rates `` is certainly possible'' following the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s increase in short-term rates to curb <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inflation The Journal later issued a statement saying it had not fully reported <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>'s comments. Separately, <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> economist <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON> confirmed that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> has nudged up short-term rates in recent weeks. He defended the move as making sense in the face of a strong economy and recent growth in the money supply. In reports published Wednesday in overseas editions of the Wall Street Journal, <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> noted, `` We did have very close coordination in the immediate aftermath'' of October's stock market collapse. The Journal said later in a statement it had failed to fully report <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>'s remarks. `` In an interview, <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> was asked if there is a possibility that governments may act in a coordinated way to raise rates in the near future, as they have done to lower rates in the past. He replied in part, ` That is certainly possible ...', `` the statement said. `` However, the article failed to note that in response to a follow-up question about the chances of coordinated interest rate rises in the near future, <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> would only state, ` What I am saying is that we do keep very closely in touch with each other. I would n't go further than that' In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the Journal report sent stock prices tumbling. The key 225-share Nikkei Index fell 251.20 points, or 0.92 percent, to close at 27,161.05. `` The remarks by <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> came at a bad time, with the market already worried about the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> refunding,'' said a trader in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, referring to the quarterly sale of $ 26 billion in notes and bonds. The three-day sale ends Thursday. Share prices also headed lower in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>. Prices on many bond markets also moved lower in response to the comments by both <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON>, sending interest rates higher. Traders said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> treasuries, British, West German and Japanese government issues all fell after the reports circulated. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the bellwether 30-year issue eased slightly in the early going. Bond prices move in the opposite direction as interest rates. Several central banks refused to comment on the <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> remarks. Any action by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> to increase interest rates would affect the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar, <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> noted. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> have resisted boosting their interest rates ahead of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rate hike for fear of weakening the dollar. In his interview with the <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> also dismissed market concern that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would resume a hands-off approach to the dollar after the upcoming presidential election and allow the dollar to fall again. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> predicted the group of seven major industrialized nations would maintain their commitment to stabilize the dollar. Currency traders in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> dismissed <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>'s comments, and the dollar continued to move in narrow, directionless activity.
</TEXT>
