 <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday signed a lease for three floors of <ORGANIZATION> Bethlehem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s headquarters, where the railroad holding company plans to relocate most of its executive offices. <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the holding company of <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION>, will transfer as many as 120 employees from its <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> office to the new <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION> corporate headquarters. Company officials said <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> will still maintain a presence in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, but all executive offices _ including that of President <PERSON> Drew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> _ will relocate to <ORGANIZATION> Martin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION>. The company expects to begin relocation in late July and complete the move in October. The Union Pacific lease represents the first step toward making the building profitable for <LOCATION> Bethelem </LOCATION>. The steelmaker has tried to unsuccessfully sell the building since last year. The tower was built 16 years ago.
