<HEAD>AFL-CIO Ad Campaign Aimed at Updating Union Image</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also moved on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PHYLLIS MESSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday said a new $ 13 million broadcast advertising campaign was designed to show that unions, like their workers, are interested in fairness, justice and life outside the job. The ads, which all end with a chorus singing `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> works best when we say union yes,'' have begun appearing on the television networks and in 13 local markets. The 30-second spots are expected to reach more than nine out of 10 of all American homes at least four times. Radio spots will be aired as well, including one that urges listeners to ask <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to override President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s expected veto of the trade legislation. Unions have been pushing a provision of the bill requiring mandatory notice of plant closings for large companies. At a closed-circuit TV news conference to the 13 cities where the TV ads will be shown, <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> said `` the labor movement has a long, well-documented record of fighting for the rights and the standard of living of working Americans. But in spite of that, there are still many Americans who have serious misconceptions about what unions do and about whether or not they are necessary in today's work place.'' `` The goal of ` Union Yes,''' he said, `` is to talk directly with American workers about the value of unions in the work place today. One of the best ways to do that now is through television.'' <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Bahr </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, told reporters in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that the ads `` fill a need to let the population at large know what the trade union movement stands for.'' He said many Americans have `` a stereotype of unions and union members. They see a heavyset fellow smoking a cigar and wearing a $ 500 suit.'' One commercial focuses on women, with a woman saying unions have ensured fairness in promotions. Another, obviously pregnant, woman says that because of unions she will be able to take time off to have her baby and come back to a job. The first phase of the ad campaign runs through mid-June. The second phase picks up on Labor Day in September. The campaign, which is paid for with union dues, is expected to last two years. The ads will star actors <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Lemmon </PERSON>, <PERSON> Tyne </PERSON> <PERSON> Daly </PERSON> and <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hesseman </PERSON>. Local TV ads will run during May and June in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla </LOCATION>.
